{"title_page": "English county histories", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''English county histories''', in other words historical and topographical (or \"[[Chorography|chorographical]]\") works concerned with individual [[ancient counties of England]], were produced by [[antiquarian]]s from the late 16th century onwards. The content was variable: most focused on recording the ownership of estates and the descent of lordships of [[manor]]s, thus the genealogies of county families, heraldry and other antiquarian material; In the introduction to one typical early work of this style, ''The Antiquities of Warwickshire'' published in 1656, the author [[William Dugdale]] writes:<ref>https://archive.org/details/antiquitiesofwar00dugd/page/n7/mode/2up</ref></br>\n:''I offer unto you my noble countriemen, as the most proper persons to whom it can be presented wherein you will see very much of your worthy ancestors, to whose memory I have erected it as a monumentall pillar and to shew in what honour they lived in those flourishing ages past. In this kind, or not much different, have divers persons in forrein parts very learnedly written; some whereof I have noted in my preface: and I could wish that there were more that would adventure in the like manner for the rest of the counties of this nation, considering how acceptable those are, which others have already performed''.</br>\nThus his work was designed primarily to be read by his fellow county gentry of Warwickshire, whose public lives and marriages were largely confined within their own county of residence, which they administered as Justices of the Peace and Sheriffs, and represented in Parliament. The genealogical and heraldic tradition continues with the series of [[Victoria County History|Victoria County Histories]] commenced in the late 19th century. \n\nOther forms recorded [[archaeological site]]s. A closely related genre, which emerged in the second half of the 17th century, was the county \"Natural History\", which focused on the county's flora, fauna and natural phenomena, but which also often included chapters on antiquities. The best known examples were [[Robert Plot]]'s two volumes on Oxfordshire (1677) and Staffordshire (1686); and [[John Aubrey]]'s unpublished work on Wiltshire.\n\n==Development==\n===Continental models===\nDugdale quotes as his foreign models C\u00e9sar de Nostredame (1553-1629), historian of [[Provence]] in France, author of ''Rerum antiquarum et nobiliorum Provinciae'', written c.1560, published 1615; Ottavio Rossi, historian of [[Brescia]] in Italy, author of ''Memorie Bresciane, Opera Historica, E Simbolica'' (1626);  Guillaume Catel (1560-1626), historian of [[Languedoc]] in France, author of ''M\u00e9moires sur l'histoire du Languedoc'' (1633); [[Samuel Guichenon]] (1607-1664), historian of Bresse in France, author of  ''Histoire de la [[Bresse]] et du [[Bugey]]'' (1650) and [[Antonius Sanderus]] (1586-1664), historian of Flanders, author of ''Flandria Illustrata'' (1641).\n\n===English pioneers===\n[[William Lambarde]]'s ''Perambulation of [[Kent]]'' (completed 1570; published 1576) is generally acknowledged as the first example of the genre in England. It was followed by [[Richard Carew (antiquary)|Richard Carew's]] ''Survey of Cornwall'' (1602), and [[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton's]] ''Description of Leicester Shire'' (1622), as well as a number of other projects (such as those of [[Sir William Pole]], [[Thomas Westcote]], and [[Tristram Risdon]] in Devon, and [[Sampson Erdeswicke]] in Staffordshire) which, although they sometimes circulated in manuscript, did not come to completion or publication. Following the appearance of [[William Dugdale]]'s ''Antiquities of Warwickshire'' (1656), a pattern was set. In the nineteenth century [[John Bowyer Nichols]] followed the line of a history of [[Leicestershire]] compiled by his father [[John Nichols (printer)|John Nichols]], and saw numerous counties histories through the press at his printing firm.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Nichols, John Bowyer}}</ref> The scope of county histories varied, but the titles became quite standard: \"Antiquities of\", \"Worthies of\", \"Geological survey\", \"Description of\", later \"Directory of\", all could indicate the intention of producing a \"history\", a term that only in later times acquired the narrower meaning it carries today. [[Chorography]], [[topography]] and [[toponymy]] might all be involved. Materials and collections for their counties were made by antiquaries, but publication might await sponsorship or enough subscriptions, as well as a capable author who would make a readable book, perhaps of multiple volumes, from notes.\n\n==Listing by county==\n\n===Bedfordshire===\nSee: [[History of Bedfordshire]]; [[:Category: History of Bedfordshire]];\n\n*''[[Magna Britannia]]'' (1806)\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=1&type=1 ''Victoria County History''] three volumes, 1904\u20131912\n\n===Berkshire===\n*[[Elias Ashmole]], ''Antiquities of Berkshire'' (1719)\n* J. Rocque, ''A Topographical Survey of the County of Berkshire'', 1761\n\n===Buckinghamshire===\nSee: [[History of Buckinghamshire]]; [[:Category: History of Buckinghamshire]]; ''Victoria County History'' edited by William Page\n*[[George Lipscomb]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Buckingham'' published in eight parts, 1831\u201347 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiquiti02lips]\n*[[James Joseph Sheahan]], ''History and Topography of Buckinghamshire: comprising a general survey of the county, preceded by an epitome of the early history of Great Britain'' (1862)\n\n===Cambridgeshire===\n*[[Edmund Carter (topographer)|Edmund Carter]], ''History of the County of Cambridge'' (1753)\n\n===Cheshire===\n*[[Sir Peter Leycester, 1st Baronet]], ''Historical antiquities'' (1673)\n*[[Peter Perez Burdett]], ''Survey of the County Palatine of Chester'' (1772)\n*[[George Ormerod]], ''The History of the County Palatine and City of Chester'' (1816\u201319)\n\n===Cornwall===\n*[[Richard Carew (antiquary)|Richard Carew]], ''The Survey of Cornwall'' (1602)\n*[[William Hals]], ''Compleat History of Cornwall'', from about 1750<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=12027|title=Hals, William|first=Jan|last=Broadway}}</ref>\n*An historical survey of the county of Cornwall, etc., compiled by William Penaluna\n*[[Richard Polwhele]], ''The History of Cornwall'' (7 vols. 1803\u201308, revised 1816)\n*[[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Daniel Lysons]] and [[Samuel Lysons]], ''[[Magna Britannia]]''\n\nThe Cornwall history was supported by [[Francis Vyvyan Jago Arundell]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=715|title=Arundell, Francis Vyvyan Jago|first=Christine|last=North}}</ref>\n\n*[[Charles Sandoe Gilbert]], ''Historical Survey of the County of Cornwall'' (2 vols., 1817\u201320)<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=10683|title=Gilbert, Charles Sandoe|first=Elizabeth|last=Baigent}}</ref>\n*[[Fortescue Hitchins]] and [[Samuel Drew]], ''The History of Cornwall'' (1824)\n\n===Cumberland and Westmorland===\n*[[Richard Burn]] and Joseph Nicolson, ''The History and Antiquities of the Counties of Westmorland and Cumberland'', 1777.\n\nThis goes back to the manuscript ''Accompt of the most considerable estates and families in the county of Cumberland'' of about 1603 by John Denton.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=74666|title=Denton, John|first1=Mary|last1=Wane|first2=Angus J. L.|last2=Winchester}}</ref> Through copies made by [[Daniel Fleming (antiquary)|Daniel Fleming]], it used material collected by [[Christopher Rawlinson (antiquary)|Christopher Rawlinson]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Rawlinson, Christopher (1677-1733)}}</ref> Joseph Nicolson (born 1706, baptised William \u2013 1777), son of John Nicolson of Hawkesdale, was a nephew of Bishop [[William Nicolson]], and inherited from him collections relating to Carlisle.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Burke|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry; Or, Commoners of Great Britain and Ireland Etc. - London, Henry Colburn 1837-1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vhpVAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA396|year=1838|publisher=Henry Colburn|page=396 note}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/transactionvol11no2cumb#page/240/mode/2up|title=Transactions of the Cumberland & Westmorland Antiquarian & Archaeological Society|work=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=T. Wilson|pages=240 note|volume=XI|accessdate=26 December 2015|location=Highgate, Kendal}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalmers1815\">{{cite book|author=Alexander Chalmers|title=The General biographical dictionary|url=https://archive.org/details/generalbiograph31chalgoog|year=1815|publisher=Printed for J. Nichols|page=[https://archive.org/details/generalbiograph31chalgoog/page/n137 187]}}</ref><ref>http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2055-1/dissemination/pdf/Article_Level_Pdf/tcwaas/001/1884/vol7/tcwaas_001_1884_vol7_0018.pdf</ref> Burn and Nicolson used in particular material collected by [[Thomas Machell]], vicar of [[Kirkby Thore]], and collated by William Nicolson.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=61544|first=Angus J. L.|last=Winchester|title=Machell, Thomas}}</ref>\n\n*[[William Hutchinson (topographer)|William Hutchinson]], ''History of the County of Cumberland'' (1794).\n\n===Derbyshire===\n*[[Stephen Glover (antiquary)|Stephen Glover]], ''Directory of the County of Derby'' (1827\u201329); and ''History of the County of Derby'' (1829\u201331)\n\nGlover made use of, and expanded, an unpublished history by William Woolley.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=10834|title=Glover, Stephen|first=Margaret|last=O'Sullivan}}</ref>\n\n*Samuel Bagshaw, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of Derbyshire'' (1846)\n*[[White's Directories|White]], ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Derby'' (1857)\n\n===Devon===\n*Sir [[William Pole (antiquary)|William Pole]] (d.1635), ''Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon'', notes made (''c''.1608\u20131617), published by [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791 \n*[[Thomas Westcote]], ''Survey of Devon'' of 1630\n*[[Tristram Risdon]], ''Chorographical Description or Survey of the County of Devon'' (c. 1632)\n*[[Richard Polwhele]], ''The History of Devonshire'' (1793\u20131806)\n\n[[John Swete]] supplied material to Polwhele.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=26827|title=Swete, John|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref>\n\n*[[William White (Sheffield, England)|William White]], ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Devon: including the city of Exeter, and comprising a general survey of the county''\n\n===Dorset===\n*[[John Hutchins (historian)|John Hutchins]], ''History and Antiquities of Dorset'' (1774)\n*John Hutchins, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Dorset'', Vols. 1\u20134, 1815.\n\n===Durham===\n*[[William Hutchinson (topographer)|William Hutchinson]], ''History and Antiquities of the Country Palatine of Durham''\n*[[Robert Surtees (antiquarian)|Robert Surtees]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County Palatine of Durham''\n\nBoth Hutchinson and Surtees drew on the work of [[George Allan (antiquary)|George Allan]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=355|title=Allan, George|first=C. M.|last=Fraser}}</ref> [[John Brewster (author)|John Brewster]] assisted Surtees.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=3373|title=Brewster, John|first=R. H.|last=Sweet}}</ref>\n\n*[[James Raine]], ''The History and Antiquities of North-Durham'', 1852\n*William Fordyce, ''The History and Antiquities of the County Palatine of Durham''\n*Whellan, ''History, Topography, and Directory of the County Palatine of Durham'' (1856)\n\n===Essex===\n*[[Philip Morant]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Essex'', two volumes 1763\u20131768\n\nMorant used collections of [[Thomas Jekyll]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=14711|title=Jekyll, Thomas|first=J. S.|last=Reynolds}}</ref> and also material from [[Richard Symonds (diarist)|Richard Symonds]] he obtained via [[Gregory King]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=26890|title=Symonds, Richard|first=Ian|last=Roy}}</ref> A major source was the parish descriptions of [[William Holman (antiquary)|William Holman]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=13581|title=Holman, William|first=W. Raymond|last=Powell}}</ref> These had been acquired by [[Nicholas Tindal]], for whom Morant worked as a curate; Tindal made a small start on publishing Essex history, around 1732.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Tindal, Nicholas (1687-1774)}}</ref> They then passed via Nathaniel Salmon, [[Anthony Allen (antiquary)|Anthony Allen]] and John Booth, before Morant had them from Booth about 1750.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=19159|title=Morant, Philip|first=G. H.|last=Martin}}</ref>\n\n*''A New and Complete History of Essex, from a late survey'' (1772)\n*[[Elizabeth Ogborne]], ''The History of Essex'' (1817, one volume only)\n\n[[Thomas Leman]] and probably [[Joseph Strutt (engraver and antiquary)|Joseph Strutt]] assisted.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=20577|title=Ogborne, Elizabeth|first=Rosemary|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n*William White, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Essex'', 1848\n\n===Gloucestershire===\n*[[Robert Atkyns (topographer)|Sir Robert Atkyns]], ''The Ancient and Present State of Glostershire'' (1712)\n*[[Samuel Rudder]], ''A New History of Gloucestershire'' (1779)\n\nRudder's work was based on Atkyns and a manuscript of [[Richard Furney]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=24248|title=Rudder, Samuel|first=Nicholas|last=Herbert}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ralph Bigland]], ''Historical, Monumental & Genealogical Collections relative to the County of Gloucester'' (1791\u201394)\n*[[Thomas Rudge]], ''The History of the County of Gloucester, compressed and brought down to the year 1803'' (1803)\n*[[Thomas Dudley Fosbroke]], ''Abstracts of Records and Manuscripts Respecting the County of Gloucester'' (1807)\n*''[[Gloucestershire Victoria County History]]''\n\n===Hampshire===\n*[[William Bingley]], ''The Topographical Account of the Hundred of Bosmere'' (fragment) 1817\n*William White, ''History, gazetteer and directory of the County of Hampshire'' (1859; 2nd edition 1878)\n\n===Herefordshire===\n*[[John Duncumb]], partial work (1804\u201312) continued by others.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=8245|title=Duncumb, John|first=Robin|last=Whittaker}}</ref>\n\nDuncumb used work by [[Richard Blyke]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=2722|title=Blyke, Richard|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref> and an older manuscript by [[Silas Taylor]] (Domville).<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=7789|title=Taylor, Silas|first=David|last=Whitehead}}</ref>\n\n===Hertfordshire===\nSee: [[History of Hertfordshire]]; [[:Category:History of Hertfordshire]]; [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=16&type=1 ''Victoria County History'']\n*[[John Norden]], ''Speculi Britaniae Pars: the Description of Hartfordshire'' (1598)\n*[[Henry Chauncy]], ''Antiquities of Hertfordshire'' (1700)\n*[[Nathaniel Salmon]], ''History of Hertfordshire'' (1728)\n\nSalmon drew on unpublished material of Chauncy.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=5197|title=Chauncy, Henry|first=Nicholas|last=Doggett}}</ref>\n\n*[[Robert Clutterbuck]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Hertford'' (1815\u201327)\n\nClutterbuck used collections of [[Thomas Blore]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=2681|title=Blore, Thomas|first=Margaret|last=O'Sullivan}}</ref>\n\n*[[John Edwin Cussans]], ''A History of Hertfordshire, containing an account of the Descents of the various Manors, Pedigrees of Families, Antiquities, Local Customs, &c.'' (16 parts in three folio volumes, 1870\u201381)\n\n===Kent===\n*[[William Lambarde]], ''A Perambulation of Kent'' (completed 1570; published 1576)\n*[[Richard Kilburne]], ''A Brief Survey of the County of Kent'' (1657) [a summary digest of parishes]; and ''A Topographie, or Survey of the County of Kent'' (1659)\n*[[Thomas Philipot]], ''Villare Cantianum: or Kent Surveyed and Illustrated'' (1659)\nPhilipot drew on materials originally collected by his father, [[John Philipot]], and the ''Villare Cantianum'' is sometimes said to be John's work published under Thomas's name.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22109|title=Philipot, Thomas |first=Ian William |last=McLellan}}</ref> He also drew on notes inherited from [[Robert Glover (officer of arms)|Robert Glover]], his great-uncle.\n*[[Edward Hasted]], ''The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent'', (1st edn, 4 folio vols, 1778\u201399); (2nd edn, 12 octavo vols, 1797\u20131801)\n*[[Samuel Henshall]], ''Specimens and parts; containing a history of the county of Kent and a dissertation on the laws'' (1798, partial)\n*Christopher Greenwood, ''An Epitome of County History'' Vol. 1 (1818)\n\n===Lancashire===\n*[[Matthew Gregson (antiquary)|Matthew Gregson]], ''Portfolio of Fragments relative to the History and Antiquities of the County Palatine and Duchy of Lancaster'' (1817)\n*[[John Corry (writer)|John Corry]], ''History of Lancashire'' (1825)\n*[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Edward Baines]], ''Directory and Gazetteer of the County of Lancaster'' (1824\u201325) and ''History of the County Palatine of Lancaster'' (1836).\n\nBaines used [[Edwin Butterworth]] as researcher and author;<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=1089|title=Baines, Edward|first=Alan G.|last=Crosby}}</ref> he also took much from Gregson's ''Portfolio''.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=11477|title=Gregson, Matthew|first=D. Ben|last=Rees}}</ref>\n\n===Leicestershire===\n*[[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton]], ''The Description of Leicester Shire'' (1622)\n\nBurton made use of notes of [[Augustine Vincent]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=28307|title=Vincent, Augustine|first=A. E.|last=Brown}}</ref>\n\n*[[John Nichols (printer)|John Nichols]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester''. 4 vols. (1795\u20131815)\n\nNichols included unpublished material from William Burton, [[Francis Peck]], and [[Richard Farmer]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=63494|title=Nichols family|first1=Julian|last1=Pooley|first2=Robin|last2=Myers}}</ref>\n\n*William White, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of Leicestershire'', 1863\n\n===Lincolnshire===\n*[[William Marrat]], ''History of Lincolnshire'' (1814\u201316), incomplete<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=18088|title=Marrat, William|first=Anita|last=McConnell}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas Allen (topographer)|Thomas Allen]], ''A History of the County of Lincoln'' (1833\u201334)\n\n===Middlesex===\n*[[John Norden]], ''Speculum Britanniae: the First Parte: an Historicall, & Chorographicall Discription of Middlesex'' (1593)\n\n===Norfolk===\n*Anonymous, ''The Chorography of Norfolk'' (''c''.1602: unpublished)<ref>An edition is published as Christobel M. Hood, ''The Chorography of Norfolk'' (Norwich 1938). Hood's attribution of the work to [[John Norden]] is no longer accepted.</ref>\n*[[Francis Blomefield]], ''Topographical History of Norfolk'' (1739\u201345) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=139&type=1]\n\nBlomefield used materials from [[Peter Le Neve]] and [[Thomas Martin of Palgrave]].<ref name=Blomefield>{{ODNBweb|id=2663|title=Blomefield, Francis|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref> [[Charles Parkin]] worked to complete the history.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=21367|title=Parkin, Charles|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref> Blomefield used material collected by [[Antony Norris]], who later worked on completing and revising the history with [[John Fenn (antiquarian)|John Fenn]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=20263|title=Norris, Antony|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref>\n\n*Anonymous, ''History and Antiquities of the County of Norfolk'' (1781)\n\nBy Crouse and Booth of Norwich, this was largely copied from Blomefield.<ref name=Blomefield/>\n\n*[[John Chambers (antiquary)|John Chambers]], ''A General History of the County of Norfolk'' (1829)\n\n===Northamptonshire===\n*[[John Morton (naturalist)|John Morton]], ''The Natural History of Northamptonshire, with some account of the antiquities; to which is annexed a transcript of Domesday Book'' (1712)\n*[[Peter Whalley (clergyman)|Peter Whalley]], ''The History and Antiquities of Northamptonshire. Compiled from the manuscript collections of the late learned antiquary, John Bridges, Esq.'' (1762\u20131791)\n\nThis resulted from a project started by [[John Bridges (topographer)|John Bridges]], and took several generations to come to fruition.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bridges, John (1666-1724)}}</ref><ref>Brown and Foard 1994</ref>\n\n*[[George Baker (topographer)|George Baker]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Northampton'' (1822\u201330)\n\n===Northumberland===\n*[[John Wallis (antiquary)|John Wallis]], ''The Natural History and Antiquities of Northumberland, and so much of the County of Durham as lies between the rivers Tyne and Tweed, commonly called North Bishoprick'' (2 vols., 1769).\n*[[Eneas Mackenzie]], ''An Historical and Descriptive View of the County of Northumberland'' (1811, 2 vols. and revised 1825); and ''A Descriptive and Historical Account of the Town and County of Newcastle-upon-Tyne'' (1827, 2 vols.)\n*[[John Hodgson (antiquary)|John Hodgson]], ''History of Northumberland'' (unfinished, from 1825)\n*[[John Hodgson Hinde]], ''A History of Northumberland'' (1858)\n*''History of the County of Northumberland'' (15 volumes 1893\u20131940). This was issued by the Northumberland County History Committee.\n\n===Nottinghamshire===\n*[[Robert Thoroton]], ''Antiquities of Nottinghamshire'', 1677\n*[[John Throsby]], ''Antiquities of Nottinghamshire'', 1790\n\n===Oxfordshire===\n*[[Robert Plot]], ''The Natural History of Oxford-shire (1677)\n\n===Rutland===\n*[[James Wright (antiquary)|James Wright]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Rutland'' (1684)\n*[[Thomas Blore]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Rutland'' (1811, partial)\n\n===Shropshire===\n*[[Charles Hulbert]], ''History of the County of Salop'' (1837)\n\nThis included an edition of the 1779 ''History and Antiquities of Shrewsbury'' by [[Thomas Phillips (historian)|Thomas Phillips]], which drew on the work of [[James Bowen (artist)|James Bowen]] and [[John Bowen (antiquary)|John Bowen]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22173|title=Phillips, Thomas|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref>\n\n*[[Thomas Farmer Dukes]], ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (1844)\n\nDukes used a manuscript of [[Edward Lloyd (antiquary)|Edward Lloyd]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=64842|title=Lloyd, Edward|first=David Boyd|last=Haycock}}</ref>\n\n===Somerset===\n*[[John Collinson (died 1793)|John Collinson]] (1791, 3 vols.) including survey by [[Edmund Rack]]<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22971|title=Rack, Edmund|first=Anne Pimlott|last=Baker}}</ref>\n*[[Somerset Victoria County History]]\n\n===Staffordshire===\n*[[Sampson Erdeswicke]], ''Survey of Staffordshire''\n*[[Robert Plot]], ''The Natural History of Staffordshire (1686)\n*[[Stebbing Shaw]], ''History of Staffordshire'' (''History and Antiquities of Staffordshire'')\n*William Pitt, ''A Topographical History of Staffordshire'' (1817)\n\n===Suffolk===\n*Anonymous, ''The Chorography of Suffolk'' (1602: unpublished)<ref>An edition is published as D.N.J. MaCullough, ''The Chorography of Suffolk'', Suffolk Records Society vol. 19 (1977).</ref>\n*[[Robert Reyce]], ''A Breviary of Suffolk'' (''c''.1618: unpublished)<ref>Two manuscript [[recension]]s survive. One (now in the British Library) was published as Robert Reyce, ''Suffolk in the XVIIth century: the Breviary of Suffolk'', ed. Lord Francis Hervey (London, 1902). The other (now Suffolk Record Office HD 474/1) is superior.</ref>\n*[[John Gage Rokewode]], ''The History and Antiquities of Suffolk'', 1838\n*[[Alfred Suckling]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Suffolk'' (1846) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.aspx?pubid=413]\n*[[M. R. James]], ''Suffolk and Norfolk: A Perambulation of the Two Counties with Notices of Their History and Their Ancient Buildings'' (1930)\n\n===Surrey===\n*[[John Aubrey]], ''Perambulation of Surrey'' (written 1673\u201392); published by [[Richard Rawlinson]] as ''The Natural History and Antiquities of the County of Surrey'' (1718\u201319)\n*[[Owen Manning]] and [[William Bray (antiquary)|William Bray]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Surrey'' (1804\u201314)\n*[[Edward Wedlake Brayley]] with [[Gideon Algernon Mantell]] (geology), ''A Topographical History of Surrey'' (1841)\n\n===Sussex===\n*[[James Dallaway]], ''History of the Western Division of Sussex'' (1815 to 1832), with Edmund Cartwright\n*[[Thomas Walker Horsfield]], ''The History, Antiquities and Topography of the County of Sussex'' (1835)\n*[[John Russell Smith]], ''Sussex archaeological collections illustrating the history and antiquities of the county'', 1853\n\n===Warwickshire===\n*[[William Dugdale]], ''The Antiquities of Warwickshire'' (1656)\n\nDugdale used notes from [[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=4141|title=Burton, William|first=Richard|last=Cust}}</ref> and much material from [[Simon Archer (antiquary)|Simon Archer]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=626|title=Archer, Simon|first=Richard|last=Cust}}</ref>\n\n===Wiltshire===\n*[[John Aubrey]], ''Antiquities of Wiltshire'' (written 1656\u201371; partially published 1862); and ''Naturall Historie of Wiltshire'' (written 1656\u201391; partially published 1847)\n*[[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Colt Hoare]], ''The History of Modern Wiltshire'' (1822\u201344)\n*''[[Wiltshire Victoria County History]]''\n*''[[Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine]]''\n\n===Worcestershire===\n*[[Treadway Russell Nash]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Worcester'' (1781)\n\nNash used collections of [[Charles Lyttelton (bishop)|Charles Lyttelton]], including older research of [[Thomas Habington]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=17305|title=Lyttelton, Charles|first=Bernard|last=Nurse}}</ref> He also was aware of the work of [[Thomas Dingley (antiquary)|Thomas Dingley]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dingley, Thomas}}</ref>\n\n===Yorkshire===\n*[[Ralph Thoresby]], using collections of [[John Hopkinson (antiquary)|John Hopkinson]]<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=13757|title=Hopkinson, John|first=Jan|last=Broadway}}</ref>\n*''Memoirs Illustrative of the History and Antiquities of the County and City of York'' (1816)\n*[[Joseph Hunter (antiquarian)|Joseph Hunter]], ''South Yorkshire (a history of the Deanery of Doncaster)'' (1828\u201331)\n*[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Edward Baines]], ''History, Directory and Gazetteer of the County of York'' (1822\u201323)\n*[[Thomas Allen (topographer)|Thomas Allen]], ''A New and Complete History of the County of York'' (1828\u201331)\n*''The Survey of the County of York'', John de Kirkby, 1866 [https://books.google.com/books?id=0tgKAAAAYAAJ&dq=york+lyvet&source=gbs_navlinks_s]\n\n==Related histories==\n\n===Worthies===\n*[[Thomas Fuller]], ''Worthies of England''\n*[[John Prince (Totnes)|John Prince]], ''Worthies of Devon''\n*[[Hartley Coleridge]], ''Worthies of Yorkshire and Lancashire'' (1836)\n*[[Mark Antony Lower]], ''Worthies of Sussex'' (1865)\n*[[Cornelius Brown]], ''Worthies of Notts''\n*Winnifrith Alfred, Men of Kent and Kentish men: biographical notices of 680 worthies of Kent\n*[[Henry Lonsdale]]  ''The Worthies of Cumberland'' (1867)\n*George Atkinson, ''The Worthies of Westmorland''\n*Browne, Edith Ophelia; Burton, John Richard (editors). ''A short biography of the Worthies of Worcestershire''\n\n===Urban and parish histories===\nHistories were also written of cities, [[ancient borough]]s, newer municipalities, and even individual parishes (parochial histories).\n\n*[[John Stow]], ''The Survey of London'' (1598 and 1603)\n*[[Francis Drake (antiquary)|Francis Drake]], ''Eboracum: The History and Antiquities of the City of York, from its Original to the Present Time; together with the History of the Cathedral Church and the Lives of the Archbishops'' (1736)\n*W. Newton, ''The History and Antiquities of Maidstone'' (1741)\n*[[Philip Morant]], ''The History and Antiquities of Colchester'' (1748)\n*[[Thomas Warton]], ''The History and Antiquities of Kiddington'' (1782)\n*[[William Barrett (antiquarian)|William Barrett]], ''History and Antiquities of Bristol'' (1788)\n*[[John Throsby]], ''The History and Antiquities of the Ancient Town of Leicester'' (1791)\n*[[John Brewster (author)|John Brewster]], ''Parochial History and Antiquities of Stockton-on-Tees'' (1796)\n*[[John Blackner]], ''History of Nottingham'' (1815)\n*[[Thomas Walker Horsfield]], ''The History and Antiquities of Lewes'' (1824\u201326)\n*[[James Thompson (journalist)|James Thompson]], ''History of Leicester'' (1849\u201371)\n*Pishey Thompson, ''The History and Antiquities of Boston''  (1856)\n*[[Richard Vickerman Taylor]], ''The Biographia Leodiensis; or, Biographical Sketches of the Worthies of Leeds and neighbourhood, from the Norman Conquest to the present time, etc.''(1865\u201367)\n*[[Howard Dudley]], ''The History and Antiquities of Horsham''\n*[[Thomas Faulkner (topographer)|Thomas Faulkner]], ''History and Antiquities of Hammersmith''\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chorography]]\n*[[English local history]]\n*[[General View of Agriculture county surveys]]\n*''[[Popular County Histories]]'' book series\n*[[Alan Ball Local History Awards]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Cite book|first=S.B. |last=Black |title=A Scholar and a Gentleman: Edward Hasted, the historian of Kent |place=Otford |publisher=Darenth Valley Publications |year=2001 |ISBN=0-9507334-8-2 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=John |last=Blatchly|title=The Topographers of Suffolk, 1561\u20131935 |place=Ipswich |publisher=Suffolk Record Office|year=1988 |ISBN=0-86055-178-4 |edition=5th }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Mark |last=Brayshay (ed.) |title=Topographical Writers in South-West England |place=Exeter |publisher=University of Exeter Press |year=1996 |ISBN=0-85989-424-X }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Jan |last=Broadway |title=\"No Historie So Meete\": gentry culture and the development of local history in Elizabethan and early Stuart England|year=2006 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |ISBN=978-0-7190-7294-9 }}\n*{{Cite book| first1=Tony |last1=Brown |first2=Glenn |last2=Foard |title=The Making of a County History: John Bridges' Northamptonshire |place=Leicester |publisher=University of Leicester; Northamptonshire County Council |year=1994 |ISBN=0-947590-20-X }}\n*{{Cite book|editor1-first=C.R.J. |editor1-last=Currie |editor2-first=C.P. |editor2-last=Lewis |title=English County Histories: a guide |place=Stroud |publisher=Alan Sutton |year=1994 |ISBN=0-7509-0289-2 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Irvine |last=Gray |title=Antiquaries of Gloucestershire and Bristol |place=Bristol |publisher=Bristol and Gloucestershire Archaeological Society |year=1981 |ISBN=0-900197-14-5 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=M.W. |last=Greenslade |title=The Staffordshire Historians |year=1982 |location=Stoke-on-Trent |publisher=Staffordshire Record Society |series=Collections for a History of Staffordshire 4th series |volume=11 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=S.A.E. |last=Mendyk |title=\"Speculum Britanniae\": regional study, antiquarianism and science in Britain to 1700 |year=1989 |location=Toronto |publisher=University of Toronto Press |ISBN=0-8020-5744-6 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Rosemary |last=Sweet |year=1997 |title=The Writing of Urban Histories in Eighteenth-Century England |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |ISBN=0-19-820669-0 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Rosemary |last=Sweet |year=2004 |title=Antiquaries: the Discovery of the Past in Eighteenth-Century Britain |place=London |publisher=Hambledon and London |ISBN=1-85285-309-3 |pages=36\u201342 }}\n\n[[Category:English antiquarians]]\n[[Category:Regional geography]]\n[[Category:English history-related lists]]\n[[Category:English local history]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n'''English county histories''', in other words historical and topographical (or \"[[Chorography|chorographical]]\") works concerned with individual [[ancient counties of England]], were produced by [[antiquarian]]s from the late 16th century onwards. The content was variable: most focused on recording the ownership of estates and the descent of lordships of [[manor]]s, thus the genealogies of county families, heraldry and other antiquarian material; In the introduction to one typical early work of this style, ''The Antiquities of Warwickshire'' published in 1656, the author [[William Dugdale]] writes:<ref>https://archive.org/details/antiquitiesofwar00dugd/page/n7/mode/2up</ref></br>\n:''I offer unto you my noble countriemen, as the most proper persons to whom it can be presented wherein you will see very much of your worthy ancestors, to whose memory I have erected it as a monumentall pillar and to shew in what honour they lived in those flourishing ages past. In this kind, or not much different, have divers persons in forrein parts very learnedly written; some whereof I have noted in my preface: and I could wish that there were more that would adventure in the like manner for the rest of the counties of this nation, considering how acceptable those are, which others have already performed''.</br>\nThus his work was designed primarily to be read by his fellow county gentry of Warwickshire, whose public lives and marriages were largely confined within their own county of residence, which they administered as Justices of the Peace and Sheriffs, and represented in Parliament. The genealogical and heraldic tradition continues with the series of [[Victoria County History|Victoria County Histories]] commenced in the late 19th century. \n\nOther forms recorded [[archaeological site]]s. A closely related genre, which emerged in the second half of the 17th century, was the county \"Natural History\", which focused on the county's flora, fauna and natural phenomena, but which also often included chapters on antiquities. The best known examples were [[Robert Plot]]'s two volumes on Oxfordshire (1677) and Staffordshire (1686); and [[John Aubrey]]'s unpublished work on Wiltshire.\n\n==Development==\n===Continental models===\nDugdale quotes as his foreign models C\u00e9sar de Nostredame (1553-1629), historian of [[Provence]] in France, author of ''Rerum antiquarum et nobiliorum Provinciae'', written c.1560, published 1615; Ottavio Rossi, historan of [[Brescia]] in Italy, author of ''Memorie Bresciane, Opera Historica, E Simbolica'' (1626);  Guillaume Catel (1560-1626), historian of [[Languedoc]] in France, author of ''M\u00e9moires sur l'histoire du Languedoc'' (1633); [[Samuel Guichenon]] (1607-1664), historian of Bresse in France, author of  ''Histoire de la [[Bresse]] et du [[Bugey]]'' (1650) and [[Antonius Sanderus]] (1586-1664), historian of Flanders, author of ''Flandria Illustrata'' (1641). \n\n===English pioneers===\n[[William Lambarde]]'s ''Perambulation of [[Kent]]'' (completed 1570; published 1576) is generally acknowledged as the first example of the genre in England. It was followed by [[Richard Carew (antiquary)|Richard Carew's]] ''Survey of Cornwall'' (1602), and [[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton's]] ''Description of Leicester Shire'' (1622), as well as a number of other projects (such as those of [[Sir William Pole]], [[Thomas Westcote]], and [[Tristram Risdon]] in Devon, and [[Sampson Erdeswicke]] in Staffordshire) which, although they sometimes circulated in manuscript, did not come to completion or publication. Following the appearance of [[William Dugdale]]'s ''Antiquities of Warwickshire'' (1656), a pattern was set. In the nineteenth century [[John Bowyer Nichols]] followed the line of a history of [[Leicestershire]] compiled by his father [[John Nichols (printer)|John Nichols]], and saw numerous counties histories through the press at his printing firm.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Nichols, John Bowyer}}</ref> The scope of county histories varied, but the titles became quite standard: \"Antiquities of\", \"Worthies of\", \"Geological survey\", \"Description of\", later \"Directory of\", all could indicate the intention of producing a \"history\", a term that only in later times acquired the narrower meaning it carries today. [[Chorography]], [[topography]] and [[toponymy]] might all be involved. Materials and collections for their counties were made by antiquaries, but publication might await sponsorship or enough subscriptions, as well as a capable author who would make a readable book, perhaps of multiple volumes, from notes.\n\n==Listing by county==\n\n===Bedfordshire===\nSee: [[History of Bedfordshire]]; [[:Category: History of Bedfordshire]];\n\n*''[[Magna Britannia]]'' (1806)\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=1&type=1 ''Victoria County History''] three volumes, 1904\u20131912\n\n===Berkshire===\n*[[Elias Ashmole]], ''Antiquities of Berkshire'' (1719)\n* J. Rocque, ''A Topographical Survey of the County of Berkshire'', 1761\n\n===Buckinghamshire===\nSee: [[History of Buckinghamshire]]; [[:Category: History of Buckinghamshire]]; ''Victoria County History'' edited by William Page\n*[[George Lipscomb]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Buckingham'' published in eight parts, 1831\u201347 [https://archive.org/details/historyantiquiti02lips]\n*[[James Joseph Sheahan]], ''History and Topography of Buckinghamshire: comprising a general survey of the county, preceded by an epitome of the early history of Great Britain'' (1862)\n\n===Cambridgeshire===\n*[[Edmund Carter (topographer)|Edmund Carter]], ''History of the County of Cambridge'' (1753)\n\n===Cheshire===\n*[[Sir Peter Leycester, 1st Baronet]], ''Historical antiquities'' (1673)\n*[[Peter Perez Burdett]], ''Survey of the County Palatine of Chester'' (1772)\n*[[George Ormerod]], ''The History of the County Palatine and City of Chester'' (1816\u201319)\n\n===Cornwall===\n*[[Richard Carew (antiquary)|Richard Carew]], ''The Survey of Cornwall'' (1602)\n*[[William Hals]], ''Compleat History of Cornwall'', from about 1750<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=12027|title=Hals, William|first=Jan|last=Broadway}}</ref>\n*An historical survey of the county of Cornwall, etc., compiled by William Penaluna\n*[[Richard Polwhele]], ''The History of Cornwall'' (7 vols. 1803\u201308, revised 1816)\n*[[Daniel Lysons (antiquarian)|Daniel Lysons]] and [[Samuel Lysons]], ''[[Magna Britannia]]''\n\nThe Cornwall history was supported by [[Francis Vyvyan Jago Arundell]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=715|title=Arundell, Francis Vyvyan Jago|first=Christine|last=North}}</ref>\n\n*[[Charles Sandoe Gilbert]], ''Historical Survey of the County of Cornwall'' (2 vols., 1817\u201320)<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=10683|title=Gilbert, Charles Sandoe|first=Elizabeth|last=Baigent}}</ref>\n*[[Fortescue Hitchins]] and [[Samuel Drew]], ''The History of Cornwall'' (1824)\n\n===Cumberland and Westmorland===\n*[[Richard Burn]] and Joseph Nicolson, ''The History and Antiquities of the Counties of Westmorland and Cumberland'', 1777.\n\nThis goes back to the manuscript ''Accompt of the most considerable estates and families in the county of Cumberland'' of about 1603 by John Denton.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=74666|title=Denton, John|first1=Mary|last1=Wane|first2=Angus J. L.|last2=Winchester}}</ref> Through copies made by [[Daniel Fleming (antiquary)|Daniel Fleming]], it used material collected by [[Christopher Rawlinson (antiquary)|Christopher Rawlinson]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Rawlinson, Christopher (1677-1733)}}</ref> Joseph Nicolson (born 1706, baptised William \u2013 1777), son of John Nicolson of Hawkesdale, was a nephew of Bishop [[William Nicolson]], and inherited from him collections relating to Carlisle.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Burke|title=A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Landed Gentry; Or, Commoners of Great Britain and Ireland Etc. - London, Henry Colburn 1837-1838|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vhpVAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA396|year=1838|publisher=Henry Colburn|page=396 note}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/transactionvol11no2cumb#page/240/mode/2up|title=Transactions of the Cumberland & Westmorland Antiquarian & Archaeological Society|work=[[Internet Archive]]|publisher=T. Wilson|pages=240 note|volume=XI|accessdate=26 December 2015|location=Highgate, Kendal}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalmers1815\">{{cite book|author=Alexander Chalmers|title=The General biographical dictionary|url=https://archive.org/details/generalbiograph31chalgoog|year=1815|publisher=Printed for J. Nichols|page=[https://archive.org/details/generalbiograph31chalgoog/page/n137 187]}}</ref><ref>http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-2055-1/dissemination/pdf/Article_Level_Pdf/tcwaas/001/1884/vol7/tcwaas_001_1884_vol7_0018.pdf</ref> Burn and Nicolson used in particular material collected by [[Thomas Machell]], vicar of [[Kirkby Thore]], and collated by William Nicolson.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=61544|first=Angus J. L.|last=Winchester|title=Machell, Thomas}}</ref>\n\n*[[William Hutchinson (topographer)|William Hutchinson]], ''History of the County of Cumberland'' (1794).\n\n===Derbyshire===\n*[[Stephen Glover (antiquary)|Stephen Glover]], ''Directory of the County of Derby'' (1827\u201329); and ''History of the County of Derby'' (1829\u201331)\n\nGlover made use of, and expanded, an unpublished history by William Woolley.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=10834|title=Glover, Stephen|first=Margaret|last=O'Sullivan}}</ref>\n\n*Samuel Bagshaw, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of Derbyshire'' (1846)\n*[[White's Directories|White]], ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Derby'' (1857)\n\n===Devon===\n*Sir [[William Pole (antiquary)|William Pole]] (d.1635), ''Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon'', notes made (''c''.1608\u20131617), published by [[Sir John de la Pole, 6th Baronet|Sir John-William de la Pole]] (ed.), London, 1791 \n*[[Thomas Westcote]], ''Survey of Devon'' of 1630\n*[[Tristram Risdon]], ''Chorographical Description or Survey of the County of Devon'' (c. 1632)\n*[[Richard Polwhele]], ''The History of Devonshire'' (1793\u20131806)\n\n[[John Swete]] supplied material to Polwhele.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=26827|title=Swete, John|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref>\n\n*[[William White (Sheffield, England)|William White]], ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Devon: including the city of Exeter, and comprising a general survey of the county''\n\n===Dorset===\n*[[John Hutchins (historian)|John Hutchins]], ''History and Antiquities of Dorset'' (1774)\n*John Hutchins, ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Dorset'', Vols. 1\u20134, 1815.\n\n===Durham===\n*[[William Hutchinson (topographer)|William Hutchinson]], ''History and Antiquities of the Country Palatine of Durham''\n*[[Robert Surtees (antiquarian)|Robert Surtees]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County Palatine of Durham''\n\nBoth Hutchinson and Surtees drew on the work of [[George Allan (antiquary)|George Allan]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=355|title=Allan, George|first=C. M.|last=Fraser}}</ref> [[John Brewster (author)|John Brewster]] assisted Surtees.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=3373|title=Brewster, John|first=R. H.|last=Sweet}}</ref>\n\n*[[James Raine]], ''The History and Antiquities of North-Durham'', 1852\n*William Fordyce, ''The History and Antiquities of the County Palatine of Durham''\n*Whellan, ''History, Topography, and Directory of the County Palatine of Durham'' (1856)\n\n===Essex===\n*[[Philip Morant]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Essex'', two volumes 1763\u20131768\n\nMorant used collections of [[Thomas Jekyll]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=14711|title=Jekyll, Thomas|first=J. S.|last=Reynolds}}</ref> and also material from [[Richard Symonds (diarist)|Richard Symonds]] he obtained via [[Gregory King]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=26890|title=Symonds, Richard|first=Ian|last=Roy}}</ref> A major source was the parish descriptions of [[William Holman (antiquary)|William Holman]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=13581|title=Holman, William|first=W. Raymond|last=Powell}}</ref> These had been acquired by [[Nicholas Tindal]], for whom Morant worked as a curate; Tindal made a small start on publishing Essex history, around 1732.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Tindal, Nicholas (1687-1774)}}</ref> They then passed via Nathaniel Salmon, [[Anthony Allen (antiquary)|Anthony Allen]] and John Booth, before Morant had them from Booth about 1750.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=19159|title=Morant, Philip|first=G. H.|last=Martin}}</ref>\n\n*''A New and Complete History of Essex, from a late survey'' (1772)\n*[[Elizabeth Ogborne]], ''The History of Essex'' (1817, one volume only)\n\n[[Thomas Leman]] and probably [[Joseph Strutt (engraver and antiquary)|Joseph Strutt]] assisted.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=20577|title=Ogborne, Elizabeth|first=Rosemary|last=Mitchell}}</ref>\n\n*William White, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of the County of Essex'', 1848\n\n===Gloucestershire===\n*[[Robert Atkyns (topographer)|Sir Robert Atkyns]], ''The Ancient and Present State of Glostershire'' (1712)\n*[[Samuel Rudder]], ''A New History of Gloucestershire'' (1779)\n\nRudder's work was based on Atkyns and a manuscript of [[Richard Furney]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=24248|title=Rudder, Samuel|first=Nicholas|last=Herbert}}</ref>\n\n*[[Ralph Bigland]], ''Historical, Monumental & Genealogical Collections relative to the County of Gloucester'' (1791\u201394)\n*[[Thomas Rudge]], ''The History of the County of Gloucester, compressed and brought down to the year 1803'' (1803)\n*[[Thomas Dudley Fosbroke]], ''Abstracts of Records and Manuscripts Respecting the County of Gloucester'' (1807)\n*''[[Gloucestershire Victoria County History]]''\n\n===Hampshire===\n*[[William Bingley]], ''The Topographical Account of the Hundred of Bosmere'' (fragment) 1817\n*William White, ''History, gazetteer and directory of the County of Hampshire'' (1859; 2nd edition 1878)\n\n===Herefordshire===\n*[[John Duncumb]], partial work (1804\u201312) continued by others.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=8245|title=Duncumb, John|first=Robin|last=Whittaker}}</ref>\n\nDuncumb used work by [[Richard Blyke]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=2722|title=Blyke, Richard|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref> and an older manuscript by [[Silas Taylor]] (Domville).<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=7789|title=Taylor, Silas|first=David|last=Whitehead}}</ref>\n\n===Hertfordshire===\nSee: [[History of Hertfordshire]]; [[:Category:History of Hertfordshire]]; [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=16&type=1 ''Victoria County History'']\n*[[John Norden]], ''Speculi Britaniae Pars: the Description of Hartfordshire'' (1598)\n*[[Henry Chauncy]], ''Antiquities of Hertfordshire'' (1700)\n*[[Nathaniel Salmon]], ''History of Hertfordshire'' (1728)\n\nSalmon drew on unpublished material of Chauncy.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=5197|title=Chauncy, Henry|first=Nicholas|last=Doggett}}</ref>\n\n*[[Robert Clutterbuck]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Hertford'' (1815\u201327)\n\nClutterbuck used collections of [[Thomas Blore]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=2681|title=Blore, Thomas|first=Margaret|last=O'Sullivan}}</ref>\n\n*[[John Edwin Cussans]], ''A History of Hertfordshire, containing an account of the Descents of the various Manors, Pedigrees of Families, Antiquities, Local Customs, &c.'' (16 parts in three folio volumes, 1870\u201381)\n\n===Kent===\n*[[William Lambarde]], ''A Perambulation of Kent'' (completed 1570; published 1576)\n*[[Richard Kilburne]], ''A Brief Survey of the County of Kent'' (1657) [a summary digest of parishes]; and ''A Topographie, or Survey of the County of Kent'' (1659)\n*[[Thomas Philipot]], ''Villare Cantianum: or Kent Surveyed and Illustrated'' (1659)\nPhilipot drew on materials originally collected by his father, [[John Philipot]], and the ''Villare Cantianum'' is sometimes said to be John's work published under Thomas's name.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22109|title=Philipot, Thomas |first=Ian William |last=McLellan}}</ref> He also drew on notes inherited from [[Robert Glover (officer of arms)|Robert Glover]], his great-uncle.\n*[[Edward Hasted]], ''The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent'', (1st edn, 4 folio vols, 1778\u201399); (2nd edn, 12 octavo vols, 1797\u20131801)\n*[[Samuel Henshall]], ''Specimens and parts; containing a history of the county of Kent and a dissertation on the laws'' (1798, partial)\n*Christopher Greenwood, ''An Epitome of County History'' Vol. 1 (1818)\n\n===Lancashire===\n*[[Matthew Gregson (antiquary)|Matthew Gregson]], ''Portfolio of Fragments relative to the History and Antiquities of the County Palatine and Duchy of Lancaster'' (1817)\n*[[John Corry (writer)|John Corry]], ''History of Lancashire'' (1825)\n*[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Edward Baines]], ''Directory and Gazetteer of the County of Lancaster'' (1824\u201325) and ''History of the County Palatine of Lancaster'' (1836).\n\nBaines used [[Edwin Butterworth]] as researcher and author;<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=1089|title=Baines, Edward|first=Alan G.|last=Crosby}}</ref> he also took much from Gregson's ''Portfolio''.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=11477|title=Gregson, Matthew|first=D. Ben|last=Rees}}</ref>\n\n===Leicestershire===\n*[[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton]], ''The Description of Leicester Shire'' (1622)\n\nBurton made use of notes of [[Augustine Vincent]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=28307|title=Vincent, Augustine|first=A. E.|last=Brown}}</ref>\n\n*[[John Nichols (printer)|John Nichols]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Leicester''. 4 vols. (1795\u20131815)\n\nNichols included unpublished material from William Burton, [[Francis Peck]], and [[Richard Farmer]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=63494|title=Nichols family|first1=Julian|last1=Pooley|first2=Robin|last2=Myers}}</ref>\n\n*William White, ''History, Gazetteer and Directory of Leicestershire'', 1863\n\n===Lincolnshire===\n*[[William Marrat]], ''History of Lincolnshire'' (1814\u201316), incomplete<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=18088|title=Marrat, William|first=Anita|last=McConnell}}</ref>\n*[[Thomas Allen (topographer)|Thomas Allen]], ''A History of the County of Lincoln'' (1833\u201334)\n\n===Middlesex===\n*[[John Norden]], ''Speculum Britanniae: the First Parte: an Historicall, & Chorographicall Discription of Middlesex'' (1593)\n\n===Norfolk===\n*Anonymous, ''The Chorography of Norfolk'' (''c''.1602: unpublished)<ref>An edition is published as Christobel M. Hood, ''The Chorography of Norfolk'' (Norwich 1938). Hood's attribution of the work to [[John Norden]] is no longer accepted.</ref>\n*[[Francis Blomefield]], ''Topographical History of Norfolk'' (1739\u201345) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/catalogue.aspx?gid=139&type=1]\n\nBlomefield used materials from [[Peter Le Neve]] and [[Thomas Martin of Palgrave]].<ref name=Blomefield>{{ODNBweb|id=2663|title=Blomefield, Francis|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref> [[Charles Parkin]] worked to complete the history.<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=21367|title=Parkin, Charles|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref> Blomefield used material collected by [[Antony Norris]], who later worked on completing and revising the history with [[John Fenn (antiquarian)|John Fenn]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=20263|title=Norris, Antony|first=David|last=Stoker}}</ref>\n\n*Anonymous, ''History and Antiquities of the County of Norfolk'' (1781)\n\nBy Crouse and Booth of Norwich, this was largely copied from Blomefield.<ref name=Blomefield/>\n\n*[[John Chambers (antiquary)|John Chambers]], ''A General History of the County of Norfolk'' (1829)\n\n===Northamptonshire===\n*[[John Morton (naturalist)|John Morton]], ''The Natural History of Northamptonshire, with some account of the antiquities; to which is annexed a transcript of Domesday Book'' (1712)\n*[[Peter Whalley (clergyman)|Peter Whalley]], ''The History and Antiquities of Northamptonshire. Compiled from the manuscript collections of the late learned antiquary, John Bridges, Esq.'' (1762\u20131791)\n\nThis resulted from a project started by [[John Bridges (topographer)|John Bridges]], and took several generations to come to fruition.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bridges, John (1666-1724)}}</ref><ref>Brown and Foard 1994</ref>\n\n*[[George Baker (topographer)|George Baker]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Northampton'' (1822\u201330)\n\n===Northumberland===\n*[[John Wallis (antiquary)|John Wallis]], ''The Natural History and Antiquities of Northumberland, and so much of the County of Durham as lies between the rivers Tyne and Tweed, commonly called North Bishoprick'' (2 vols., 1769).\n*[[Eneas Mackenzie]], ''An Historical and Descriptive View of the County of Northumberland'' (1811, 2 vols. and revised 1825); and ''A Descriptive and Historical Account of the Town and County of Newcastle-upon-Tyne'' (1827, 2 vols.)\n*[[John Hodgson (antiquary)|John Hodgson]], ''History of Northumberland'' (unfinished, from 1825)\n*[[John Hodgson Hinde]], ''A History of Northumberland'' (1858)\n*''History of the County of Northumberland'' (15 volumes 1893\u20131940). This was issued by the Northumberland County History Committee.\n\n===Nottinghamshire===\n*[[Robert Thoroton]], ''Antiquities of Nottinghamshire'', 1677\n*[[John Throsby]], ''Antiquities of Nottinghamshire'', 1790\n\n===Oxfordshire===\n*[[Robert Plot]], ''The Natural History of Oxford-shire (1677)\n\n===Rutland===\n*[[James Wright (antiquary)|James Wright]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Rutland'' (1684)\n*[[Thomas Blore]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Rutland'' (1811, partial)\n\n===Shropshire===\n*[[Charles Hulbert]], ''History of the County of Salop'' (1837)\n\nThis included an edition of the 1779 ''History and Antiquities of Shrewsbury'' by [[Thomas Phillips (historian)|Thomas Phillips]], which drew on the work of [[James Bowen (artist)|James Bowen]] and [[John Bowen (antiquary)|John Bowen]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22173|title=Phillips, Thomas|first=J. A.|last=Marchand}}</ref>\n\n*[[Thomas Farmer Dukes]], ''Antiquities of Shropshire'' (1844)\n\nDukes used a manuscript of [[Edward Lloyd (antiquary)|Edward Lloyd]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=64842|title=Lloyd, Edward|first=David Boyd|last=Haycock}}</ref>\n\n===Somerset===\n*[[John Collinson (died 1793)|John Collinson]] (1791, 3 vols.) including survey by [[Edmund Rack]]<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=22971|title=Rack, Edmund|first=Anne Pimlott|last=Baker}}</ref>\n*[[Somerset Victoria County History]]\n\n===Staffordshire===\n*[[Sampson Erdeswicke]], ''Survey of Staffordshire''\n*[[Robert Plot]], ''The Natural History of Staffordshire (1686)\n*[[Stebbing Shaw]], ''History of Staffordshire'' (''History and Antiquities of Staffordshire'')\n*William Pitt, ''A Topographical History of Staffordshire'' (1817)\n\n===Suffolk===\n*Anonymous, ''The Chorography of Suffolk'' (1602: unpublished)<ref>An edition is published as D.N.J. MaCullough, ''The Chorography of Suffolk'', Suffolk Records Society vol. 19 (1977).</ref>\n*[[Robert Reyce]], ''A Breviary of Suffolk'' (''c''.1618: unpublished)<ref>Two manuscript [[recension]]s survive. One (now in the British Library) was published as Robert Reyce, ''Suffolk in the XVIIth century: the Breviary of Suffolk'', ed. Lord Francis Hervey (London, 1902). The other (now Suffolk Record Office HD 474/1) is superior.</ref>\n*[[John Gage Rokewode]], ''The History and Antiquities of Suffolk'', 1838\n*[[Alfred Suckling]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Suffolk'' (1846) [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.aspx?pubid=413]\n*[[M. R. James]], ''Suffolk and Norfolk: A Perambulation of the Two Counties with Notices of Their History and Their Ancient Buildings'' (1930)\n\n===Surrey===\n*[[John Aubrey]], ''Perambulation of Surrey'' (written 1673\u201392); published by [[Richard Rawlinson]] as ''The Natural History and Antiquities of the County of Surrey'' (1718\u201319)\n*[[Owen Manning]] and [[William Bray (antiquary)|William Bray]], ''The History and Antiquities of the County of Surrey'' (1804\u201314)\n*[[Edward Wedlake Brayley]] with [[Gideon Algernon Mantell]] (geology), ''A Topographical History of Surrey'' (1841)\n\n===Sussex===\n*[[James Dallaway]], ''History of the Western Division of Sussex'' (1815 to 1832), with Edmund Cartwright\n*[[Thomas Walker Horsfield]], ''The History, Antiquities and Topography of the County of Sussex'' (1835)\n*[[John Russell Smith]], ''Sussex archaeological collections illustrating the history and antiquities of the county'', 1853\n\n===Warwickshire===\n*[[William Dugdale]], ''The Antiquities of Warwickshire'' (1656)\n\nDugdale used notes from [[William Burton (antiquary, died 1645)|William Burton]];<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=4141|title=Burton, William|first=Richard|last=Cust}}</ref> and much material from [[Simon Archer (antiquary)|Simon Archer]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=626|title=Archer, Simon|first=Richard|last=Cust}}</ref>\n\n===Wiltshire===\n*[[John Aubrey]], ''Antiquities of Wiltshire'' (written 1656\u201371; partially published 1862); and ''Naturall Historie of Wiltshire'' (written 1656\u201391; partially published 1847)\n*[[Sir Richard Hoare, 2nd Baronet|Sir Richard Colt Hoare]], ''The History of Modern Wiltshire'' (1822\u201344)\n*''[[Wiltshire Victoria County History]]''\n*''[[Wiltshire Archaeological and Natural History Magazine]]''\n\n===Worcestershire===\n*[[Treadway Russell Nash]], ''History and Antiquities of the County of Worcester'' (1781)\n\nNash used collections of [[Charles Lyttelton (bishop)|Charles Lyttelton]], including older research of [[Thomas Habington]].<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=17305|title=Lyttelton, Charles|first=Bernard|last=Nurse}}</ref> He also was aware of the work of [[Thomas Dingley (antiquary)|Thomas Dingley]].<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dingley, Thomas}}</ref>\n\n===Yorkshire===\n*[[Ralph Thoresby]], using collections of [[John Hopkinson (antiquary)|John Hopkinson]]<ref>{{ODNBweb|id=13757|title=Hopkinson, John|first=Jan|last=Broadway}}</ref>\n*''Memoirs Illustrative of the History and Antiquities of the County and City of York'' (1816)\n*[[Joseph Hunter (antiquarian)|Joseph Hunter]], ''South Yorkshire (a history of the Deanery of Doncaster)'' (1828\u201331)\n*[[Edward Baines (1774\u20131848)|Edward Baines]], ''History, Directory and Gazetteer of the County of York'' (1822\u201323)\n*[[Thomas Allen (topographer)|Thomas Allen]], ''A New and Complete History of the County of York'' (1828\u201331)\n*''The Survey of the County of York'', John de Kirkby, 1866 [https://books.google.com/books?id=0tgKAAAAYAAJ&dq=york+lyvet&source=gbs_navlinks_s]\n\n==Related histories==\n\n===Worthies===\n*[[Thomas Fuller]], ''Worthies of England''\n*[[John Prince (Totnes)|John Prince]], ''Worthies of Devon''\n*[[Hartley Coleridge]], ''Worthies of Yorkshire and Lancashire'' (1836)\n*[[Mark Antony Lower]], ''Worthies of Sussex'' (1865)\n*[[Cornelius Brown]], ''Worthies of Notts''\n*Winnifrith Alfred, Men of Kent and Kentish men: biographical notices of 680 worthies of Kent\n*[[Henry Lonsdale]]  ''The Worthies of Cumberland'' (1867)\n*George Atkinson, ''The Worthies of Westmorland''\n*Browne, Edith Ophelia; Burton, John Richard (editors). ''A short biography of the Worthies of Worcestershire''\n\n===Urban and parish histories===\nHistories were also written of cities, [[ancient borough]]s, newer municipalities, and even individual parishes (parochial histories).\n\n*[[John Stow]], ''The Survey of London'' (1598 and 1603)\n*[[Francis Drake (antiquary)|Francis Drake]], ''Eboracum: The History and Antiquities of the City of York, from its Original to the Present Time; together with the History of the Cathedral Church and the Lives of the Archbishops'' (1736)\n*W. Newton, ''The History and Antiquities of Maidstone'' (1741)\n*[[Philip Morant]], ''The History and Antiquities of Colchester'' (1748)\n*[[Thomas Warton]], ''The History and Antiquities of Kiddington'' (1782)\n*[[William Barrett (antiquarian)|William Barrett]], ''History and Antiquities of Bristol'' (1788)\n*[[John Throsby]], ''The History and Antiquities of the Ancient Town of Leicester'' (1791)\n*[[John Brewster (author)|John Brewster]], ''Parochial History and Antiquities of Stockton-on-Tees'' (1796)\n*[[John Blackner]], ''History of Nottingham'' (1815)\n*[[Thomas Walker Horsfield]], ''The History and Antiquities of Lewes'' (1824\u201326)\n*[[James Thompson (journalist)|James Thompson]], ''History of Leicester'' (1849\u201371)\n*Pishey Thompson, ''The History and Antiquities of Boston''  (1856)\n*[[Richard Vickerman Taylor]], ''The Biographia Leodiensis; or, Biographical Sketches of the Worthies of Leeds and neighbourhood, from the Norman Conquest to the present time, etc.''(1865\u201367)\n*[[Howard Dudley]], ''The History and Antiquities of Horsham''\n*[[Thomas Faulkner (topographer)|Thomas Faulkner]], ''History and Antiquities of Hammersmith''\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chorography]]\n*[[English local history]]\n*[[General View of Agriculture county surveys]]\n*''[[Popular County Histories]]'' book series\n*[[Alan Ball Local History Awards]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Cite book|first=S.B. |last=Black |title=A Scholar and a Gentleman: Edward Hasted, the historian of Kent |place=Otford |publisher=Darenth Valley Publications |year=2001 |ISBN=0-9507334-8-2 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=John |last=Blatchly|title=The Topographers of Suffolk, 1561\u20131935 |place=Ipswich |publisher=Suffolk Record Office|year=1988 |ISBN=0-86055-178-4 |edition=5th }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Mark |last=Brayshay (ed.) |title=Topographical Writers in South-West England |place=Exeter |publisher=University of Exeter Press |year=1996 |ISBN=0-85989-424-X }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Jan |last=Broadway |title=\"No Historie So Meete\": gentry culture and the development of local history in Elizabethan and early Stuart England|year=2006 |location=Manchester |publisher=Manchester University Press |ISBN=978-0-7190-7294-9 }}\n*{{Cite book| first1=Tony |last1=Brown |first2=Glenn |last2=Foard |title=The Making of a County History: John Bridges' Northamptonshire |place=Leicester |publisher=University of Leicester; Northamptonshire County Council |year=1994 |ISBN=0-947590-20-X }}\n*{{Cite book|editor1-first=C.R.J. |editor1-last=Currie |editor2-first=C.P. |editor2-last=Lewis |title=English County Histories: a guide |place=Stroud |publisher=Alan Sutton |year=1994 |ISBN=0-7509-0289-2 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Irvine |last=Gray |title=Antiquaries of Gloucestershire and Bristol |place=Bristol |publisher=Bristol and Gloucestershire Archaeological Society |year=1981 |ISBN=0-900197-14-5 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=M.W. |last=Greenslade |title=The Staffordshire Historians |year=1982 |location=Stoke-on-Trent |publisher=Staffordshire Record Society |series=Collections for a History of Staffordshire 4th series |volume=11 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=S.A.E. |last=Mendyk |title=\"Speculum Britanniae\": regional study, antiquarianism and science in Britain to 1700 |year=1989 |location=Toronto |publisher=University of Toronto Press |ISBN=0-8020-5744-6 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Rosemary |last=Sweet |year=1997 |title=The Writing of Urban Histories in Eighteenth-Century England |place=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |ISBN=0-19-820669-0 }}\n*{{Cite book|first=Rosemary |last=Sweet |year=2004 |title=Antiquaries: the Discovery of the Past in Eighteenth-Century Britain |place=London |publisher=Hambledon and London |ISBN=1-85285-309-3 |pages=36\u201342 }}\n\n[[Category:English antiquarians]]\n[[Category:Regional geography]]\n[[Category:English history-related lists]]\n[[Category:English local history]]\n", "name_user": "Lobsterthermidor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContinental models", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_county_histories"}
{"title_page": "Umwani", "text_new": "{{Short description|Genus of spiders}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| taxon = Umwani\n| authority = Griswold, 2001<ref name=NMBE />\n| type_species = ''[[Umwani artigamos|U. artigamos]]''\n| type_species_authority = Griswold, 2001\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = {{Specieslist\n| [[Umwani anymphos|U. anymphos]]|<small>Griswold, 2001</small> \u2013 Malawi\n| [[Umwani artigamos|U. artigamos]]|<small>Griswold, 2001</small> \u2013 Tanzania}}\n}}\n\n'''''Umwani''''' is a [[genus]] of [[East Africa]]n [[Araneomorphae|araneomorph]] spiders in the family [[Cyatholipidae]], and was first described by C. E. Griswold in 2001.<ref name=Gris2001>{{cite journal| last=Griswold| first=C. E.| year=2001| title=A monograph of the living world genera and Afrotropical species of cyatholipid spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae, Araneoidea, Cyatholipidae).| journal=Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences| pages=1\u2013251| volume=26}}</ref> {{as of|2019|04}} it contains only two species: ''U. anymphos'' and ''U. artigamos''.<ref name=NMBE>{{cite web| title=Gen. Umwani Griswold, 2001| website=World Spider Catalog Version 20.0| accessdate=2019-05-30| year=2019| publisher=Natural History Museum Bern| url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/676| doi=10.24436/2}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3548249}}\n\n[[Category:Araneomorphae genera]]\n[[Category:Cyatholipidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 2001]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Africa]]\n\n\n{{Araneomorphae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Genus of spiders}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| taxon = Umwani\n| authority = Griswold, 2001<ref name=NMBE />\n| type_species = ''[[Umwani artigamos|U. artigamos]]''\n| type_species_authority = Griswold, 2001\n| subdivision_ranks = Species\n| subdivision = {{Specieslist\n| [[Umwani anymphos|U. anymphos]]|<small>Griswold, 2001</small> \u2013 Malawi\n| [[Umwani artigamos|U. artigamos]]|<small>Griswold, 2001</small> \u2013 Tanzania}}\n}}\n\n'''''Umwani''''' is a [[genus]] of [[East Africa]]n [[Araneomorphae|araneomorph]] spiders in the [[Cyatholipidae]] family, and was first described by C. E. Griswold in 2001.<ref name=Gris2001>{{cite journal| last=Griswold| first=C. E.| year=2001| title=A monograph of the living world genera and Afrotropical species of cyatholipid spiders (Araneae, Orbiculariae, Araneoidea, Cyatholipidae).| journal=Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences| pages=1\u2013251| volume=26}}</ref> {{as of|2019|04}} it contains only two species: ''U. anymphos'' and ''U. artigamos''.<ref name=NMBE>{{cite web| title=Gen. Umwani Griswold, 2001| website=World Spider Catalog Version 20.0| accessdate=2019-05-30| year=2019| publisher=Natural History Museum Bern| url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/genus/676| doi=10.24436/2}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3548249}}\n\n[[Category:Araneomorphae genera]]\n[[Category:Cyatholipidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 2001]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Africa]]\n\n\n{{Araneomorphae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Umwani"}
{"title_page": "Women's sports", "text_new": "{{short description|Sports participated by females}}\n{{globalize|article|the United States|date=August 2012}}\n{{multiple image\n | perrow = 2\n | total_width = 400\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | image1            = United States vs New Zealand, 19 September, 2017 (36536441784).jpg\n | width1            =  \n | image2            = Nadia Com\u0103neci 2.jpg \n | width2            =  \n | image3            = 2008 LPGA Championship - Annika Sorenstam tee shot.jpg\n | width3            =  \n | image4            = Lenglen Wills Match of the Century 1926 2 (instant) (cropped).jpg\n | width4            =  \n | image5            = La Maga (4815861789).jpg\n | width5            = \n | image6            = Australia v England netball 2008.jpg\n | width6            =  \n | footer = [[United States women's national soccer team]]; Olympic gold medal gymnast [[Nadia Com\u0103neci]]; Hall of Fame golfer [[Annika S\u00f6renstam]]; Tennis players [[Suzanne Lenglen]] and [[Helen Wills]]; Legend of Hockey [[Luciana Aymar]]; [[Australia national netball team|Australia]] and [[England national netball team|England]] national [[netball]] teams\n}}\n\n{{Women in society sidebar}}\n\n'''Women's sports''', both amateur and [[women's professional sports|professional,]] have existed throughout the world for centuries in all varieties of [[sports]]. Female participation and popularity in sports increased dramatically in the 20th century, especially in the last quarter-century, reflecting changes in modern societies that emphasize '''[[gender]] parity.''' Although the level of participation and performance still varies greatly by [[country]] and by [[Sports|sport]], [[women]]'s sports are generally accepted throughout the world today.\n\nHowever, despite a rise in women's participation in sports, a large disparity in participation rates between [[Woman|women]] and [[Man|men]] remains.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/examination-of-gender-equity-and-female-participation-in-sport/ |title=Examination of Gender Equity and Female Participation in Sport |date=2016-02-26 |newspaper=The Sport Journal |access-date=2017-02-08 }}</ref> These disparities are prevalent globally and continue to hinder equality in sports. Many institutions and programs still remain conservative and do not contribute to gender equity in sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://athleteassessments.com/gender-equality-debate/|title=The Gender Equality Debate; Women in Sport|last=Hanson|first=Liz|date=2016-06-17|website=Athlete Assessments|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\nWomen who play sports face many obstacles today, such as lower pay, less media coverage, and different injuries compared to their male counterparts. Many female athletes have engaged in peaceful protests, such as playing strikes, social media campaigns, and even federal lawsuits to address these inequalities.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient civilizations===\n[[File:Villa romana bikini girls.JPG|thumb|Roman women engaged in sports. [[Mosaic]] at the [[Villa del Casale|Villa Romana del Casale]] near [[Piazza Armerina]] in [[Sicily]]]]\n[[File:Greek Runner Maiden 2.png|thumb|A statue of a victress of the Heraean Games, represented near the start of a race]]\nBefore each [[ancient Olympic Games]] there was a separate women's athletic event held at the same stadium in Olympia, the [[Heraean Games]],  dedicated to the goddess [[Hera]]. Myth held that the Heraea was founded by [[Hippodameia]], the wife of the king who founded the Olympics.<ref name=Scanlon>{{cite web |author=Scanlon, Thomas F. |title=Games for Girls |work=Ancient Olympics Guide |url=http://www.archaeology.org/online/features/olympics/girls.html |access-date=February 18, 2006}}</ref> According to E. Norman Gardiner:\n\n{{Quote| At the festival there were races for maidens of various ages. Their course was 500 feet, or one-sixth less than the men's stadium. The maidens ran with their hair down their backs, a short tunic reaching just below the knee, and their right shoulder bare to the breast. The victors received crowns of olive and a share of the heifer sacrificed to Hera. They had, too, the right of setting up their statues in the Heraeum.<ref>Gardiner, E. Norman, 'The Rise of the Athletic Festival' in ''Greek Athletic Sport and Festivals'', London:MacMillan, 1910, pp. 47\u201348</ref> }}\n\nthe art of cooking has belonged to women since the beginning of time  \n\nAlthough married women were excluded from the Olympics even as spectators, [[Cynisca]] won an Olympic game as owner of a chariot (champions of chariot races were owners not riders), as did [[Euryleonis]], [[Belistiche]], [[Polycrates of Argos|Zeuxo, Encrateia and Hermione]], Timareta, Theodota and Cassia.\n\nAfter the classical period, there was some participation by women in men's athletic festivals.<ref name=Scanlon/> Women in Sparta began to practice the same athletic exercises that men did, exhibiting the qualities of Spartan soldiers. Plato even supported women in sports by advocating running and sword-fighting for women.<ref>Swaddling, Judith. The Ancient Olympic Games. Austin: U of Texas, 1980. Print.</ref>\n\nNotably, cultural representations of a pronounced female physicality were not limited to sport in Ancient Greece and can also be found in representations of a group of warrioresses known as the [[Amazons]].\n\n===Early modern===\nDuring the [[Song dynasty|Song]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], and [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] dynasties, women played in professional [[Cuju]] teams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://features.cultural-china.com/cuju/index02.html |title=Cuju \u2013 Ancient Chinese Football |author= |date= |work=Cultural-China.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://features.cultural-china.com/cuju/ |title=Cuju \u2013 Ancient Chinese Football |author= |date= |work=Cultural-China.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Chujutu.jpg|thumb|Chinese ladies playing ''cuju'', by the [[Ming Dynasty]] painter [[Du Jin]]]] The first Olympic games in the modern era, which were in 1896 were not open to women, but since then the number of women who have participated in the Olympic games have increased dramatically.<ref>{{cite web |title=Women and Sport Commission |url=http://www.olympic.org/women-sport-commission |work=Olympic.org |access-date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===19th and early 20th centuries===\nThe educational committees of the [[French Revolution]] (1789) included intellectual, moral, and physical education for both girls and boys. With the victory of Napoleon less than twenty years later, physical education was reduced to military preparedness for boys and men. In Germany, the physical education of [[GutsMuths]] (1793) included girl's education. This included the measurement of performances of girls. This led to women's sport being more actively pursued in Germany than in most other countries.<ref>[[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (2003): ''Germany'', in: [[James Riordan]] & [[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (eds.): ''European Cultures in Sport. Examining the Nations and Regions''. Bristol: Intellect 2003, pp. 57 \u2013 88.</ref> When the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Sportive F\u00e9minine Internationale]] was formed as an all women's international organization it had a German male vice-president in addition to German international success in elite sports.\n\nWomen's sports in the late 1800s focused on correct posture, facial and bodily beauty, muscles, and health.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Padgett |first1=Jessica |title=The Issues of Women in Sport |url=http://serendip.brynmawr.edu/local/scisoc/sports02/papers/jpadgett.html |website=Serendip Studio |accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1870, activities for women were recreational rather than sport-specific in nature. They were noncompetitive, informal, rule-less; they emphasized physical activity rather than competition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Richard |title=A History of Women in Sport Prior to Title IX |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/a-history-of-women-in-sport-prior-to-title-ix/ |website=The Sport Journal |accessdate=7 April 2017|date=2008-03-14 }}</ref> Sports for women before the 20th century placed more emphasis on fitness rather than the competitive aspects we now associate with all sports.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/a-history-of-women-in-sport-prior-to-title-ix/ |title=A History of Women in Sport Prior to Title IX |date=2008-03-14 |newspaper=The Sport Journal |access-date=2017-02-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1916 the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) held its first national championship for women (in swimming),{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DWmCWO6SpsYC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=In+1916+the+Amateur+Athletic+Union+(AAU)+held+its+first+national+championship+for+women.#v=onepage&q=In%201916%20the%20Amateur%20Athletic%20Union%20(AAU)%20held%20its%20first%20national%20championship%20for%20women.&f=false |title=Outstanding Women Athletes: Who They are and how They Influenced Sports in America |last=Woolum |first=Janet |date=1998-01-01 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=9781573561204 }}</ref> In 1923 the AAU also sponsored the [[1923 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|First American Track & Field championships for women]]. Earlier that year the [[Women's Amateur Athletic Association]] (WAAA) held [[1923 WAAA Championships|the first WAAA Championships]].\n\nFew women competed in sports in Europe and North America before the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, as social changes favored increased female participation in society as equals with men. Although women were technically permitted to participate in many sports, relatively few did. There was often disapproval of those who did.\n\n\"Bicycling has done more to emancipate women than anything else in the world.\" [[Susan B. Anthony]] said \"I stand and rejoice every time I see a woman ride on a wheel. It gives women a feeling of freedom and self-reliance.\"\n\nThe modern [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] had female competitors from 1900 onward, though women at first participated in considerably fewer events than men. Women first made their appearance in the Olympic Games in Paris in 1900. That year, 22 women competed in tennis, sailing, croquet, equestrian, and golf.<ref>\"Equality for Women in the Olympics.\" Feminist Majority Foundation. Web. November 2014. http://www.feminist.org/sports/olympics.asp</ref>  As of the IOC-Congress in Paris 1914 a woman's medal had formally the same weight as a man's in the official medal table. This left the decisions about women's participation to the individual international sports federations.<ref>[[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]]: Forgotton Decisions. The IOC on the Eve of World War I, in: ''Olympika'' 6 (1997), 85 \u2013 98. <http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/Olympika/Olympika_1997/olympika0601g.pdf></ref> Concern over the physical strength and stamina of women led to the discouragement of female participation in more physically intensive sports, and in some cases led to less physically demanding female versions of male sports.  Thus [[netball]] was developed out of [[basketball]] and [[softball]] out of [[baseball]].\n\nIn response to the lack of support for women's international sport the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Sportive F\u00e9minine Internationale]] was founded in France by [[Alice Milliat]]. This organization initiated the Women's Olympiad (held [[1921 Women's Olympiad|1921]], [[1922 Women's Olympiad|1922]] and [[1923 Women's Olympiad|1923]]) and the [[Women's World Games]], which attracted participation of nearly 20 countries and was held four times ([[1922 Women's World Games|1922]], [[1926 Women's World Games|1926]], [[1930 Women's World Games|1930]] and [[1934 Women's World Games|1934]]).<ref name=\"LeighBonin\">{{Cite journal |last=Leigh |first=Mary H. |author2=Bonin, Th\u00e9r\u00e8se M. |title=The Pioneering Role Of Madame Alice Milliat and the FSFI in Establishing International Trade and Field Competition for Women |journal=Journal of Sport History |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=72\u201383 |year=1977 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1977/JSH0401/jsh0401f.pdf |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>  In 1924 the [[1924 Women's Olympiad]] was held at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in [[London]]. The [[International Olympic Committee]] began to incorporate greater participation of [[women at the Olympics]] in response. The number of Olympic women athletes increased over five-fold in the period, going from 65 at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] to 331 at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref>[http://www.olympic.org/antwerp-1920-summer-olympics Antwerp 1920]. IOC. Retrieved on 2014-01-11.</ref><ref>[http://www.olympic.org/berlin-1936-summer-olympics Berlin 1936]. IOC. Retrieved on 2014-01-11.</ref>\n\nMost early women's professional sports leagues foundered.  This is often attributed to a lack of spectator support.  Amateur competitions became the primary venue for women's sports. Throughout the mid-twentieth century, Communist countries dominated many [[Olympic sports]], including women's sports, due to state-sponsored athletic programs that were technically regarded as amateur.  The legacy of these programs endured, as former Communist countries continue to produce many of the top female athletes. Germany and Scandinavia also developed strong women's athletic programs in this period.\n<gallery caption=\"Women's sports in history\">\nFile:Bronze figure of a running girl, Greek, about 520-500 BC, Found at Prizren, Serbia, Winning at the ancient Games, British Museum (7667206370).jpg|A [[Spartan]] woman running. The bare right breast is indicative of her being an athlete.\nFile:1912 Fraulein Kussin Mrs Edwards boxing.jpg|Fraulein Kussinn and Mrs. Edwards boxing, 1912.\nFile:Camogie Team, Waterford, 17 October 1915.jpg|thumb|A [[camogie]] team posing with their hurling sticks, around 1915.\nFile:Bw 1920 competition medals.jpg|Young women wearing swimming competition medals, around 1920.\nFile:1910 to 1920 Sibyl Marston holding foil.jpg|Fencer Sibyl Marston holding a foil.\nFile:Time Cover in 1924-08-25.JPG|[[Edith Cummings]] was the first woman [[athletic sports|athlete]] to appear on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|Time magazine]], a major step in women's athletic history.\n</gallery>\n\n====United States====\n{{see also|Timeline of women's sports in the United States|National Collegiate Athletic Association}}\n{{multiple image |total_width=330\n|image1 = 2011 Okemos High School Girls' Water Polo State Championship Team.jpg\n|image2 = TWU Gymnastics (Bars) Amy Winczura (5694030475).jpg\n|footer = Women's sports is given very high priority in U.S. from school itself.<ref name=\"Empowering Women in Sports\">{{cite web |website=Femenist Majority Foundation |title=Empowering Women in Sports |url=http://www.feminist.org/research/sports/sports12.html}}</ref> Picture on left shows a U.S. high school girls' [[water polo]] team (with their male coaches in background) posing with their trophy. Picture on right shows a U.S. university girl practising a difficult [[gymnastics]] manoeuvre under the watchful eyes of her coach.}}{{Main|Title IX}}\n\n=====Implementation and regulation of Title IX=====\n\n====== Overview ======\nIn 1972 the [[United States Congress]] passed the Title IX legislation as a part of the additional Amendment Act to the 1964 Civil Rights Act.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\">{{cite book|title=A Sporting Chance: Sports and Genders|last=Steiner|first=Andy|year=1995}}</ref> Title IX states that: \"no person shall on the basis of sex, be excluded from participating in, be denied benefits of, or be subjected to discrimination under any educational programs or activities receiving federal financial assistance...\";<ref name=\"Greenburg_1997\">{{cite book|title=Getting into the Game: Women and Sports|last=Greenburg|first=Judith E.|publisher=Franklin Watts|year=1997|location=New York}}</ref> in other words, Title IX prohibits gender discrimination in schools that receive federal funds through grants, scholarships, or other support for students. The law states that federal funds can be withdrawn from a school engaging in intentional gender discrimination in the provision of curriculum, counseling, academic support, or general educational opportunities; this includes interscholastic or varsity sports.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sports in Society|last=Coakley|first=Jay|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2007|location=New York|page=238}}</ref> This law from the Education Act requires that both male and female athletes have equal facilities and equal benefits. The equal benefits are the necessities such as equal equipment, uniforms, supplies, training, practice, quality in coaches and opponents, awards, cheerleaders and bands at the game.<ref name=\"Greenburg_1997\" /> In 1979, there was a policy interpretation that offered three ways in which schools could be compliant with Title IX; it became known as the \"three-part test\".\n\n# Providing athletic participation opportunities that are substantially proportionate to the student enrollment. This prong of the test is satisfied when participation opportunities for men and women are \"substantially proportionate\" to their respective undergraduate enrollment.\n# Demonstrating a continual expansion of athletic opportunities for the underrepresented sex. This prong of the test is satisfied when an institution has a history and continuing practice of program expansion that is responsive to the developing interests and abilities of the underrepresented sex (typically female).\n# Accommodating the interest and ability of the underrepresented sex. This prong of the test is satisfied when an institution is meeting the interests and abilities of its female students even where there are disproportionately fewer females than males participating in sports.\n\n====== Room for improvement ======\nAlthough schools only have to be compliant with one of the three prongs, a 1999 study by Sigelman and Wahlbeck found that many schools are \"nowhere near compliance\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sigelman|first=Lee|last2=Wahlbeck|first2=Paul|date=1999|title=Gender Proportionality in Intercollegiate Athletics: The Mathematics of Title IX Compliance|journal=Social Science Quarterly|volume=80|issue=3|pages=518\u2013538|jstor=42863927}}</ref> Many schools attempt to achieve compliance through the first prong; however, in order to achieve that compliance schools cut men's programs, which is not the way the OCR wanted compliance achieved.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Irons|first=Alicia|date=Spring 2006|title=The Economic Inefficiency of Title IX|url=http://business.uni.edu/economics/Themes/irons.pdf|journal=Major Themes in Economics|access-date=April 17, 2012}}</ref> Equity is not the only way to be compliant with Title IX; athletic departments need to show that they are making efforts to achieve parity in participation, treatment, and athletic financial assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacwaa.org/advocacy/title-ix/information|title=Title IX Information|access-date=April 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to research done by National Women's Law Center in 2011, 4500 public high schools across the nation have extremely high gender inequality and are violating the Title IX laws.<ref name=\"auto\">Wong, A. (2015, June 26). Where Girls Are Missing Out on High-School Sports. Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2015/06/girls-high-school-sports-inequality/396782/</nowiki></ref> According to further research done by the Women's Law Center, schools with a high number of minority students and a greater number of people of color mainly in southern states had a much higher rate of gender disparity. There is also a huge disparity regarding sport related scholarships for men and women, with men getting 190 million more in funding than women.<ref name=\":2\">Wallace, K. (2016, March 14). The real March Madness: When will women's teams get equal buzz? Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/30/living/feat-march-madness-womens-sports-attention-money-men/</nowiki></ref> This pattern has persisted over a long period of time as, most colleges focus on their male athletics team and plow more money into them. This disparity shows the link between race and gender, and how it plays a significant role in the hierarchy of sports.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n=====Effect of Title IX on women's sports=====\n\n====== Participation in sports ======\nThe main objective of Title IX is to make sure there is equal treatment in sports and school, regardless of sex, in a federally funded program. It was also used to provide protection to those who are being discriminated due to their gender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/cor/coord/titleix.php|publisher=The United States Department of Judgement|access-date=November 12, 2013}}</ref>  However, Title IX is most commonly associated with its impact on athletics and more specifically the impact it has had on women's participation in athletics at every age. Title IX has allowed women and girls in educational institutions to increase their opportunity in different sports they are able to play now.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Proxy Services {{!}} St. Ambrose University, Davenport, Iowa|id = {{ProQuest|1081454393}}}}</ref> Today{{When|date=April 2017}} there are more females participating in athletics than ever before. As of the 2007\u20132008 school year, females made up 41% of the participants in college athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aauw.org/act/laf/library/athleticStatistics.cfm|title=Title IX Athletic Statistics|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114061928/http://www.aauw.org/act/laf/library/athleticStatistics.cfm|archivedate=November 14, 2011|accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref> To see the growth of women's sports, consider the difference in participation before the passing of Title IX and today. In 1971\u20131972 there were 294,015 females participating in high school athletics and in 2007\u20132008 there were over three million females participating, meaning there has been a 940% increase in female participation in high school athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIn 1971\u20131972 there were 29,972 females participating in college athletics and in 2007\u20132008 there were 166,728 females participating, a 456% increase in female participation in college athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> In 1971, less than 300,000 females played in high school sports. After the law was passed many females started to get involved in sports. By 1990, eighteen years later, 1.9 million female high school students were playing sports.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\" /> Increased participation in sports has had a direct impact on other areas of women's lives; these effects can be seen in women's education and employment later on in life; a 2010 study found that the changes set in motion by Title IX explained about 20 percent of the increase in women's education and about 40 percent of the rise in employment for 25-to-34-year-old women.<ref name=\"parker1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/16/health/16well.html|title=As Girls Become Women, Sports Pay Dividends|last=Parker-Pope|first=Tara|date=February 16, 2010|work=New York Times|access-date=February 16, 2012}}</ref> This is not to say that all women who are successful later on in life played sports, but it is saying that women who did participate in athletics received benefits in their education and employment later on in life.<ref name=\"parker1\" />\n\nIn 1971, fewer than 295,000 girls participated in high school varsity athletics, accounting for just 7 percent of all varsity athletes; in 2001, that number leaped to 2.8 million, or 41.5 percent of all varsity athletes, according to the National Coalition for Women and Girls in Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncwge.org/|title=The National Coalition for Women and Girls in Education|website=www.ncwge.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> In 1966, 16,000 females competed in intercollegiate athletics. By 2001, that number jumped to more than 150,000, accounting for 43 percent of all college athletes. In addition, a 2008 study of intercollegiate athletics showed that women's collegiate sports had grown to 9,101 teams, or 8.65 per school. The five most frequently offered college sports for women are, in order: (1) basketball, 98.8% of schools have a team, (2) volleyball, 95.7%, (3) soccer, 92.0%, (4) cross country, 90.8%, and (5) softball, 89.2%. Since 1972, women have also competed in the traditional male sports of wrestling, weightlifting, rugby, and boxing. An article in the ''New York Times'' found that there are lasting benefits for women from Title IX: participation in sports increased education as well as employment opportunities for girls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/16/health/16well.html|title=From Title IX, Evidence of Sports' Lasting Effects|last=Parker-Pope|first=Tara|date=2010-02-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Furthermore, the athletic participation by girls and women spurred by Title IX was associated with lower obesity rates. No other public health program can claim similar success.<ref name=\"gilderlehrman.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/history-by-era/seventies/essays/impact-title-ix|title=The Impact of Title IX &#124; The Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History|last=Winslow|first=Barbara|date=|publisher=Gilderlehrman.org|access-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====== Participation in leadership roles ======\nAlthough female participation in sports has increased due to Title IX, there has not been a similar effect in terms of women holding coaching or other managerial positions in sports. Most sport teams or institutions, regardless of gender, are managed by male coaches and managers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kimelsesser/2019/03/01/heres-why-womens-teams-are-coached-by-men/#22ad3566b3f9|title=Here's Why Women's Teams Are Coached by Men|last=Elsesser|first=Kim|date=March 1, 2019|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> For example, according to 2016 data, 33% of WNBA teams are led by women coaches or managers.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\">{{cite web|url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/examination-of-gender-equity-and-female-participation-in-sport/|title=Examination of Gender Equity and Female Participation in Sport|author=Senne|date=February 26, 2016|work=TheSportJournal.org|access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> The International Olympic Committee also consists of 20% female members.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\" /> The data presented also showed that 15% of athletic directors in colleges nationwide were females, and that number is much less in the southern states.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\" /> There are various reasons that have been suggested to account for this trend. Messner and Bozada-Deas (2009) suggest traditional gender roles may play a role and that society's historical division of labor leads to men volunteering as team coaches and women volunteering as team \"moms\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Messner|first=Michael|last2=Suzel|first2=Bozada-Deas|date=2009|title=Separating the Men from the Moms: The Making of Adult Gender Segregation in Youth Sports|url=http://www.michaelmessner.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/menfrommoms.pdf|journal=Gender & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=49\u201371|doi=10.1177/0891243208327363|via=}}</ref> Everhart and Chelladurai (1998) show that this phenomenon may be part of a larger cycle --- girls who are coached by men growing up are less likely to view themselves as coaches when they are adults, and so the number of female coaches decreases, meaning more girls are coached by men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Everhart|first=C. Bonnie|last2=Chelladurai|first2=Packianathan|date=1998|title=Gender Differences in Preferences for Coaching as an Occupation: The Role of Self-Efficacy, Valence, and Perceived Barriers|url=|journal=Research Quarterly for Exercise and Sport|volume=69|issue=2|pages=188\u2013200|doi=10.1080/02701367.1998.10607683|pmid=9635332}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carty |first1=Victoria |title=Textual Portrayals of Female Athletes: Liberation of Nuanced Forms of Patriarchy? |journal=Frontiers: A Journal of Women Studies |date=2005 |volume=26 |pages=132-155 |url=www.jstor.org/stable/4137402 |accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\n{{main|History of Canadian women}}\n[[File:Canada Summer Games by Steve Carmichael - Womens Volleyball 03.jpg|thumb|Women's [[volleyball]] at Canada Summer Games, 2017.]]\n\nSports are a high priority in Canadian culture, but women were long relegated to second-class status. There were also regional differences, with the eastern provinces emphasizing a more feminine \"girls rule\" game of basketball, while the Western provinces preferred identical rules.  Girls' and women's sport have traditionally been slowed down by a series of factors: both historically have low levels of interest and participation.  There were very few women in leadership positions in academic administration, student affairs or athletics and not many female coaches.  The media strongly emphasized men's sports as a demonstration of masculinity, suggesting that women seriously interested in sports were crossing gender lines with the male sports establishment actively hostile. Staunch feminists dismissed sports and thought of them as unworthy of their support. Women's progress was uphill; they first had to counter the common notion that women's bodies were restricted and delicate and that vigorous physical activity was dangerous. These notions where first challenged by the \"new women\" around 1900. These women started with bicycling; they rode into new gender spaces in education, work, and suffrage. The 1920s marked a breakthrough for women, including working-class young women in addition to the pioneering middle class sportswomen.<ref>M. Ann Hall, ''The Girl and the Game: A History of Women's Sport in Canada'' (Broadview Press, 2002)</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{main|Sport in the United Kingdom}}\nThe [[United Kingdom]] has produced a range of major international sports including: association football, rugby (union and league), cricket, netball, darts, golf, tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, bowls, rounders, modern rowing, hockey, boxing, snooker, billiards, and curling.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nauright |first1=John |last2=Parrish |first2=Charles |title=Sports around the World: History, Culture, and Practice |date=2012 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781598843019 |pages=169}}</ref> In the 19th century, women primarily participated in the \"new games\" which included golf, lawn tennis, cycling, and hockey. Now, women also participate at a professional/international level in football, rugby, cricket, and netball.\n\nSince the late 1980s, Women In Sport,<ref>{{cite web |title=Women In Sport |url=https://www.womeninsport.org |website=Women In Sport |publisher=Charities Commission |accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> a non-profit organization, has hoped to transform sport for the benefit of women and girls in the UK. Based in London, the organization's mission is to \"champion the right of every woman and girl in the UK to take part in, and benefit from, sport: from the field of play to the boardroom, from early years and throughout her life\".\n\nThe [[Henley Royal Regatta]], just recently allowed women to compete at this prestigious rowing race. Although, the benefits that men receive at this race versus what women receive is still drastically different, there is progress within allowing women to compete competitively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2018/07/03/henley-royal-regatta-celebrates-move-towards-gender-equality/|title=Henley Royal Regatta celebrates further move towards gender equality with bump for women's races|last=Quarrell|first=Rachel|date=2018-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-08|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n===1960s to 2010s===\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2012}}\nBefore the 1960s, in the early 1800s women romped, skated, played ball games and some even boxed. It wasn't until the late 1900s when women started participating in organized sports. After the civil war wealthy women started playing country club sports such as golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/sports/0|title=Sports {{!}} The Reader's Companion to U.S. Women's History - Credo Reference|website=search.credoreference.com|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\nOver the last fifty years, women's sports have developed substantially and made significant progress.\n\nTennis was a popular professional female sport from the 1970s onward, and it provided the occasion for a symbolic \"[[Battle of the Sexes (tennis)|battle of the sexes]]\" between [[Billie Jean King]] and [[Bobby Riggs]], which King won, thus enhancing the profile of female athletics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Maureen|date=2006|title=Reviewed Work: Billie Jean King: Portrait of a Pioneer|journal=Journal of Sport History|volume=33|issue=1|pages=113\u2013117|jstor=43610465}}</ref> [[Serena]] and [[Venus Williams]] were able to bring a strong female representation to sports. The sisters were both very successful with their accomplishments playing tennis and were able to set a strong positive model for other female tennis players and athletes as a whole. The two faced many obstacles along their journey to success, as they are African American women successfully conquering a predominately white sport. They were critiqued for their personal upbringings, their muscular builds, and the clothes they wore. James McKay and Helen Johnson described them as \"Ghetto Cinderellas,\" because of those very factors. Although they were not like other females playing sports, the women were able to bring a powerful new meaning and image to female athletics. Facing the challenges of racial and gender discrimination, the sisters enhanced and modeled a strong representation of both.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McKay |first1=James |last2=Johnson |first2=Helen |title=Pornographic Eroticism and Sexual Grotesquerie in Representations of African American Sportswomen |journal=Social Identities |date=November 4, 2008 |volume=14 |page=491-504}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of women's professional tennis in the 1970s, [[Women's professional sports|women's professional team sports]] did not achieve prominence until the 1990s, particularly in [[basketball]] and [[football (soccer)]], when the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] was formed and the first [[FIFA Women's World Cup|Women's World Cup]]s and women's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic soccer]] matches were held.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.pov.org/trueheartedvixens/timeline/|title=A Brief History of Women's Team Sports in America|last=American Documentary Inc.|date=2001-01-17|website=Archive.POV.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:USWNT Celebrates.jpg|thumb|The United States Women's National Soccer Team celebrating their 2012 CONCACAF Olympic Qualifiers Tournament championship.]]\nIn 1999, at the [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]] in [[Pasadena, California]], after scoring the fifth kick in the [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalty shootout]] to give the United States the win over [[China women's national football team|China]] in the final game, [[Brandi Chastain]] celebrated by spontaneously taking off her jersey and falling to her knees in a [[sports bra]].<ref name=\"Distillations\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|date=2017|title=Women's work|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/womens-work|journal=Distillations|volume=3|issue=1|pages=6\u201311|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> While removing a jersey in celebration of a goal was common in men's soccer, it was highly unusual in women's football at the international level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-27189681|title=Why Women's World Cup champion Brandi Chastain bared her bra|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=July 13, 2014|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The image of her celebration has been considered one of the more famous and controversial photographs of a woman celebrating an athletic victory.<ref name=\"Longman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/05/sports/soccer-the-sports-bra-seen-round-the-world.html|title=The Sports Bra Seen Round the World|author=Jere Longman|date=July 5, 2003|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/main/photos/1212/100-greatest-sports-photos-of-all-time-final/14 100 Greatest Sports Photos of All Time #14]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/07/05/brandi-chastains-sports-bra-changed-womens-soccer-womens-history-years-ago/|title=Brandi Chastain's sports bra changed women's soccer - and women's history - 20 years ago|last=Rosenwald|first=Michael S.|date=July 7, 2019|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, it was announced that a statue of Chastain's celebration would be displayed at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] to commemorate the twenty-year anniversary of the team's win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/rose-bowl-stadium-unveils-bronze-statue-of-brandi-chastains-1999-world-cup-celebration/|title=Rose Bowl Stadium unveils bronze statue of Brandi Chastain's 1999 World Cup celebration|last=Benjamin|first=Cody|date=July 11, 2019|website=CBS Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nToday, women and girls compete professionally and as amateurs in virtually every major sport, though girls' participation in sports may be higher in the United States than in other places like Western Europe and Latin America.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=J.|last2=Hardman|first2=K.|date=2016-07-24|title=The State and Status of Physical Education in Schools in International Context|journal=[[European Physical Education Review]]|volume=6|issue=3|pages=203\u2013229|doi=10.1177/1356336x000063001}}</ref>  Additionally, the level of girls' participation typically decreases when it comes to the more violent contact sports in which boys overwhelmingly outnumber girls, particularly football,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/well/family/football-girls-concussions.html|title=More Girls Are Playing Football. Is That Progress?|last=de la Cretaz|first=Britni|date=February 2, 2018|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> wrestling,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/more-high-school-girls-are-wrestling-but-theyre-still-grappling-for-respect/2017/02/10/de00814a-e7ee-11e6-bf6f-301b6b443624_story.html|title=More high school girls are wrestling, but they're still grappling for respect|last=Needelman|first=Joshua|date=February 10, 2017|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> and boxing.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} (Some leagues for girls do exist, however, such as the [[Utah Girls Football League]] and [[Professional Girl Wrestling Association]].) These typical non-participation habits may slowly be evolving as more women participate in stereotypical male sports; for example, [[Katie Hnida]] became the first woman ever to score points in a [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[NCAA]] [[American football]] game when she kicked two [[Conversion (gridiron football)|extra points]] for the [[New Mexico Lobos football|University of New Mexico]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/katie-hnida-is-first-woman-to-play-in-division-i-football-game|title=Katie Hnida is first woman to play in Division I football game|date=November 16, 2009|website=History.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Heather Watson]] and [[Fu Yuanhui]] broke one of the last taboos in women's sport when both openly admitted they were menstruating, Watson after a self-described poor performance in a tennis match in 2015, and Fu at the Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paula Cocozza |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/shortcuts/2015/jan/21/menstruation-last-great-sporting-taboo |title=Menstruation: the last great sporting taboo &#124; Sport |newspaper=The Guardian |date= 2015-01-21|access-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-37081669 |title=Rio 2016: Support as China's Fu Yuanhui breaks period taboo |first=Helier |last=Cheung |date=August 15, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=April 14, 2017 |via=www.BBC.co.uk|work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n== Professional sports ==\n{{Main|Women's professional sports}}\n\n=== Overview ===\n[[Professional sports]] refers to sports in which athletes are paid for their performance. Opportunities for women to play professional sports vary by country. Some women's professional sports leagues are directly affiliated with a men's professional sports league (like the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/howardmegdal/2018/11/19/wnba-cba-adam-silver-terri-jackson-discuss-stakes-and-the-grand-bargain/#58a36d495b7b|title=WNBA CBA Negotiations|last=Megdal|first=Howard|date=November 19, 2018|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>); others are independently owned and operated (like the [[National Women's Hockey League|NWHL]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/4/2/18291437/the-cwhl-folded-now-what-happens-to-womens-hockey-in-canada|title=The CWHL folded - now what happens to women's hockey in Canada?|last=Jay|first=Michelle|date=April 2, 2019|website=The Ice Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>).\n\nWhile women today do have the opportunity to play professional sports, the pay for [[women's professional sports]] is significantly lower than for men's,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kosofsky|first=Syda|date=1993|title=Toward Gender Equality in Professional Sports|url=https://repository.uchastings.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1029&context=hwlj|journal=Hastings Women's Law Journal|volume=4|issue=2|pages=213\u2013214|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/11/sports/us-womens-soccer-pay.html|title=The Long Fight for Pay Equality in Sports|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=March 11, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> a phenomenon known as the [[gender pay gap in sports]]. Many female professional athletes hold second jobs in addition to playing their respective sports due to their low salaries.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2015/0621/Outside-World-Cup-women-pro-soccer-players-struggle-to-make-ends-meet|title=Outside World Cup, women pro soccer players struggle to make ends meet|journal=Christian Science Monitor|last=Gass|first=Henry|date=June 21, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/making-a-living-as-womens-pro-soccer-player-is-no-easy-task/|title=Why making a living as a women's pro soccer player is no easy task|last=Giambalvo|first=Emily|date=July 10, 2017|website=Seattle Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grandstandcentral.com/2019/sections/gender/when-professional-hockey-is-your-side-hustle/|title=When professional hockey is your side hustle|last=Varriano|first=Anthony|date=March 15, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Female professional athletes play in lower-quality, smaller facilities than male professional athletes and generally have lower fan attendance at games or matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/the-avenue/2019/03/22/when-it-comes-to-sports-men-and-women-dont-play-on-the-same-fields/|title=When it comes to sports, men and women don't play on the same fields|last=Schuetz|first=Jenny|date=March 25, 2019|website=Brookings|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenintheworld.com/2015/07/09/why-you-should-think-twice-about-ignoring-womens-sports/|title=Why you should think twice about ignoring women's sports|last=Iversen|first=Katja|date=July 9, 2015|website=Women in the World|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> Many women's professional sports are not regularly broadcast on live television like many men's professional sports,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooky|first=Cheryl|last2=Messner|first2=Michael A.|last3=Hextrum|first3=Robin H.|date=April 4, 2013|title=Women Play Sport, But Not on TV: A Longitudinal Study of Televised News Media|journal=Communication and Sport|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1177/2167479513476947|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a7f3c72db565618d35a7188a1b274631aae218b8}}</ref> but are live-streamed on platforms such as [[Twitter]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-announces-20-game-twitter-livestream-schedule-for-2019-season/|title=WNBA Announces 20-Game Twitter Livestream Schedule for 2019 Season|last=|first=|date=May 1, 2019|website=WNBA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> or [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/nwhl-signs-three-year-streaming-deal-with-twitch-receives-broadcasting-rights-fee|title=NWHL signs three-year streaming deal with Twitch|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=September 5, 2019|website=The Hockey News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> instead.\n\nNot only do female athletes themselves face inequality, but so too do women looking to enter the business side of sports. Research has shown that women occupy leadership positions in sports business at a lower rate than men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burton|first=Laura|date=May 2015|title=Underrepresentation of women in sport leadership: A review of research|journal=Sport Management Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=155\u2013165|doi=10.1016/j.smr.2014.02.004}}</ref> When women ''do'' occupy the same positions as men, they may be paid less,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Humphreys|first=Brad R.|date=August 2000|title=Equal Pay on the Hardwood: The Earnings Gap Between Male and Female NCAA Division I Basketball Coaches|journal=Journal of Sports Economics|volume=1|issue=2|pages=299\u2013307|doi=10.1177/152700250000100306|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/694dc115d425dce85b433f60b19dbd3b7443805c}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Osborne|first=Barbara|last2=Yarbrough|first2=Marilyn V.|date=2000|title=Pay Equity for Coaches and Athletic Administrators: An Element of Title IX?|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1469&context=mjlr|journal=University of Michigan Journal of Law Reform|volume=34|issue=1|pages=231\u2013251|via=}}</ref> although some research has shown revenue-specific variables may be more relevant than gender-specific variables when examining compensation levels.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Traugutt|first=Alex|last2=Sellars|first2=Nicole|last3=Morse|first3=Alan L.|date=April 2018|title=Salary Disparities Between Male and Female Head Coaches: An Investigation of the NCAA Power Five Conferences|url=https://digitalcommons.kent.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1054&context=sport|journal=The Journal of SPORT|volume=6|issue=1|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough several professional women's sports leagues have been established throughout the world in the post-Title IX era, they are generally behind in terms of exposure, funding, and attendance compared to the men's teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-xpm-2014-feb-10-la-sp-womens-sports-leagues-20140211-story.html|title=Women's pro sports leagues have trouble staying in the game|last=Rohlin|first=Melissa|last2=Baxter|first2=Kevin|date=February 10, 2014|website=LA Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fink|first=Janet|date=2015|title=Female athletes, women's sport, and the sport media commercial complex: Have we really \"come a long way, baby\"?|journal=Sport Management Review|volume=18|issue=3|pages=331\u2013342|doi=10.1016/j.smr.2014.05.001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliviaabrams/2019/06/23/why-female-athletes-earn-less-than-men-across-most-sports/#1ba69a2d40fb|title=Why Female Athletes Earn Less Than Men Across Most Sports|last=Abrams|first=Olivia|date=June 23, 2019|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> However, there are notable exceptions. The 2015 Women's World Cup final was the most-watched soccer game ever in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/07/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-final-was-most-watched-soccer-game-in-united-states-history.html|title=Women's World Cup Final Was Most-Watched Soccer Game in United States History|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=July 6, 2015|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2015}}</ref> And in 2017, [[Portland Thorns FC]] of the [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]] had higher average attendance than several men's professional teams, including 15 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] teams, 13 [[National Hockey League|NHL]] teams, and 1 [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/13/sports/soccer/portland-thorns-nwsl.html|title=A Blueprint for Women's Sports Success - But Can It Be Copied?|last=Murray|first=Caitlin|date=October 13, 2017|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The Thorns' 2019 season saw an even higher average attendance of 20,098.<ref>{{cite web|title=2019 NWSL Attendance|url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2019-nwsl-attendance/ |publisher=Soccer Stadium Digest |date=October 12, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> This was higher than all but one of the 30 NBA teams in the 2018\u201319 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/attendance/_/year/2019 |title=NBA Attendance Report \u2013 2019 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> all but three of the 31 NHL teams in the 2018\u201319 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nhl/attendance/_/year/2019 |title=NHL Attendance Report \u2013 2019 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> 15 of the 24 MLS teams in the 2019 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=2019 MLS Attendance|url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2019-mls-attendance/ |publisher=Soccer Stadium Digest |date=October 6, 2019 |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> and 6 of the 30 MLB teams in the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2019-misc.shtml |title=2019 MLB Attendance & Team Age |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Active women's professional leagues and associations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Country\n!Sport\n!League or Association Name\n|-\n|Australia\n|Australian rules football\n|[[AFL Women's]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's National Basketball League]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Golf\n|[[ALPG Tour]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Netball\n|[[Suncorp Super Netball]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Association football\n|[[W-League (Australia)|Westfield W-League]]\n|-\n|China\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's Chinese Basketball Association]]\n|-\n|China\n|Golf\n|[[China LPGA Tour]]\n|-\n|Denmark\n|Handball\n|[[Danish Women's Handball League|HTH Ligaen]]\n|-\n|England\n|Association football\n|[[FA Women's Super League]]\n|-\n|Europe\n|Golf\n|[[Ladies European Tour]]\n|-\n|France\n|Association football\n|[[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]]\n|-\n|Germany\n|Association football\n|[[Frauen-Bundesliga]]\n|-\n|Japan\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA of Japan Tour]]\n|-\n|Mexico\n|Association football\n|[[Liga MX Femenil]]\n|-\n|New Zealand\n|Netball\n|[[ANZ Premiership]]\n|-\n|Russia\n|Basketball\n|[[Russian Women's Basketball Premier League]]\n|-\n|South Korea\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA of Korea Tour]]\n|-\n|Turkey\n|Volleyball\n|[[Turkish Women's Volleyball League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's National Basketball Association]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA|Ladies Professional Golf Association]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[Legends Tour]] (age 45 and over)\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[Symetra Tour]] (second-tier tour)\n|-\n|USA\n|Ice hockey\n|[[National Women's Hockey League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Lacrosse\n|[[Women's Professional Lacrosse League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Lacrosse\n|[[United Women's Lacrosse League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Association football\n|[[National Women's Soccer League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Softball\n|[[National Pro Fastpitch]]\n|-\n| Worldwide\n| Tennis\n| [[Women's Tennis Association]]\n|}\n\n==Battle for equality==\n<!-- [[Gender and sport]] redirects here. The anchor insulates against section title changes, please do not remove it. -->\nThe [[2012 London Olympics]] were the first games of their kind in which women competed in every sport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/london-2012-is-this-the-womens-olympics |title=London 2012: was this the women's Olympics? \u2013 Channel 4 News |publisher=Channel4.com |date=2012-08-12 |access-date=2016-03-24}}</ref> The fight for women to gain equality on national levels and in professional leagues, in terms of pay and better funding, has continued; however sports still remain dominated by men, financially and globally. Gender remains a selective and primary factor in terms of determining if women are able-bodied as men and if they should get the same treatment in terms of sports.<ref>Henne, K. (2014). The \"Science\" of Fair Play in Sport: Gender and the Politics of Testing. ''Signs: Journal of Women in Culture & Society'', ''39''(3), 787\u2013812.</ref> It is often said{{By whom|date=April 2017}} that sports are a thing for men, and has become a stereotypical notion within society. Negative gender-based characteristics such as masculinity and femininity have been described as the deciding factor in order to play sports, and has often been held as justifiable dismissing sports equity.<ref>Spaaij, R., Farquharson, K., & Marjoribanks, T. (2015). Sport and Social Inequalities. ''Sociology Compass'', ''9''(5), 400\u2013411. doi:10.1111/soc4.12254</ref> Although there are various purposes and outcomes of organized teamsport participation in Western cultures, a consistent finding is that sport is principally organized around the political project of physically and symbolically elevating men over women [1]. There was evidence throughout the study that notions of audience interest or preference were based on personal beliefs and assumptions\u2014rather than evidence or research\u2014and in some cases it was clear that these beliefs and assumptions still prioritized the coverage of men's professional sports.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Lauren J.|last2=Anderson|first2=Eric|date=2016-09-02|title=The influence of gender segregation and teamsport experience on occupational discrimination in sport-based employment|journal=Journal of Gender Studies|language=en|volume=25|issue=5|pages=586\u2013598|doi=10.1080/09589236.2015.1070712|issn=0958-9236}}</ref>\n\nThe pay gap in women sports is a controversial issue.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Women athletes, in their respective fields, are often get paid far less than their male counterparts, and this has been true for a long  time. The difference between the American men's and women's soccer teams' salaries serves as an example regarding pay inequality.  Women on the U.S national team earned $99,000 per year, while men earned $263,320 if they were to win 20 exhibition matches.<ref name=\"auto2\">WALTERS, J. (2016, April 1). TAKING A CLOSER LOOK AT THE GENDER PAY GAP IN SPORTS. Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>http://www.newsweek.com/womens-soccer-suit-underscores-sports-gender-pay-gap-443137</nowiki></ref> There is a substantial gap in rewards in regards to winning the [[FIFA World Cup]]. The German men's national team earned 35 million dollars, while the American women's national team earned 2 million dollars after winning the World Cup.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The battle in equality for fair pay divulges in to other sports in which men earn far more than women. Golf is another sport which has a significant rising female presence. In 2014, the [[PGA Tour|PGA tour]] awarded US$340 million in prize money for men's tournaments, compared to 62 million dollars awarded to the [[LPGA|LPGA Tour]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|author=Brennan, A.|date=May 5, 2016|title=Which Sports Have The Largest And Smallest Pay Gaps?|access-date=January 23, 2017|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewbrennan/2016/05/05/the-pay-discrimination-in-sports-we-wish-didnt-exist-will-only-dissipate-with-womens-leadership/#48f31f9941d6}}</ref> Basketball is another sport which has surged in popularity in the last few decades and has significant female presence. In the United States, the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] organizes top-level professional basketball competition for both sexes, with men playing in the NBA proper and women in the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]. A WNBA player's minimum salary is $38,000, while an NBA player's minimum salary is $525,000.<ref name=\":3\" /> An average NBA player makes over $5 million while an average WNBA player makes $72,000.<ref name=\":2\" /> Male athletes generate more revenue for their teams. However, when one compares the revenue earned to salary received, women athletes often get an extremely low{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}} salary in comparison to the revenue they generate and their accomplishments. Although female athletes have come a long way since the establishment of professional sports, they still remain far behind in terms of pay (and ticket sales) and media coverage.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nIn September 2018, the [[World Surf League]] announced equal pay for both male and female athletes for all events. This decision has contributed to the conversation in the world of professional sports surrounding equality .\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn September 2015, the [[Australia women's national soccer team|Australian women's national soccer team]] (nicknamed the Matildas) announced that it had canceled a sold-out tour of the United States due to a dispute with the [[Football Federation Australia|Football Federation of Australia]] (FFA) over their pay. Their salary was below [[Minimum wage law|minimum wage]] levels in Australia. The Matildas requested health care, [[Parental leave|maternity leave]], and improved travel arrangements, as well as an increased salary. The players also said that their low salaries forced them to remain living at home, since they could not afford rent, and their strict training schedule meant they were unable to get another job.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/football/australia-matildas-women-soccer-pay/index.html|title=Australian women's soccer team boycott sell-out U.S. tour over pay|last=McCafferty|first=Georgia|date=September 11, 2015|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/09/12/matildas-boycott-us-tour-as-they-call-foul-on-gender-pay-gap.html|title=Matildas boycott US tour as they call foul on gender pay gap|last=Smyth|first=Jamie|date=September 12, 2015|website=CNBC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, a new pay deal was announced for players in Australia's national soccer league, the [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]]. The deal included an increase in wages, an increase in the salary cap, improved medical standards, and a formal maternity policy. Some commentators have attributed the success of the new W-League deal to the Matildas' boycott in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/11/w-league-breaks-new-ground-with-pay-deal-for-trailblazers-of-womens-sport|title=W-League breaks new ground with pay deal for 'trailblazers' of women's sport|last=Australian Associated Press|date=September 10, 2017|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/wleague-ffa-and-pfa-unveil-new-pay-deal-for-womens-soccer/news-story/ee0dcf9abb601663ee67dcb3f308253a|title=W-League, FFA and PFA unveil new pay deal for women's soccer|last=Gatt|first=Ray|date=September 12, 2017|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the FFA announced a new contract with the union [[Professional Footballers Australia]] (PFA) in which the Matildas and the [[Australia national soccer team|men's national team]] (the Caltex Socceroos) will receive equal shares of total player revenue and equal resources. In addition, the guaranteed minimum salary for a player on the Matildas will increase as a result of this deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/06/sports/soccer/australia-soccer-matildas-equal-pay.html|title=Australian Women and Men's Soccer Teams Reach Deal to Close Pay Gap|last=Zraick|first=Karen|date=November 6, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== China ===\nOne of the earliest examples of women's sports in modern China was [[Qiu Jin]]. Qiu Jin, a Chinese revolutionary during the late 1800s and early 1900s, trained women to be soldiers alongside men in sports societies. They were taught fencing, riding, and gymnastics.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Freeing the female body : inspirational icons|author=Mangan, J. A.|author2=Fan, Hong|date=2001|publisher=F. Cass|isbn=0714650889|location=London|oclc=45363183}}</ref> According to Susan Bronwell, the most important moment for women's sports in China came in 1981 with a Chinese victory in the [[1981 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1981 FIVB Women's World Cup]] in Tokyo, Japan. This victory made the female volleyball players household names in China, though the victory was portrayed as the work of leading male government officials like Ma Qiwei, [[He Long]], and [[Zhou Enlai]], who helped contribute at various stages to the success of the team. The victory symbolized a growth of women's sports in China after the [[Cultural Revolution]] of the 1960s and 1970s, wherein many athletes were suppressed:<ref>{{Cite book|title=Beijing's games : what the Olympics mean to China|last=Brownell, Susan.|date=2008|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780742556409|location=Lanham, Md.|oclc=173243758|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beijingsgames00brow}}</ref>\n{{Block quote|text=In the years following the women's volleyball victory, female athletes generally had greater success in international sports than males, and so they became the symbolic figureheads in the revival of Chinese nationalism.|sign=Susan Bronwell|source=Beijing's Games, Pg. 107}}\n[[File:London 2012 Olympics 052 Basketball Arena (2) China (7682998022).jpg|thumb|The Chinese women's basketball team prepares to compete at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.]]\nContemporary Chinese sports teams are noted for their wide breadth of participation by female athletes, specifically in the [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Noland|first=Marcus|last2=Stahler|first2=Kevin|date=2014|title=What Goes into a Medal: Women's Inclusion and Success at the Olympic Games|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/dfe11fa406f813d37ae4d1f7e2c654c6b338c714|doi=10.2139/ssrn.2512876|issn=1556-5068}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brownell|first=Susan|date=1996-02-01|title=Representing gender in the Chinese nation: Chinese sportswomen and Beijing's bid for the 2000 olympics|journal=Identities|volume=2|issue=3|pages=223\u2013247|doi=10.1080/1070289X.1996.9962536|issn=1070-289X}}</ref> A [[Herfindahl\u2013Hirschman Index|Herfindahl Index]] (a measure often used in economics to show the degree of concentration when individuals are classified by type, and a lower number indicates higher diversity) showing Female Participation in the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]] indicated China's female Olympic delegation, the fourth largest present, to be the second most spread out across all events at 0.050, compared to higher numbers from over 190 other delegations. The same index showed the ratio of women to men to be 7 to 10. 213 total female athletes participated.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roche|first=Maurice|date=November 2008|title=Putting the London 2012 Olympics into perspective: the challenge of understanding mega-events|journal=Twenty-First Century Society|volume=3|issue=3|pages=285\u2013290|doi=10.1080/17450140802447212|issn=1745-0144}}</ref> In total, approximately 60% of Chinese Olympic gold medals were earned by female athletes over the last 8 Olympic games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/sports/article/19492563/world-fame-100-china-female-athletes-winning-competition-losing-fame-game|title=Chinese women winning in sports but losing in fame game|date=2017-05-30|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> Challenges to equality remain such as media representation. According to Yu Chia Chen, female Asian athletes receive much less coverage than their male counterparts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Chia-Chen|date=June 2009|title=A Content Analysis of News Coverage of Asian Female Olympic Athletes|journal=International Review for the Sociology of Sport|volume=44|issue=2\u20133|pages=283\u2013305|doi=10.1177/1012690209104796|issn=1012-6902}}</ref> Another report indicates Chinese girls and women are also less likely to be exposed to sports programming on television.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lagaert|first=Susan|last2=Van Houtte|first2=Mieke|last3=Roose|first3=Henk|date=2019-09-01|title=Gender Differences in Sport Spectatorship and (Fe)male Adolescents' Gender Identity, Experienced Pressure for Gender Conformity and Gender Role Attitudes|journal=Sociology of Sport Journal|volume=36|issue=3|pages=233\u2013243|doi=10.1123/ssj.2018-0022|issn=0741-1235}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\nIn October 2017, the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]] (IRFU) advertised an available position for head coach of the [[Ireland women's national rugby union team|Irish women's national rugby team]]. The job was advertised as \"part-time,\" \"casual,\" and available on six-month basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rugby-union/2017/10/22/english-womens-rugby-players-lend-support-irish-protest/|title=English women's rugby players lend support to Irish protest|last=Rowan|first=Kate|date=October 22, 2017|website=Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> Players expressed their disagreement with the decision, believing it was a sign that the IRFU was disrespecting and not prioritizing the women's game. In response to this announcement, the players highlighted what they perceived as the IRFU's lack of commitment to the long-term development of the women's game by wearing bracelets with \"#Legacy\" written on them for games with their club teams in the All Ireland League.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/rugby/international/irish-women-s-rugby-legacy-campaign-gathers-pace-1.3264755|title=Irish women's rugby 'Legacy' campaign gathers pace|last=Cummiskey|first=Gavin|date=October 22, 2017|website=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nThe [[Jamaica women's national football team|Jamaican women's national soccer team]] (nicknamed the Reggae Girlz) participated in the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]. This was the first [[FIFA Women's World Cup|Women's World Cup]] the country had qualified for, and the country was also the first Caribbean country to ever qualify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/teams/team/1885011/profile/|title=Jamaica Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, in September 2019, members of the team, including [[Khadija Shaw]] and [[Allyson Swaby]], posted a graphic on [[Instagram]] with captions stating that they had not been paid by the [[Jamaica Football Federation]] (JFF) for nine months of work. They announced that the team would not participate in any future tournaments until they received payment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2019/09/03/jamaica-womens-team-on-strike-after-not-being-paid/|title=Jamaica women's team on strike after not being paid|last=Bonn|first=Kyle|date=September 3, 2019|website=NBC Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> JFF President Michael Ricketts later announced that the team would be paid by the end of September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mls/article234660082.html|title=Jamaica's Reggae Girlz say 'No Pay, No Play,' threaten strike over unpaid salary|last=Kaufman|first=Michelle|date=September 3, 2019|website=The Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, the Reggae Girlz began playing again, and they won their group in the [[2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship qualification|Qualification Tournament]] for the [[2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship|2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Competition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1085649/jamaica-win-concacaf-olympic-qualifier|title=Jamaica thump St. Lucia at CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship|last=Etchells|first=Daniel|date=6 October 2019|website=Inside the Games|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Jamaica national netball team|Jamaican national netball team]] (nicknamed the Sunshine Girls) is ranked 4th in the world, as of July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netball.sport/events-and-results/current-world-rankings|title=Current World Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=International Netball Federation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, the team has not been well-funded, and had to resort to [[crowdfunding]] to attend the [[2019 Netball World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/all-woman/game-changers_176411?profile=1440|title=Game changers - modern-day athletes who are fighting for women's rights in sports|last=Knight|first=Candiece|date=October 7, 2019|website=The Jamaica Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> After receiving support from sponsors, the Sunshine Girls were able to go to the tournament, where they placed 5th overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/laptestnews/_Sunshine_Girls_beat_Malawi,_claim_fifth_spot?profile=1548|title=Netball World Cup: Sunshine Girls beat Malawi; claim fifth spot|last=Myers|first=Sanjay|date=July 21, 2019|website=The Jamaica Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Muslim world===\n{{Main|Muslim women in sport}}\n[[File:Sania Mirza (5993143538).jpg|thumb|upright=.65|[[Sania Mirza]], a former world No. 1 in women's tennis doubles, is an Indian Muslim.]]\n\nMuslim women are less likely to take part in sport than Western non-Muslims.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5286568.stm Muslims 'face barriers' over sport]. [[BBC Sport]]. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref> This is particularly so for [[women in Arab societies]]. The traditions of [[Islamic modesty]] in dress and requirements for women's sport to take place in a [[Sex segregation|single-sex environment]] make sports participation more difficult for devout female adherents. The lack of availability of suitably modest sports clothing and sports facilities that allow women to play in private contributes to the lack of participation. Cultural norms of women's roles and responsibilities towards the family may also be a source of discouragement from time-consuming sports practice.<ref name=\"Women1\">[http://sites.duke.edu/wcwp/research-projects/middle-east/muslim-women-in-sport/#_ftn7 Muslim Women in Sport]. Soccer Politics. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref><ref name=\"Women2\">Maesam, T-AbdulRazak, et al (2010). [http://www.japss.org/upload/13.maesam.pdf The Perspective of Arabic Muslim Women toward Sport Participation]. ''Journal of Asia Pacific Studies'', Vol 1, No 2, 364\u2013377. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref>\n\nHowever, Islamic tenets and religious texts suggest that women's sports in general should be promoted and are not against the values of the religion. The Quranic statements that followers of Islam should be healthy, fit and make time for leisure are not sex-specific. The prophet [[Muhammad]] is said to have raced his wife [[Aisha]] on several occasions, with Aisha beating him the first couple of times. Correspondingly, some scholars have proposed that Muslim women's lack of engagement with sport is due to cultural or societal reasons, rather than strictly religious ones.<ref name=\"Women1\" /><ref name=\"Women2\" />\n\nHowever, besides religious testaments, there are many barriers for Muslim women in relation to sports participation. A significant barrier to Muslim women's sports participation is bans on the Islamic headscarf, commonly known as the [[hijab]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ayub|first=Awista|date=2011-04-14|title=A Closer Look at FIFA's Hijab Ban: What it Means for Muslim Players and Lessons Learned|journal=SAIS Review of International Affairs|volume=31|issue=1|pages=43\u201350|doi=10.1353/sais.2011.0010|issn=1945-4724}}</ref> FIFA instituted such a ban in 2011, preventing the Iranian women's national football team from competing.<ref name=\":0\" /> They have since repealed the ban, but other organizations, including FIBA, maintain such regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://muslimmatters.org/2016/07/19/muslim-basketball-players-urge-fiba-to-allow-hijab/|title=\u00bb Muslim Basketball Players Urge FIBA To Allow Hijab|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> At the same time, many Muslim female athletes have achieved significant success in athletic competitions. Some have also used sports towards their own empowerment, working for women's rights, education, and health and wellbeing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dubey|first=Bipin Kumar|last2=Dubey|first2=Binayak Kumar|last3=Acharya|first3=Jayashree|date=2010-09-01|title=Participation in sport as an assessment of women empowerment|url=http://bjsm.bmj.com/content/44/Suppl_1/i62.2|journal=British Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=44|issue=Suppl 1|pages=i62|doi=10.1136/bjsm.2010.078725.208|issn=1473-0480}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=worldfocusonline|title=Female soccer players shoot down Turkish taboos|date=2009-09-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IIsM93orVn8|accessdate=2016-11-16}}</ref><ref>Contomichalos, Stephanie. \"How is Sport Employed as a Vehicle for Redefining Gender Identity in Islamic Societies?\" ''Retrieved'' 4, no. 7 (2010): 2015.</ref>\n\nIranian women were banned from attending a volleyball game and an Iranian girl was arrested for attending a match. Iran was given the right to host the International Beach Volleyball tournament, and many Iranian women were looking forward to attending the event. However, when the women tried to attend the event, they were disallowed, and told it was forbidden to attend by the FIVB. The women took to social media to share their outrage; however the Federation of International Beach volleyball refuted the accusations, saying it was a misunderstanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2016/08/17/iranian-women-should-not-face-arrest-and-threats-for-watching-volleyball/|title=Iranian women should not face arrest and threats for watching volleyball|author=|date=August 17, 2016|work=NYTimes.com|access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> This is one of the instances of unfair treatment of women, trying to participate in supporting their teams in Iran.\n\n\nIn October 2018 Iran announced that, after 40 years, it would allow women to enter sport arenas.<ref>[https://dailytimes.com.pk/312207/football-stadium-politics/ Football stadium politics]</ref> On September 22, 2019, the Iranian authorities assured [[FIFA]] that women would be able to attend the October qualifier of [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] in [[Tehran]], stated [[Gianni Infantino]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.compuserve.com/sports/story/0002/20190922/KBN1W7072_1|title=Iran has 'assured' women can attend qualifier: Infantino|website=CompuServe|accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Nigeria ===\nIn 2016, the [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigerian women's national soccer team]], known as the Super Falcons, won the [[2016 Africa Women Cup of Nations]]. The players alleged that they had not received their earned bonuses from winning the tournament owed to them by the [[Nigeria Football Federation]] (NFF). The NFF promised that it would pay them, but said the \"money [was] not readily available at the moment.\" In response, players engaged in a sit-in at their hotel as well as publicly demonstrated outside Nigeria's [[National Assembly (Nigeria)|National Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/nigerian-womens-soccer-team-protest-unpaid-victory-bonuses|title=Nigerian Women's Soccer Team Protest at Unpaid Victory Bonuses|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2016|website=VOA News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Super Falcons participated in the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 Women's World Cup]] and were eliminated from the tournament in the Round of 16. Following their elimination, the players engaged in another sit-in at their hotel, refusing to leave Paris until the NFF paid them the bonuses and daily allowances they had earned both from the World Cup as well as from other matches played in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3882567/nigeria-stage-sit-in-at-wwc-over-unpaid-bonuses|title=Nigeria Stage Sit-In at WWC Over Unpaid Bonuses|last=Udoh|first=Colin|date=June 22, 2019|website=ESPN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\n\nNorwegian sports are shaped by the values associated with them. For example, aggression generally is associated with males and being personable, with females. However, in terms of Norwegian handball, a study done by the Norwegian School of Sports and Sciences shows that gender is disregarded when the sport is covered in the media. The same study revealed that Women's handball is covered and followed as equally if not more than the men's team. In contrast to international handball coverage, the Norwegian coverage of Men's and Women's handball are discussed in the media using the same or similar verbiage. While they are especially noticeable in handball, equality and opportunity in Norwegian sports is not limited to the handball. Many top-female athletes from a number of sports have come from Norway. The act of playing or coaching were described slightly differently but categorized as successful using similar terms despite the gender of the coach or the player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencenordic.com/unique-norwegian-female-sports-heroes|title=The unique Norwegian female sports heroes|date=2014-09-30}}</ref>\n\n[[Ada Hegerberg]] is a highly skilled and decorated Norwegian soccer player, having won numerous [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]] and [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]] titles with French club [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Olympique Lyonnais]]. She also won the first-ever women's [[Ballon d'Or F\u00e9minin|Ballon D'Or]], a prestigious award given to the best soccer player in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/05/football/ada-hegerberg-ballon-dor-norway-spt-intl/index.html|title=Ada Hegerberg: The world's best player won't be at the Women's World Cup|last=Lewis|first=Aimee|last2=Davies|first2=Amanda|date=December 5, 2018|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> However, in 2017, she stopped playing with the [[Norway women's national football team|Norwegian national team]], citing unequal pay and conditions between the women's team and the men's team as her reason for stepping away from the team. She said she would no longer play for the national team until she felt that it was more respected by the [[Norwegian Football Federation]] and the culture surrounding women's soccer had improved, which meant she did not participate in the high-profile [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2019/6/5/18653682/ada-hegerberg-womens-world-cup-norway-skipping|title=Why Ada Hegerberg, the best player in soccer, is skipping the World Cup|last=Dator|first=James|date=June 5, 2019|website=SB Nation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== South Africa ===\nBetween 2004 and 2008, the previously highly successful [[South Africa women's national football team|South African women's national soccer team]], known as Banyana Banyana, began to struggle on the field due to a lack of a permanent coach. Members of the [[South African Football Association]] (SAFA) attributed the declining quality of play to the players' \"lack of femininity\" (Engh 2010), and the players were instructed to take etiquette classes and maintain stereotypical feminine hairstyles, as well as wear more feminine uniforms while playing. In response, players threatened to strike unless they were able to return to their preferred styles of dress.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engh|first=Mari Haugaa|date=2010|title=The battle for centre stage: Women's football in South Africa|journal=Agenda: Empowering Women for Gender Equity|volume=85|issue=85|pages=11\u201320|jstor=27917362}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Banyana Banyana was not paid the agreed-upon amount owed to them after qualifying for the [[2018 Africa Women Cup of Nations]] (AWCON), and they protested by not returning their official national team uniforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kayafm.co.za/banyana-banyana-payment-woes/|title=Banyana Banyana payment woes|last=|first=|date=July 3, 2018|website=Kayafm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, the team was again not paid their stipends and bonuses, despite finishing in second place at AWCON. They threatened to strike by not attending interviews or team practices, as well as not playing in a game against the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Dutch national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-01-18-00-banyanas-payment-woes-continue/|title=Banyana yet to be paid SAFA monies|last=Feltham|first=Luke|last2=Mokwena|first2=Busisiwe|date=January 17, 2019|website=Mail & Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, in May 2019, it was announced that Banyana Banyana would receive equal pay with the men's team heading into the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/south-africa-national-womens-football-team-banyana-banyana-to-get-equal-pay/|title=South Africa's National Women's Football Team to Receive Equal Pay|last=Durosomo|first=Damola|date=May 24, 2019|website=OkayAfrica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n\nIn Sweden, public funds are mostly given to men's hockey and football, and the women's team are left without proper funding. In 2016, Al Jazeera published an article bringing the discrimination that female Swedish athletes face to light by mentioning the double standard put on female athletes in terms of having to work double and still not receive the recognition or pay of the men's teams. Sweden is recognized as being a feminist country, however the wage gap is significant between male and female athletes. In 2013, Swedish striker, Zlatan Ibrahimovic earned  $16.7 million a year playing for Paris Saint-German, whereas Lotta Schellin who played for Lyon in France only earned $239,720. The wage gap is also evident among coaches. The difference in pay is evident in how male athletes and female athletes are able to spend their time between games. Women often have to work between training and games to make a living and to pay for their training camps, whereas men have that time to recuperate and relax; men also don't pay to attend training camps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2016/03/swedish-female-athletes-face-discrimination-160315110758946.html|title=Swedish female athletes face discrimination &#124; Europe &#124; al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the [[Sweden women's national ice hockey team|Swedish women's national ice hockey team]] boycotted the team's training camp and the Five Nations Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2019/08/16/swedish-womens-hockey-players-boycott-over-pay-dispute/|title=Swedish women's hockey players boycott over pay dispute|last1=Dure|first1=Beau|date=2019-08-16|website=NBC Sports|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> In a movement they called #F\u00f6rFramtiden (in English, \"For the Future\"), all 43 players invited to camp cited lack of equal pay as well as various instances of poor treatment by [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association|Svenska Ishockeyf\u00f6rbundet]] (the Swedish Ice Hockey Association, or SIF) toward the national team, including, but not limited to:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/8/18/20805729/for-the-future-how-team-sweden-reached-their-limit-damkronorna-sdhl|title=For the future: How Team Sweden reached their limit|last1=Foster|first1=Meredith|date=2019-08-18|website=The Ice Garden|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Team travel conditions - traveling by ferry instead of by plane to games; arriving to games one day before a tournament began, without accounting for time differences and jet lag\n* Team uniforms - players are provided men's clothing by SIF, not women's clothing\n* Nutrition - players are provided expired products\n* Lack of development - players allege that SIF has not adequately created a program to foster development of women's hockey at the youth level\n\nThe [[4 Nations Cup|Four Nations Cup]], originally scheduled for November 2019, was canceled by SIF due to the players' dispute with the federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/09/13/four-nations-cup-cancelled-amid-team-swedens-equality-battle/|title=Women's Four Nations Cup cancelled amid Team Sweden's equality battle|last1=Ingemi|first1=Marisa|date=2019-09-13|website=The Boston Herald|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the boycott, it was announced in October 2019 that the players had reached a new agreement with the federation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swehockey.se/Nyheter/nyheterfransvenskaishockeyforbundet/2019/Oktober2016/damkronornaklaraforspel/|title=The Crowns are Ready for Play|last=|first=|date=October 15, 2019|website=Svenska Ishockeyf\u00f6rbundet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> and that the team will begin training in November 2019 and play in a tournament against [[Switzerland women's national ice hockey team|Switzerland]], [[Finland women's national ice hockey team|Finland]], and [[Germany women's national ice hockey team|Germany]] in December 2019. The new deal includes terms guaranteeing performance-based bonuses and additional compensation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/10/15/20915396/damkronorna-players-boycott-is-over-a-deal-has-been-reached-with-the-swedish-ice-hockey-association|title=Damkronorna players' boycott is over, a deal has been reached with the Swedish Ice Hockey Association|last=Jay|first=Michelle|date=October 15, 2019|website=The Ice Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Training of Seattle Mist Lingerie Football 0154.jpg|thumb|Players of [[Legends Football League]] do a [[warming up]] exercise, USA]]\n\nWomen make up 54% of enrollment at 832 schools that responded to an NCAA gender equity study in 2000; however, females at these institutions only account for 41% of the athletes. Before Title IX, 90% of women's college athletic programs were run by women, but by 1992 the number dropped to 42% since Title IX requires that there are equal opportunities for both genders.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\"/>  This violates Title IX's premise that the ratio of female athletes to male athletes should be roughly equivalent to the overall proportion of female and male students.<ref name=\"garber1\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/gen/womenandsports/020619title9.html|title=Landmark law faces new challenges even now|last=Garber|first=Greg|accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref> Many of the issues today often revolve around the amount of money going into men's and women's sports. According to 2000\u20132001 figures, men's college programs still have many advantages over women's in the average number of scholarships (60.5%), operating expenses (64.5%), recruiting expenses (68.2%) and head coaching salaries (59.5%).<ref name=\"garber1\"/> Other forms of inequality are in the coaching positions. Before Title IX, women coached 90% of women's teams; in 1978 that percentage dropped to 58, and in 2004 it dropped even more to 44 percent.<ref name=\"coakley255\">{{cite book|title=Sports in Society|last=Coakley|first=Jay|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2007|location=New York|page=255}}</ref> In 1972, women administered 90 percent of women's athletic programs, and in 2004 this fell to 19 percent. Also in 2004, 18 percent of all women's programs had no women administrators.<ref name=\"coakley255\"/> In 2004, there were 3,356 administrative jobs in NCAA women's athletic programs and of those jobs, women held 35 percent of them.<ref name=\"coakley255\"/>\n\nThe fight for equality extends to the wallet. On March 30, 2016, five players from the U.S. women's soccer team filed a federal complaint of wage discrimination against U.S. Soccer, the governing body that pays both the men's and women's team.<ref name=\"Love equals\">{{cite web|url=https://loveequals.net/blogs/sports/u-s-women-s-soccer-team-sued-federation-for-equal-pay|title=U.S. Women's Soccer Team Sued Federation For Equal Pay}}</ref> The complaint argues that U.S. Soccer pays players on the women's team as little as forty percent of what it pays players on the men's team. This pay discrepancy exists despite the fact that the women's team has been much more successful in international competitions; the women's team has won four Olympic gold medals and three of the last five Women's World Cups, while the men's team has never won either of these competitions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/01/sports/soccer/uswnt-us-women-carli-lloyd-alex-morgan-hope-solo-complain.html?_r=0|title=Top Female Players Accuse U.S. Soccer of Wage Discrimination|author=Andrew Das|date=2016-03-31|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===World conferences===\n\nIn 1994, the International Working Group on Women and Sport organized the first World Conference on Women and Sport in Brighton, United Kingdom, where the Brighton Declaration was published. The IWG hosted further world conferences every four years, with the result of the Windfoek Call for Action (1998), Montreal Tool Kit (2002) and Brighton Plus Helsinki 2014 Declaration (2014). The conferences pretend to \"develop a sporting culture that enables and values the full involvement of women in every aspect of sport and physical activity\", by \"increas[ing] the involvement of women in sport at all levels and in all functions and roles\".<ref>[http://www.fisu.net/medias/fichiers/EN_Helsinki_calls_the_world_of_sport_to_LEAD_THE_CHANGE_BE_THE_CHANGE_2.pdf 6th IWG World Conference on Women and Sport 2014 \u2013 The Legacy Document]</ref>\n\n== Media coverage ==\n[[File:Alem\u00e3s levam ouro no v\u00f4lei de praia em Copacabana 1038687-18.08.2016 ffz-9127.jpg|thumb|Spectators and media personnel take photos even as Brazil's [[\u00c1gatha Bednarczuk]] hugs her support staff after winning a women's [[beach volleyball]] match in [[2016 Summer Olympics]].]]\n\nMedia coverage for women's sports is significantly less than the coverage for men's sports. Substantial research indicates that women's sports and female athletes gain only a small fraction of sports media coverage worldwide. Research that has examined why this is the case suggested this can be attributed to three particular factors that govern sports newswork: the male-dominated sports newsroom, ingrained assumptions about readership, and the systematic, repetitive nature of sports news.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherwood|first=Merryn|last2=Osborne|first2=Angela|last3=Nicholson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherry|first4=Emma|date=December 2017|title=Newswork, News Values, and Audience Considerations: Factors That Facilitate Media Coverage of Women's Sports|journal=Communication & Sport|language=en|volume=5|issue=6|pages=647\u2013668|doi=10.1177/2167479516645535|issn=2167-4795}}</ref> In 1989, a study was conducted that recorded and compared the amount of media coverage of men and women's sports on popular sports commentary shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=When it comes to women in sports, TV news tunes out |url=https://news.usc.edu/82382/when-it-comes-to-women-in-sports-tv-news-tunes-out/}}</ref> Michael Messner and his team in 2010 analyzed three different two-week periods by recording the amount of time that the stories were on air and the content of the stories. After recording sports news and highlights, they wrote a quantitative description of what they saw and a qualitative description of the amount of time that story received.<ref>Messner, Michael A., and Cheryl Cooky (2010): [https://dornsifecms.usc.edu/assets/sites/80/docs/tvsports.pdf \"Gender in Televised Sports\"]. n. pag. Dornsife.usc.edu. Center for Feminist Research, University of Southern California, June 2010.</ref>\n\nDuring that first year that the research was conducted in 1989, it was recorded that 5% of the sports segments were based on women's sports, compared to the 92% that were based on men's sports and the 3% that was a combination of both. In the late 1900s Women's Sports started to gain popularity in the media because of their talent in the Olympics.<ref>{{cite journal |title=An Imperceptible Difference: Visual and Textual Constructions of Femininity in Sport Illustrated and Sports Illustrated for Women |url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=4&sid=b1aa5c2a-a43c-40c6-97e5-7d193c12cfdd%40sdc-v-sessmgr01}}</ref> In 1999, women's sports coverage reached an all-time high when it was recorded at 8.7%. It maintained its higher percentages until it reached an all-time low in 2009, decreasing to 1.6%. The researchers also measured the amount of time that women's sports were reported in the [[news ticker]], the strip that displays information at the bottom of most news broadcasts. When recorded in 2009, 5% of ticker coverage was based on women's sports, compared to the 95% that was based on men's sports. These percentages were recorded in order to compare the amount of media coverage for each gender.\n\nWhen researching the actual amount of time that women's sports stories were mentioned, they focused specifically on differences between the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Women's National Basketball Association]]. They recorded two different time periods: when they were in season and when they were off-season. The WNBA had 8 stories, totaling 5:31 minutes, during their season, which was less than the NBA, which had a total of 72 stories, totaling approximately 65:51 minutes. During the off-season, the WNBA did not receive any stories or time on the ticker, while the NBA received a total of 81, which were approximately 50:15 minutes. When compared, the WNBA had a total of 8 stories and 5:31 minutes while the NBA had 153 stories and 1:56:06 hours. The actual games had several differences in the way the games were presented. The findings were that WNBA games had lower sound quality, more editing mistakes, fewer views of the shot clock and fewer camera angles. There was less verbal commentary and visual statistics about the players throughout the games as well.<ref>\"Gender Stereotyping in Televised Sports.\" LA 48 Foundation. June 2010. Web. November 2014. http://www.la84.org/gender-stereotyping-in-televised-sports/</ref> The quality of the stories has also significantly changed. In past studies, women were sexualized, portrayed as violent, or portrayed as girlfriends, wives and mothers. Female athletes were often included in gag stories that involved sexual dialogue or emphasized their bodies. In Australia, the wives of the men's cricket team members were given more media coverage than the players on the women's cricket team, who also had won more games than the men's rugby team.<ref>Holmes, Tracy. \"After Homophobia Let's Tackle Prejudice Against Women's Sports.\" ABC. April 2014. Web. November 2014. http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/after-homophobia-lets-tackle-prejudice-against-womens-sport/5381930</ref> In 2009, ''SportsCenter'' broadcast segments called \"Her Story\", which was a commentary that highlighted women's athletic careers.<ref>\"Gender in Televised Sports News and Highlights Shows, 1989\u20132009.\" Center for Feminist Research, University of California. June 2010. Web. November 2014</ref>\n\nIn newspapers articles, coverage on men's sports once again had a greater number of articles than women's sports in a ratio of 23\u20131. In 1990, a study was conducted that recorded and compared the amount of media coverage of men and women's sports on popular newspapers. They analyzed four different sports magazines for three months and recorded the number of women's sports stories that were featured and the content of the stories. Women's sports made up 3.5%, compared to the 81% of men's coverage. The lengths of these articles were 25\u201327% shorter than the length of men's articles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la84.org/coverage-of-womens-sports-in-four-daily-newspapers/ |title=Coverage of Women's Sports in Four Daily Newspapers \u2013 LA84 Foundation |author= |date= |work=LA84.org |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> There was an international frenzy in 2012 when the first woman that represented Saudi Arabia in the 2012 Olympics competed in track. That was the most women's sports coverage that there had been in several years.Women played 90 minutes of football, 80 minutes of rugby, 18 holes of golf and ran the same distance in a marathon as men. Exactly 12 months later, the newspapers returned to featuring 4% of articles on women's sports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/07/sport/olympics-women-equality-attar/index.html |title=Why has coverage of women's sport stopped post Olympics? - CNN.com |first=Amanda |last=Davies |date=August 7, 2013 |work=CNN.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> This same trend can be seen with regards to the FIFA World Cup. The 2015 Women's World Cup Final had an average of 25.4 million American viewers throughout the duration of the match, and peaked at 30.9 million viewers.<ref>Deitsch, Richard. \"USA-Japan's Women's World Cup Final Shatters American TV \nRecord Ratings.\" Futbol Planet. Sports Illustrated, 6 July 2015. Web. 8 May 2016.</ref> It was the most-viewed game of soccer ever in the United States\u2013men's or women's\u2013by a margin of almost 7 million viewers. Despite this jump in viewership of women's soccer in the U.S., television broadcasting of the women's professional soccer league in the U.S. remained much lower than that of the men's league. Fox Sports Network (the company that owns the rights to broadcast the National Women's Soccer League) broadcast 3 regular season NWSL games and 34 Major League Soccer regular-season games during the 2016 seasons. The dearth of coverage of women's sports is evidenced by the low number of segments (i.e., stories) in our sample. Of the 934 local network affiliate news segments (over 12 hr of broadcasts), 880 were on men's sports (or approximately 11\u00bd hr), 22 segments (or nearly 18 min) were on gender-neutral sports (e.g., a horse race, coverage of the Los Angeles [LA] marathon, and a recreational sports event), and only 32 segments (about 23 min) featured women's sports. SportsCenter's numbers were similar. Of the 405 total SportsCenter segments in our sample (nearly 14 hr), 376 covered men's sports (slightly over 13 hr), 16 segments were on gender-neutral sports (just over 20 min), and only 13 segments featured women's sports (approximately 17 min).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooky|first=Cheryl|last2=Messner|first2=Michael A.|last3=Musto|first3=Michela|date=September 2015|title=\"It's Dude Time!\": A Quarter Century of Excluding Women's Sports in Televised News and Highlight Shows|journal=Communication & Sport|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|pages=261\u2013287|doi=10.1177/2167479515588761|issn=2167-4795}}</ref>\n\nA recent article from the Wall Street Journal states \u201cfrom 2016 to 2018, women's games generated about $50.8 million in revenue compared with $49.9 million for the men, according to U.S. soccer's audited financial statements<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bachman |first1=Rachel |title=U.S. Women's Soccer Games Outearned Men's Games |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-womens-soccer-games-out-earned-mens-games-11560765600. |website=Wall Street Journal |publisher=Dow Jones & Company |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\u201d (Bachman, 2019). These numbers contrasts the idea that women's sports are not entertaining enough for the viewer or typical fan by $1.9 million. This idea stems from the male dominated sports perspective, which constantly undermines the perception of quality, effort, and potential that women's soccer exhibits. However, we can see through the caliber of women's soccer displayed most recently within the Women's FIFA World Cup of 2019 that it was on par if not better than the level of play of their male counterparts.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The U.S. Women's National Team scored 13 goals against Thailand in their opening match, the most goals scored in any World Cup match in history. Media outlets though may remain concerned that increased coverage of women's sport will lead to a reduction in audience draw and advertising revenue. \n\nAmy Godoy-Pressland conducted a study that investigated the relationship between sports reporting and gender in Great Britain. She studied Great Britain's newspapers from January 2008 to December 2009 and documented how media coverage of men's sports and women's sports was fairly equal during the Olympics and then altered after the Olympics were over. \"Sportswomen are disproportionately under-represented and the sheer quantity and quality of news items on sportsmen demonstrates how male athletes are represented as dominant and superior to females.\" She also documented how women's bodies were sexualized in photographs and written coverage, noting that the women featured were either nude, semi-nude, or wearing revealing clothing. \"The sexualization of sportswomen in Sunday reporting is commonplace and aimed at the mostly male readership. It promotes the idea of female aesthetics over achievements, while the coverage of women not directly involved in sport misrepresents the place of women in sport and inferiorizes real sportswomen's achievements.\"<ref>\"Women underrepresented, sexualized in weekend sports reporting\" ''Science Daily''. September 2013. Web. December 2014. https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/09/130918090756.htm</ref> The media has the ability to create or prevent interest in women's sports. Excluding women's sports from the media makes it much less likely for young girls to have role models that are women athletes.<ref>Donna A. Lopiano, Ph.D., (2008). Media Coverage of Women's Sports is Important, (2), Sports Management Resources, http://www.sportsmanagementresources.com/library/media-coverage-womens-sports</ref> According to Tucker Center for Research on Girls & Women in Sport at the University of Minnesota 40% of all athletes in the United States are women but women's sports only receive about 4% of sports media coverage.<ref>University of Minnesota (Producer) and PBS, (2014). Media Coverage & Female Athletes, http://video.tpt.org/video/2365132906/</ref> This amount of coverage has decreased in the last 20 years although there has been a major increase in women athletes.\n\nMedia coverage has slightly increased and this is mostly due to social networking.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Social media has further exposed women sports out to the public world, and often at a much greater rate than traditional news media. Traditional media has also improved its coverage of women's sports through more exposure time and using better equipment to record the events. Recent research has shown that in the past twenty years, camera angles, slow motion replays, quality and graphics regarding the presentation of women sports has gradually improved.<ref name=\"Cooky, C. 2012\">Cooky, C., & Lavoi, N. (2012). Playing but losing women's sports after title ix. ''Contexts,'' ''11''(1), 42\u201346. {{jstor|41960748}}</ref> However, mainstream media still is far behind in its showcasing of female sports in comparison to that of men's. A study has shown that ESPN, which began airing women NCAA tournament in 2003, aired eleven women tournament segments in comparison to one-hundred men's tournament segments.<ref name=\"Cooky, C. 2012\"/> ESPN and other sports outlets are airing more female-oriented sporting events; however the length of the segments are very small. This representative data is showcases a main part of the minimal interaction the media has with women athletes. Media coverage of women sports in the United States has further justified the divisional hierarchy faced by women athletes in terms of popularity and coverage. Scholarly studies (Kane, M. J., LaVoi, N. M., Fink, J. S. (2013) also show that when women athletes were given the option to pick a photo of a picture that would increase respect for their sport, they picked an on-the-court competency picture. However, when women athletes were told to pick a picture that would increase interest in their sport, 47% picked a picture that sexualized the women athlete.<ref>Kane, M. J., LaVoi, N. M., Fink, J. S. (2013). Exploring elite female athletes' interpretations of sport media images: A window into the construction of social identity and \"selling sex\" in women's sports. Communication & Sport, 1(3), 269\u2013298. doi: 10.1177/2167479512473585</ref> The UK is more representative than the United States with the BBC giving women's sports about 20% of their sports coverage (BBC spokesperson). Many women athletes in the UK do not see this as adequate coverage for the 36% of women who participate in sports.<ref>Gareth Lewis, (2014). Nicole Cooke calls for women's sport to have equal coverage on BBC, (p. 2), BBC News Wales, https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-26653208</ref> [[NewsChain]] is the first commercial publisher totally dedicated to women's sport coverage based in the UK.\n\n== Sex-specific sports injuries ==\nThere are some common sports injuries for which female athletes may be at a higher risk than male athletes.\n\nSeveral studies have shown that female athletes are more likely to tear their [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|anterior cruciate ligaments]] (ACLs) than male athletes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DeHaven|first=Kenneth E.|last2=Lintner|first2=David|date=1986|title=Athletic injuries: Comparison by age, sport, and gender|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=14|issue=3|pages=218\u2013224|doi=10.1177/036354658601400307|pmid=3752362}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ito|first=Eri|last2=Iwamoto|first2=Jun|displayauthors=1|date=2015|title=Sex-specific differences in injury types among basketball players|journal=Open Access Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=6|pages=1\u20136|pmc=4284005|pmid=25565908|doi=10.2147/OAJSM.S73625}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lindenfeld|first=Thomas|last2=Schmitt|first2=David|displayauthors=1|date=1994|title=Incidence of Injury in Indoor Soccer|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=22|issue=3|pages=364\u2013371|doi=10.1177/036354659402200312|pmid=8037278}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zelisko|first=John|last2=Noble|first2=H. Bates|displayauthors=1|date=1982|title=A comparison of men's and women's professional basketball injuries|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=10|issue=5|pages=297\u2013299|doi=10.1177/036354658201000507|pmid=6814271}}</ref> There are several different theories about why women are more prone to this injury, but there is no consensus on one theory in particular. The difference in injury risk may be due to female-specific hormonal changes associated with the menstrual cycle, or due to different skeletal and muscular structures (like a wider pelvis, stronger quadriceps than hamstrings, or more elastic ligaments) that cause women to place more stress on and more easily stretch the ACL than men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Editorial|date=2016|title=The female ACL: Why is it more prone to injury?|journal=Journal of Orthopaedics|volume=13|issue=2|pages=A1\u2013A4|pmc=4805849|pmid=27053841|doi=10.1016/S0972-978X(16)00023-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orthonc.com/your-health/preventing-acl-tears-why-are-acl-tears-more-common-in-female-athletes|title=Preventing ACL Tears - Why are ACL Tears More Common in Female Athletes?|last=Galland|first=Mark|date=|website=Orthnonc.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beaconortho.com/blog/risk-acl-injuries-female-athletes/|title=The Risk of ACL Injuries in Female Athletes|last=|first=|date=|website=Beaconortho.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcm.edu/news/sports-medicine/female-athletes-at-higher-risk-for-acl-tears|title=Female athletes at higher risk of ACL tears|last=Pathak|first=Dipali|date=August 12, 2015|website=Baylor College of Medicine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFemale athletes are also more prone to concussions than male athletes. They exhibit more visible symptoms of a concussion than male athletes and for a longer period of time than male athletes, a phenomenon known as the \"concussion gap.\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mollayeva|first=Tatyana|last2=El-Khechen-Richandi|first2=Graziella|displayauthors=1|date=2018|title=Sex and Gender Considerations in Concussion Research|journal=Concussion|volume=3|issue=1|pages=CNC51|pmc=6094024|pmid=30202593|doi=10.2217/cnc-2017-0015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frommer|first=Leah|last2=Gurka|first2=Kelly|displayauthors=1|date=2011|title=Sex Differences in Concussion Symptoms of High School Athletes|url=|journal=Journal of Athletic Training|volume=46|issue=1|pages=76\u201384|doi=10.4085/1062-6050-46.1.76|pmid=21214354|pmc=3017493}}</ref> However, there is no consensus on the reason women are more prone to concussions than men or experience symptoms differently. Some theories have been that women have smaller, more breakable nerve fibers in their brains,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolle|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Jaye|first2=Andrew|displayauthors=1|date=2018|title=Newfound sex differences in axonal structure underlie differential outcomes from in vitro traumatic axonal injury|url=|journal=Experimental Neurology|volume=300|issue=|pages=121\u2013134|doi=10.1016/j.expneurol.2017.11.001|pmid=29104114|pmc=6495524}}</ref> that their necks are weaker and so their brains accelerate more sharply on impact,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tierney|first=R|last2=Sitler|first2=MR|displayauthors=1|date=2005|title=Gender differences in head-neck segment dynamic stabilization during head acceleration|journal=Med Sci Sports Exerc|volume=37|issue=2|pages=272\u2013279|pmid=15692324|doi=10.1249/01.MSS.0000152734.47516.AA|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1196f9acb8d4ca46a3f48728b0c0bad8b6e8dbf2}}</ref> or fluctuating hormones during menstrual cycles that make them more susceptible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/news/story/3965/menstrual-cycle-influences-concussion-outcomes.aspx|title=Menstrual Cycle Influences Concussion Outcomes|last=University of Rochester Medical Center|date=November 13, 2013|website=URMC.Rochester.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\n== Gallery of women athletes today ==\n<gallery caption=\"Women athletes today\">\nFile:Greek women's indoor volleyball team in bikini uniform.jpg|Greek women's indoor [[volleyball]] team at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]\nFile:Camogie.jpg|thumb|Camogie players at [[Croke Park]] in 2006\nFile:Meseret Defar Valencia 2008.jpg|[[Olympic Games]] track gold medalist [[Meseret Defar]] of Ethiopia\nFile:1 patti 060123 1Ds 7037.jpg|Master [[Hao Zhihua]], the most accomplished female [[Wushu (sport)|Wushu]] athlete in China's history\nFile:Ellen van Dijk, Time Trial Olympic Summer Games 2012.jpg|Dutch cyclist [[Ellen van Dijk]], at the [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's road time trial|2012 Summer Olympics]]\nFile:Fernanda BRITO 5962.JPG|Fernanda Brito of Chile playing women's doubles tennis at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 2010\nFile:Russia 4 x 400 m Paris 2011.jpg|Russian women's team pose after winning 4 \u00d7 400 m relay at [[2011 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dong Jinxia: ''Women, Sport and Society in Modern China: Holding Up More Than Half the Sky'', Routledge, 2002, {{ISBN|0-7146-8214-4}}\n*Allen Guttmann: ''Women's Sports: A History'', Columbia University Press 1992, {{ISBN|0-231-06957-X}}\n*Helen Jefferson Lenskyj: ''Out of Bounds: Women, Sport and Sexuality.''  Women's Press, 1986.\n*Helen Jefferson Lenskyj: ''Out on the Field: Gender, Sport and Sexualities''.  Women's Press, 2003.\n*[https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138919822/the-nation-sports-dont-need-sex-to-sell The Nation: Sports Don't Need Sex To Sell] \u2013 NPR, Mary Jo Kane \u2013 August 2, 2011\n* Else Trangbaek & [[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (eds.): ''Gender and Sport from European Perspectives''. Copenhagen: University of Copenhagen 1999\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Feminism}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Women's professional sports]]\n* [[Mixed-sex sports]]\n*[[Bikini in popular culture#Sports|Bikini as sportswear]]\n*[[Sex verification in sports]]\n* [[Timeline of women's sports]]\n* [[Title IX]] (Patsy T. Mink Equal Opportunity in Education Act)\n* [[Women's Sports Foundation]]\n* [[Major women's sport leagues in North America]]\n* [[WTSN (TV channel)]]\n* [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (defunct since 1982)\n* [[Misogyny in sports]]\n* [[Participation of women in the Olympics]]\n* [[Sportswear (activewear)]]\n* [[Legends Football League]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* https://www.irishtimes.com/student-hub/tackling-gender-barriers-to-sporting-equality-1.2619267\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|Women's sports}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140527131109/http://www.northnet.org/stlawrenceaauw/timeline.htm History of Women in Sports Timeline]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041115121944/http://www.personal.psu.edu/users/s/j/sjf187/olympics/6.html Heraea Games]\n\n{{Women's sports}}\n{{Sport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Women's sports}}\n[[Category:Women's sports| ]]\n[[Category:Sports by type]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sports participated by females}}\n{{globalize|article|the United States|date=August 2012}}\n{{multiple image\n | perrow = 2\n | total_width = 400\n | align             = right\n | direction         = horizontal\n | image1            = United States vs New Zealand, 19 September, 2017 (36536441784).jpg\n | width1            =  \n | image2            = Nadia Com\u0103neci 2.jpg \n | width2            =  \n | image3            = 2008 LPGA Championship - Annika Sorenstam tee shot.jpg\n | width3            =  \n | image4            = Lenglen Wills Match of the Century 1926 2 (instant) (cropped).jpg\n | width4            =  \n | image5            = La Maga (4815861789).jpg\n | width5            = \n | image6            = Australia v England netball 2008.jpg\n | width6            =  \n | footer = [[United States women's national soccer team]]; Olympic gold medal gymnast [[Nadia Com\u0103neci]]; Hall of Fame golfer [[Annika S\u00f6renstam]]; Tennis players [[Suzanne Lenglen]] and [[Helen Wills]]; Legend of Hockey [[Luciana Aymar]]; [[Australia national netball team|Australia]] and [[England national netball team|England]] national [[netball]] teams\n}}\n\n{{Women in society sidebar}}\n\n'''Women's sports''', both amateur and [[women's professional sports|professional,]] have existed throughout the world for centuries in all varieties of [[sports]]. Female participation and popularity in sports increased dramatically in the 20th century, especially in the last quarter-century, reflecting changes in modern societies that emphasize '''[[gender]] parity.''' Although the level of participation and performance still varies greatly by [[country]] and by [[Sports|sport]], [[women]]'s sports are generally accepted throughout the world today.\n\nHowever, despite a rise in women's participation in sports, a large disparity in participation rates between [[Woman|women]] and [[Man|men]] remains.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/examination-of-gender-equity-and-female-participation-in-sport/ |title=Examination of Gender Equity and Female Participation in Sport |date=2016-02-26 |newspaper=The Sport Journal |access-date=2017-02-08 }}</ref> These disparities are prevalent globally and continue to hinder equality in sports. Many institutions and programs still remain conservative and do not contribute to gender equity in sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://athleteassessments.com/gender-equality-debate/|title=The Gender Equality Debate; Women in Sport|last=Hanson|first=Liz|date=2016-06-17|website=Athlete Assessments|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\nWomen who play sports face many obstacles today, such as lower pay, less media coverage, and different injuries compared to their male counterparts. Many female athletes have engaged in peaceful protests, such as playing strikes, social media campaigns, and even federal lawsuits to address these inequalities.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ancient civilizations===\n[[File:Villa romana bikini girls.JPG|thumb|Roman women engaged in sports. [[Mosaic]] at the [[Villa del Casale|Villa Romana del Casale]] near [[Piazza Armerina]] in [[Sicily]]]]\n[[File:Greek Runner Maiden 2.png|thumb|A statue of a victress of the Heraean Games, represented near the start of a race]]\nBefore each [[ancient Olympic Games]] there was a separate women's athletic event held at the same stadium in Olympia, the [[Heraean Games]],  dedicated to the goddess [[Hera]]. Myth held that the Heraea was founded by [[Hippodameia]], the wife of the king who founded the Olympics.<ref name=Scanlon>{{cite web |author=Scanlon, Thomas F. |title=Games for Girls |work=Ancient Olympics Guide |url=http://www.archaeology.org/online/features/olympics/girls.html |access-date=February 18, 2006}}</ref> According to E. Norman Gardiner:\n\n{{Quote| At the festival there were races for maidens of various ages. Their course was 500 feet, or one-sixth less than the men's stadium. The maidens ran with their hair down their backs, a short tunic reaching just below the knee, and their right shoulder bare to the breast. The victors received crowns of olive and a share of the heifer sacrificed to Hera. They had, too, the right of setting up their statues in the Heraeum.<ref>Gardiner, E. Norman, 'The Rise of the Athletic Festival' in ''Greek Athletic Sport and Festivals'', London:MacMillan, 1910, pp. 47\u201348</ref> }}\n\nAlthough married women were excluded from the Olympics even as spectators, [[Cynisca]] won an Olympic game as owner of a chariot (champions of chariot races were owners not riders), as did [[Euryleonis]], [[Belistiche]], [[Polycrates of Argos|Zeuxo, Encrateia and Hermione]], Timareta, Theodota and Cassia.\n\nAfter the classical period, there was some participation by women in men's athletic festivals.<ref name=Scanlon/> Women in Sparta began to practice the same athletic exercises that men did, exhibiting the qualities of Spartan soldiers. Plato even supported women in sports by advocating running and sword-fighting for women.<ref>Swaddling, Judith. The Ancient Olympic Games. Austin: U of Texas, 1980. Print.</ref>\n\nNotably, cultural representations of a pronounced female physicality were not limited to sport in Ancient Greece and can also be found in representations of a group of warrioresses known as the [[Amazons]].\n\n===Early modern===\nDuring the [[Song dynasty|Song]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], and [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] dynasties, women played in professional [[Cuju]] teams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://features.cultural-china.com/cuju/index02.html |title=Cuju \u2013 Ancient Chinese Football |author= |date= |work=Cultural-China.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://features.cultural-china.com/cuju/ |title=Cuju \u2013 Ancient Chinese Football |author= |date= |work=Cultural-China.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Chujutu.jpg|thumb|Chinese ladies playing ''cuju'', by the [[Ming Dynasty]] painter [[Du Jin]]]] The first Olympic games in the modern era, which were in 1896 were not open to women, but since then the number of women who have participated in the Olympic games have increased dramatically.<ref>{{cite web |title=Women and Sport Commission |url=http://www.olympic.org/women-sport-commission |work=Olympic.org |access-date=January 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===19th and early 20th centuries===\nThe educational committees of the [[French Revolution]] (1789) included intellectual, moral, and physical education for both girls and boys. With the victory of Napoleon less than twenty years later, physical education was reduced to military preparedness for boys and men. In Germany, the physical education of [[GutsMuths]] (1793) included girl's education. This included the measurement of performances of girls. This led to women's sport being more actively pursued in Germany than in most other countries.<ref>[[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (2003): ''Germany'', in: [[James Riordan]] & [[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (eds.): ''European Cultures in Sport. Examining the Nations and Regions''. Bristol: Intellect 2003, pp. 57 \u2013 88.</ref> When the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Sportive F\u00e9minine Internationale]] was formed as an all women's international organization it had a German male vice-president in addition to German international success in elite sports.\n\nWomen's sports in the late 1800s focused on correct posture, facial and bodily beauty, muscles, and health.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Padgett |first1=Jessica |title=The Issues of Women in Sport |url=http://serendip.brynmawr.edu/local/scisoc/sports02/papers/jpadgett.html |website=Serendip Studio |accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 1870, activities for women were recreational rather than sport-specific in nature. They were noncompetitive, informal, rule-less; they emphasized physical activity rather than competition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bell |first1=Richard |title=A History of Women in Sport Prior to Title IX |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/a-history-of-women-in-sport-prior-to-title-ix/ |website=The Sport Journal |accessdate=7 April 2017|date=2008-03-14 }}</ref> Sports for women before the 20th century placed more emphasis on fitness rather than the competitive aspects we now associate with all sports.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/a-history-of-women-in-sport-prior-to-title-ix/ |title=A History of Women in Sport Prior to Title IX |date=2008-03-14 |newspaper=The Sport Journal |access-date=2017-02-05 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1916 the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) held its first national championship for women (in swimming),{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=DWmCWO6SpsYC&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=In+1916+the+Amateur+Athletic+Union+(AAU)+held+its+first+national+championship+for+women.#v=onepage&q=In%201916%20the%20Amateur%20Athletic%20Union%20(AAU)%20held%20its%20first%20national%20championship%20for%20women.&f=false |title=Outstanding Women Athletes: Who They are and how They Influenced Sports in America |last=Woolum |first=Janet |date=1998-01-01 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |isbn=9781573561204 }}</ref> In 1923 the AAU also sponsored the [[1923 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|First American Track & Field championships for women]]. Earlier that year the [[Women's Amateur Athletic Association]] (WAAA) held [[1923 WAAA Championships|the first WAAA Championships]].\n\nFew women competed in sports in Europe and North America before the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, as social changes favored increased female participation in society as equals with men. Although women were technically permitted to participate in many sports, relatively few did. There was often disapproval of those who did.\n\n\"Bicycling has done more to emancipate women than anything else in the world.\" [[Susan B. Anthony]] said \"I stand and rejoice every time I see a woman ride on a wheel. It gives women a feeling of freedom and self-reliance.\"\n\nThe modern [[Olympic Games|Olympics]] had female competitors from 1900 onward, though women at first participated in considerably fewer events than men. Women first made their appearance in the Olympic Games in Paris in 1900. That year, 22 women competed in tennis, sailing, croquet, equestrian, and golf.<ref>\"Equality for Women in the Olympics.\" Feminist Majority Foundation. Web. November 2014. http://www.feminist.org/sports/olympics.asp</ref>  As of the IOC-Congress in Paris 1914 a woman's medal had formally the same weight as a man's in the official medal table. This left the decisions about women's participation to the individual international sports federations.<ref>[[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]]: Forgotton Decisions. The IOC on the Eve of World War I, in: ''Olympika'' 6 (1997), 85 \u2013 98. <http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/Olympika/Olympika_1997/olympika0601g.pdf></ref> Concern over the physical strength and stamina of women led to the discouragement of female participation in more physically intensive sports, and in some cases led to less physically demanding female versions of male sports.  Thus [[netball]] was developed out of [[basketball]] and [[softball]] out of [[baseball]].\n\nIn response to the lack of support for women's international sport the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Sportive F\u00e9minine Internationale]] was founded in France by [[Alice Milliat]]. This organization initiated the Women's Olympiad (held [[1921 Women's Olympiad|1921]], [[1922 Women's Olympiad|1922]] and [[1923 Women's Olympiad|1923]]) and the [[Women's World Games]], which attracted participation of nearly 20 countries and was held four times ([[1922 Women's World Games|1922]], [[1926 Women's World Games|1926]], [[1930 Women's World Games|1930]] and [[1934 Women's World Games|1934]]).<ref name=\"LeighBonin\">{{Cite journal |last=Leigh |first=Mary H. |author2=Bonin, Th\u00e9r\u00e8se M. |title=The Pioneering Role Of Madame Alice Milliat and the FSFI in Establishing International Trade and Field Competition for Women |journal=Journal of Sport History |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=72\u201383 |year=1977 |url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1977/JSH0401/jsh0401f.pdf |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>  In 1924 the [[1924 Women's Olympiad]] was held at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in [[London]]. The [[International Olympic Committee]] began to incorporate greater participation of [[women at the Olympics]] in response. The number of Olympic women athletes increased over five-fold in the period, going from 65 at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]] to 331 at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]].<ref>[http://www.olympic.org/antwerp-1920-summer-olympics Antwerp 1920]. IOC. Retrieved on 2014-01-11.</ref><ref>[http://www.olympic.org/berlin-1936-summer-olympics Berlin 1936]. IOC. Retrieved on 2014-01-11.</ref>\n\nMost early women's professional sports leagues foundered.  This is often attributed to a lack of spectator support.  Amateur competitions became the primary venue for women's sports. Throughout the mid-twentieth century, Communist countries dominated many [[Olympic sports]], including women's sports, due to state-sponsored athletic programs that were technically regarded as amateur.  The legacy of these programs endured, as former Communist countries continue to produce many of the top female athletes. Germany and Scandinavia also developed strong women's athletic programs in this period.\n<gallery caption=\"Women's sports in history\">\nFile:Bronze figure of a running girl, Greek, about 520-500 BC, Found at Prizren, Serbia, Winning at the ancient Games, British Museum (7667206370).jpg|A [[Spartan]] woman running. The bare right breast is indicative of her being an athlete.\nFile:1912 Fraulein Kussin Mrs Edwards boxing.jpg|Fraulein Kussinn and Mrs. Edwards boxing, 1912.\nFile:Camogie Team, Waterford, 17 October 1915.jpg|thumb|A [[camogie]] team posing with their hurling sticks, around 1915.\nFile:Bw 1920 competition medals.jpg|Young women wearing swimming competition medals, around 1920.\nFile:1910 to 1920 Sibyl Marston holding foil.jpg|Fencer Sibyl Marston holding a foil.\nFile:Time Cover in 1924-08-25.JPG|[[Edith Cummings]] was the first woman [[athletic sports|athlete]] to appear on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|Time magazine]], a major step in women's athletic history.\n</gallery>\n\n====United States====\n{{see also|Timeline of women's sports in the United States|National Collegiate Athletic Association}}\n{{multiple image |total_width=330\n|image1 = 2011 Okemos High School Girls' Water Polo State Championship Team.jpg\n|image2 = TWU Gymnastics (Bars) Amy Winczura (5694030475).jpg\n|footer = Women's sports is given very high priority in U.S. from school itself.<ref name=\"Empowering Women in Sports\">{{cite web |website=Femenist Majority Foundation |title=Empowering Women in Sports |url=http://www.feminist.org/research/sports/sports12.html}}</ref> Picture on left shows a U.S. high school girls' [[water polo]] team (with their male coaches in background) posing with their trophy. Picture on right shows a U.S. university girl practising a difficult [[gymnastics]] manoeuvre under the watchful eyes of her coach.}}{{Main|Title IX}}\n\n=====Implementation and regulation of Title IX=====\n\n====== Overview ======\nIn 1972 the [[United States Congress]] passed the Title IX legislation as a part of the additional Amendment Act to the 1964 Civil Rights Act.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\">{{cite book|title=A Sporting Chance: Sports and Genders|last=Steiner|first=Andy|year=1995}}</ref> Title IX states that: \"no person shall on the basis of sex, be excluded from participating in, be denied benefits of, or be subjected to discrimination under any educational programs or activities receiving federal financial assistance...\";<ref name=\"Greenburg_1997\">{{cite book|title=Getting into the Game: Women and Sports|last=Greenburg|first=Judith E.|publisher=Franklin Watts|year=1997|location=New York}}</ref> in other words, Title IX prohibits gender discrimination in schools that receive federal funds through grants, scholarships, or other support for students. The law states that federal funds can be withdrawn from a school engaging in intentional gender discrimination in the provision of curriculum, counseling, academic support, or general educational opportunities; this includes interscholastic or varsity sports.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sports in Society|last=Coakley|first=Jay|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2007|location=New York|page=238}}</ref> This law from the Education Act requires that both male and female athletes have equal facilities and equal benefits. The equal benefits are the necessities such as equal equipment, uniforms, supplies, training, practice, quality in coaches and opponents, awards, cheerleaders and bands at the game.<ref name=\"Greenburg_1997\" /> In 1979, there was a policy interpretation that offered three ways in which schools could be compliant with Title IX; it became known as the \"three-part test\".\n\n# Providing athletic participation opportunities that are substantially proportionate to the student enrollment. This prong of the test is satisfied when participation opportunities for men and women are \"substantially proportionate\" to their respective undergraduate enrollment.\n# Demonstrating a continual expansion of athletic opportunities for the underrepresented sex. This prong of the test is satisfied when an institution has a history and continuing practice of program expansion that is responsive to the developing interests and abilities of the underrepresented sex (typically female).\n# Accommodating the interest and ability of the underrepresented sex. This prong of the test is satisfied when an institution is meeting the interests and abilities of its female students even where there are disproportionately fewer females than males participating in sports.\n\n====== Room for improvement ======\nAlthough schools only have to be compliant with one of the three prongs, a 1999 study by Sigelman and Wahlbeck found that many schools are \"nowhere near compliance\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sigelman|first=Lee|last2=Wahlbeck|first2=Paul|date=1999|title=Gender Proportionality in Intercollegiate Athletics: The Mathematics of Title IX Compliance|journal=Social Science Quarterly|volume=80|issue=3|pages=518\u2013538|jstor=42863927}}</ref> Many schools attempt to achieve compliance through the first prong; however, in order to achieve that compliance schools cut men's programs, which is not the way the OCR wanted compliance achieved.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Irons|first=Alicia|date=Spring 2006|title=The Economic Inefficiency of Title IX|url=http://business.uni.edu/economics/Themes/irons.pdf|journal=Major Themes in Economics|access-date=April 17, 2012}}</ref> Equity is not the only way to be compliant with Title IX; athletic departments need to show that they are making efforts to achieve parity in participation, treatment, and athletic financial assistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacwaa.org/advocacy/title-ix/information|title=Title IX Information|access-date=April 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to research done by National Women's Law Center in 2011, 4500 public high schools across the nation have extremely high gender inequality and are violating the Title IX laws.<ref name=\"auto\">Wong, A. (2015, June 26). Where Girls Are Missing Out on High-School Sports. Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2015/06/girls-high-school-sports-inequality/396782/</nowiki></ref> According to further research done by the Women's Law Center, schools with a high number of minority students and a greater number of people of color mainly in southern states had a much higher rate of gender disparity. There is also a huge disparity regarding sport related scholarships for men and women, with men getting 190 million more in funding than women.<ref name=\":2\">Wallace, K. (2016, March 14). The real March Madness: When will women's teams get equal buzz? Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/30/living/feat-march-madness-womens-sports-attention-money-men/</nowiki></ref> This pattern has persisted over a long period of time as, most colleges focus on their male athletics team and plow more money into them. This disparity shows the link between race and gender, and how it plays a significant role in the hierarchy of sports.<ref name=\"auto\" />\n\n=====Effect of Title IX on women's sports=====\n\n====== Participation in sports ======\nThe main objective of Title IX is to make sure there is equal treatment in sports and school, regardless of sex, in a federally funded program. It was also used to provide protection to those who are being discriminated due to their gender.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/crt/about/cor/coord/titleix.php|publisher=The United States Department of Judgement|access-date=November 12, 2013}}</ref>  However, Title IX is most commonly associated with its impact on athletics and more specifically the impact it has had on women's participation in athletics at every age. Title IX has allowed women and girls in educational institutions to increase their opportunity in different sports they are able to play now.<ref>{{Cite document|title=Proxy Services {{!}} St. Ambrose University, Davenport, Iowa|id = {{ProQuest|1081454393}}}}</ref> Today{{When|date=April 2017}} there are more females participating in athletics than ever before. As of the 2007\u20132008 school year, females made up 41% of the participants in college athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aauw.org/act/laf/library/athleticStatistics.cfm|title=Title IX Athletic Statistics|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114061928/http://www.aauw.org/act/laf/library/athleticStatistics.cfm|archivedate=November 14, 2011|accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref> To see the growth of women's sports, consider the difference in participation before the passing of Title IX and today. In 1971\u20131972 there were 294,015 females participating in high school athletics and in 2007\u20132008 there were over three million females participating, meaning there has been a 940% increase in female participation in high school athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIn 1971\u20131972 there were 29,972 females participating in college athletics and in 2007\u20132008 there were 166,728 females participating, a 456% increase in female participation in college athletics.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> In 1971, less than 300,000 females played in high school sports. After the law was passed many females started to get involved in sports. By 1990, eighteen years later, 1.9 million female high school students were playing sports.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\" /> Increased participation in sports has had a direct impact on other areas of women's lives; these effects can be seen in women's education and employment later on in life; a 2010 study found that the changes set in motion by Title IX explained about 20 percent of the increase in women's education and about 40 percent of the rise in employment for 25-to-34-year-old women.<ref name=\"parker1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/16/health/16well.html|title=As Girls Become Women, Sports Pay Dividends|last=Parker-Pope|first=Tara|date=February 16, 2010|work=New York Times|access-date=February 16, 2012}}</ref> This is not to say that all women who are successful later on in life played sports, but it is saying that women who did participate in athletics received benefits in their education and employment later on in life.<ref name=\"parker1\" />\n\nIn 1971, fewer than 295,000 girls participated in high school varsity athletics, accounting for just 7 percent of all varsity athletes; in 2001, that number leaped to 2.8 million, or 41.5 percent of all varsity athletes, according to the National Coalition for Women and Girls in Education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncwge.org/|title=The National Coalition for Women and Girls in Education|website=www.ncwge.org|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref> In 1966, 16,000 females competed in intercollegiate athletics. By 2001, that number jumped to more than 150,000, accounting for 43 percent of all college athletes. In addition, a 2008 study of intercollegiate athletics showed that women's collegiate sports had grown to 9,101 teams, or 8.65 per school. The five most frequently offered college sports for women are, in order: (1) basketball, 98.8% of schools have a team, (2) volleyball, 95.7%, (3) soccer, 92.0%, (4) cross country, 90.8%, and (5) softball, 89.2%. Since 1972, women have also competed in the traditional male sports of wrestling, weightlifting, rugby, and boxing. An article in the ''New York Times'' found that there are lasting benefits for women from Title IX: participation in sports increased education as well as employment opportunities for girls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/16/health/16well.html|title=From Title IX, Evidence of Sports' Lasting Effects|last=Parker-Pope|first=Tara|date=2010-02-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Furthermore, the athletic participation by girls and women spurred by Title IX was associated with lower obesity rates. No other public health program can claim similar success.<ref name=\"gilderlehrman.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/history-by-era/seventies/essays/impact-title-ix|title=The Impact of Title IX &#124; The Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History|last=Winslow|first=Barbara|date=|publisher=Gilderlehrman.org|access-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====== Participation in leadership roles ======\nAlthough female participation in sports has increased due to Title IX, there has not been a similar effect in terms of women holding coaching or other managerial positions in sports. Most sport teams or institutions, regardless of gender, are managed by male coaches and managers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kimelsesser/2019/03/01/heres-why-womens-teams-are-coached-by-men/#22ad3566b3f9|title=Here's Why Women's Teams Are Coached by Men|last=Elsesser|first=Kim|date=March 1, 2019|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> For example, according to 2016 data, 33% of WNBA teams are led by women coaches or managers.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\">{{cite web|url=http://thesportjournal.org/article/examination-of-gender-equity-and-female-participation-in-sport/|title=Examination of Gender Equity and Female Participation in Sport|author=Senne|date=February 26, 2016|work=TheSportJournal.org|access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> The International Olympic Committee also consists of 20% female members.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\" /> The data presented also showed that 15% of athletic directors in colleges nationwide were females, and that number is much less in the southern states.<ref name=\"Senne_2016\" /> There are various reasons that have been suggested to account for this trend. Messner and Bozada-Deas (2009) suggest traditional gender roles may play a role and that society's historical division of labor leads to men volunteering as team coaches and women volunteering as team \"moms\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Messner|first=Michael|last2=Suzel|first2=Bozada-Deas|date=2009|title=Separating the Men from the Moms: The Making of Adult Gender Segregation in Youth Sports|url=http://www.michaelmessner.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/menfrommoms.pdf|journal=Gender & Society|volume=23|issue=1|pages=49\u201371|doi=10.1177/0891243208327363|via=}}</ref> Everhart and Chelladurai (1998) show that this phenomenon may be part of a larger cycle --- girls who are coached by men growing up are less likely to view themselves as coaches when they are adults, and so the number of female coaches decreases, meaning more girls are coached by men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Everhart|first=C. Bonnie|last2=Chelladurai|first2=Packianathan|date=1998|title=Gender Differences in Preferences for Coaching as an Occupation: The Role of Self-Efficacy, Valence, and Perceived Barriers|url=|journal=Research Quarterly for Exercise and Sport|volume=69|issue=2|pages=188\u2013200|doi=10.1080/02701367.1998.10607683|pmid=9635332}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carty |first1=Victoria |title=Textual Portrayals of Female Athletes: Liberation of Nuanced Forms of Patriarchy? |journal=Frontiers: A Journal of Women Studies |date=2005 |volume=26 |pages=132-155 |url=www.jstor.org/stable/4137402 |accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Canada====\n{{main|History of Canadian women}}\n[[File:Canada Summer Games by Steve Carmichael - Womens Volleyball 03.jpg|thumb|Women's [[volleyball]] at Canada Summer Games, 2017.]]\n\nSports are a high priority in Canadian culture, but women were long relegated to second-class status. There were also regional differences, with the eastern provinces emphasizing a more feminine \"girls rule\" game of basketball, while the Western provinces preferred identical rules.  Girls' and women's sport have traditionally been slowed down by a series of factors: both historically have low levels of interest and participation.  There were very few women in leadership positions in academic administration, student affairs or athletics and not many female coaches.  The media strongly emphasized men's sports as a demonstration of masculinity, suggesting that women seriously interested in sports were crossing gender lines with the male sports establishment actively hostile. Staunch feminists dismissed sports and thought of them as unworthy of their support. Women's progress was uphill; they first had to counter the common notion that women's bodies were restricted and delicate and that vigorous physical activity was dangerous. These notions where first challenged by the \"new women\" around 1900. These women started with bicycling; they rode into new gender spaces in education, work, and suffrage. The 1920s marked a breakthrough for women, including working-class young women in addition to the pioneering middle class sportswomen.<ref>M. Ann Hall, ''The Girl and the Game: A History of Women's Sport in Canada'' (Broadview Press, 2002)</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n{{main|Sport in the United Kingdom}}\nThe [[United Kingdom]] has produced a range of major international sports including: association football, rugby (union and league), cricket, netball, darts, golf, tennis, table tennis, badminton, squash, bowls, rounders, modern rowing, hockey, boxing, snooker, billiards, and curling.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nauright |first1=John |last2=Parrish |first2=Charles |title=Sports around the World: History, Culture, and Practice |date=2012 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781598843019 |pages=169}}</ref> In the 19th century, women primarily participated in the \"new games\" which included golf, lawn tennis, cycling, and hockey. Now, women also participate at a professional/international level in football, rugby, cricket, and netball.\n\nSince the late 1980s, Women In Sport,<ref>{{cite web |title=Women In Sport |url=https://www.womeninsport.org |website=Women In Sport |publisher=Charities Commission |accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> a non-profit organization, has hoped to transform sport for the benefit of women and girls in the UK. Based in London, the organization's mission is to \"champion the right of every woman and girl in the UK to take part in, and benefit from, sport: from the field of play to the boardroom, from early years and throughout her life\".\n\nThe [[Henley Royal Regatta]], just recently allowed women to compete at this prestigious rowing race. Although, the benefits that men receive at this race versus what women receive is still drastically different, there is progress within allowing women to compete competitively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rowing/2018/07/03/henley-royal-regatta-celebrates-move-towards-gender-equality/|title=Henley Royal Regatta celebrates further move towards gender equality with bump for women's races|last=Quarrell|first=Rachel|date=2018-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-08|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n===1960s to 2010s===\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2012}}\nBefore the 1960s, in the early 1800s women romped, skated, played ball games and some even boxed. It wasn't until the late 1900s when women started participating in organized sports. After the civil war wealthy women started playing country club sports such as golf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/sports/0|title=Sports {{!}} The Reader's Companion to U.S. Women's History - Credo Reference|website=search.credoreference.com|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\nOver the last fifty years, women's sports have developed substantially and made significant progress.\n\nTennis was a popular professional female sport from the 1970s onward, and it provided the occasion for a symbolic \"[[Battle of the Sexes (tennis)|battle of the sexes]]\" between [[Billie Jean King]] and [[Bobby Riggs]], which King won, thus enhancing the profile of female athletics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Maureen|date=2006|title=Reviewed Work: Billie Jean King: Portrait of a Pioneer|journal=Journal of Sport History|volume=33|issue=1|pages=113\u2013117|jstor=43610465}}</ref> [[Serena]] and [[Venus Williams]] were able to bring a strong female representation to sports. The sisters were both very successful with their accomplishments playing tennis and were able to set a strong positive model for other female tennis players and athletes as a whole. The two faced many obstacles along their journey to success, as they are African American women successfully conquering a predominately white sport. They were critiqued for their personal upbringings, their muscular builds, and the clothes they wore. James McKay and Helen Johnson described them as \"Ghetto Cinderellas,\" because of those very factors. Although they were not like other females playing sports, the women were able to bring a powerful new meaning and image to female athletics. Facing the challenges of racial and gender discrimination, the sisters enhanced and modeled a strong representation of both.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McKay |first1=James |last2=Johnson |first2=Helen |title=Pornographic Eroticism and Sexual Grotesquerie in Representations of African American Sportswomen |journal=Social Identities |date=November 4, 2008 |volume=14 |page=491-504}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of women's professional tennis in the 1970s, [[Women's professional sports|women's professional team sports]] did not achieve prominence until the 1990s, particularly in [[basketball]] and [[football (soccer)]], when the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]] was formed and the first [[FIFA Women's World Cup|Women's World Cup]]s and women's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Olympic soccer]] matches were held.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.pov.org/trueheartedvixens/timeline/|title=A Brief History of Women's Team Sports in America|last=American Documentary Inc.|date=2001-01-17|website=Archive.POV.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:USWNT Celebrates.jpg|thumb|The United States Women's National Soccer Team celebrating their 2012 CONCACAF Olympic Qualifiers Tournament championship.]]\nIn 1999, at the [[1999 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]] in [[Pasadena, California]], after scoring the fifth kick in the [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalty shootout]] to give the United States the win over [[China women's national football team|China]] in the final game, [[Brandi Chastain]] celebrated by spontaneously taking off her jersey and falling to her knees in a [[sports bra]].<ref name=\"Distillations\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|date=2017|title=Women's work|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/womens-work|journal=Distillations|volume=3|issue=1|pages=6\u201311|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref> While removing a jersey in celebration of a goal was common in men's soccer, it was highly unusual in women's football at the international level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-27189681|title=Why Women's World Cup champion Brandi Chastain bared her bra|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=July 13, 2014|website=BBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The image of her celebration has been considered one of the more famous and controversial photographs of a woman celebrating an athletic victory.<ref name=\"Longman\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/07/05/sports/soccer-the-sports-bra-seen-round-the-world.html|title=The Sports Bra Seen Round the World|author=Jere Longman|date=July 5, 2003|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/main/photos/1212/100-greatest-sports-photos-of-all-time-final/14 100 Greatest Sports Photos of All Time #14]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/history/2019/07/05/brandi-chastains-sports-bra-changed-womens-soccer-womens-history-years-ago/|title=Brandi Chastain's sports bra changed women's soccer - and women's history - 20 years ago|last=Rosenwald|first=Michael S.|date=July 7, 2019|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, it was announced that a statue of Chastain's celebration would be displayed at the [[Rose Bowl (stadium)|Rose Bowl]] to commemorate the twenty-year anniversary of the team's win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/world-cup/news/rose-bowl-stadium-unveils-bronze-statue-of-brandi-chastains-1999-world-cup-celebration/|title=Rose Bowl Stadium unveils bronze statue of Brandi Chastain's 1999 World Cup celebration|last=Benjamin|first=Cody|date=July 11, 2019|website=CBS Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nToday, women and girls compete professionally and as amateurs in virtually every major sport, though girls' participation in sports may be higher in the United States than in other places like Western Europe and Latin America.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=J.|last2=Hardman|first2=K.|date=2016-07-24|title=The State and Status of Physical Education in Schools in International Context|journal=[[European Physical Education Review]]|volume=6|issue=3|pages=203\u2013229|doi=10.1177/1356336x000063001}}</ref>  Additionally, the level of girls' participation typically decreases when it comes to the more violent contact sports in which boys overwhelmingly outnumber girls, particularly football,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/02/well/family/football-girls-concussions.html|title=More Girls Are Playing Football. Is That Progress?|last=de la Cretaz|first=Britni|date=February 2, 2018|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> wrestling,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/highschools/more-high-school-girls-are-wrestling-but-theyre-still-grappling-for-respect/2017/02/10/de00814a-e7ee-11e6-bf6f-301b6b443624_story.html|title=More high school girls are wrestling, but they're still grappling for respect|last=Needelman|first=Joshua|date=February 10, 2017|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> and boxing.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} (Some leagues for girls do exist, however, such as the [[Utah Girls Football League]] and [[Professional Girl Wrestling Association]].) These typical non-participation habits may slowly be evolving as more women participate in stereotypical male sports; for example, [[Katie Hnida]] became the first woman ever to score points in a [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[NCAA]] [[American football]] game when she kicked two [[Conversion (gridiron football)|extra points]] for the [[New Mexico Lobos football|University of New Mexico]] in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/katie-hnida-is-first-woman-to-play-in-division-i-football-game|title=Katie Hnida is first woman to play in Division I football game|date=November 16, 2009|website=History.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Heather Watson]] and [[Fu Yuanhui]] broke one of the last taboos in women's sport when both openly admitted they were menstruating, Watson after a self-described poor performance in a tennis match in 2015, and Fu at the Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.<ref>{{cite news |author=Paula Cocozza |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/shortcuts/2015/jan/21/menstruation-last-great-sporting-taboo |title=Menstruation: the last great sporting taboo &#124; Sport |newspaper=The Guardian |date= 2015-01-21|access-date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-37081669 |title=Rio 2016: Support as China's Fu Yuanhui breaks period taboo |first=Helier |last=Cheung |date=August 15, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=April 14, 2017 |via=www.BBC.co.uk|work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n== Professional sports ==\n{{Main|Women's professional sports}}\n\n=== Overview ===\n[[Professional sports]] refers to sports in which athletes are paid for their performance. Opportunities for women to play professional sports vary by country. Some women's professional sports leagues are directly affiliated with a men's professional sports league (like the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/howardmegdal/2018/11/19/wnba-cba-adam-silver-terri-jackson-discuss-stakes-and-the-grand-bargain/#58a36d495b7b|title=WNBA CBA Negotiations|last=Megdal|first=Howard|date=November 19, 2018|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>); others are independently owned and operated (like the [[National Women's Hockey League|NWHL]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/4/2/18291437/the-cwhl-folded-now-what-happens-to-womens-hockey-in-canada|title=The CWHL folded - now what happens to women's hockey in Canada?|last=Jay|first=Michelle|date=April 2, 2019|website=The Ice Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>).\n\nWhile women today do have the opportunity to play professional sports, the pay for [[women's professional sports]] is significantly lower than for men's,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kosofsky|first=Syda|date=1993|title=Toward Gender Equality in Professional Sports|url=https://repository.uchastings.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1029&context=hwlj|journal=Hastings Women's Law Journal|volume=4|issue=2|pages=213\u2013214|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/11/sports/us-womens-soccer-pay.html|title=The Long Fight for Pay Equality in Sports|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=March 11, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> a phenomenon known as the [[gender pay gap in sports]]. Many female professional athletes hold second jobs in addition to playing their respective sports due to their low salaries.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2015/0621/Outside-World-Cup-women-pro-soccer-players-struggle-to-make-ends-meet|title=Outside World Cup, women pro soccer players struggle to make ends meet|journal=Christian Science Monitor|last=Gass|first=Henry|date=June 21, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/reign/making-a-living-as-womens-pro-soccer-player-is-no-easy-task/|title=Why making a living as a women's pro soccer player is no easy task|last=Giambalvo|first=Emily|date=July 10, 2017|website=Seattle Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grandstandcentral.com/2019/sections/gender/when-professional-hockey-is-your-side-hustle/|title=When professional hockey is your side hustle|last=Varriano|first=Anthony|date=March 15, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Female professional athletes play in lower-quality, smaller facilities than male professional athletes and generally have lower fan attendance at games or matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/the-avenue/2019/03/22/when-it-comes-to-sports-men-and-women-dont-play-on-the-same-fields/|title=When it comes to sports, men and women don't play on the same fields|last=Schuetz|first=Jenny|date=March 25, 2019|website=Brookings|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://womenintheworld.com/2015/07/09/why-you-should-think-twice-about-ignoring-womens-sports/|title=Why you should think twice about ignoring women's sports|last=Iversen|first=Katja|date=July 9, 2015|website=Women in the World|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> Many women's professional sports are not regularly broadcast on live television like many men's professional sports,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooky|first=Cheryl|last2=Messner|first2=Michael A.|last3=Hextrum|first3=Robin H.|date=April 4, 2013|title=Women Play Sport, But Not on TV: A Longitudinal Study of Televised News Media|journal=Communication and Sport|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1177/2167479513476947|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a7f3c72db565618d35a7188a1b274631aae218b8}}</ref> but are live-streamed on platforms such as [[Twitter]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-announces-20-game-twitter-livestream-schedule-for-2019-season/|title=WNBA Announces 20-Game Twitter Livestream Schedule for 2019 Season|last=|first=|date=May 1, 2019|website=WNBA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> or [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/nwhl-signs-three-year-streaming-deal-with-twitch-receives-broadcasting-rights-fee|title=NWHL signs three-year streaming deal with Twitch|last=Clinton|first=Jared|date=September 5, 2019|website=The Hockey News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> instead.\n\nNot only do female athletes themselves face inequality, but so too do women looking to enter the business side of sports. Research has shown that women occupy leadership positions in sports business at a lower rate than men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Burton|first=Laura|date=May 2015|title=Underrepresentation of women in sport leadership: A review of research|journal=Sport Management Review|volume=18|issue=2|pages=155\u2013165|doi=10.1016/j.smr.2014.02.004}}</ref> When women ''do'' occupy the same positions as men, they may be paid less,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Humphreys|first=Brad R.|date=August 2000|title=Equal Pay on the Hardwood: The Earnings Gap Between Male and Female NCAA Division I Basketball Coaches|journal=Journal of Sports Economics|volume=1|issue=2|pages=299\u2013307|doi=10.1177/152700250000100306|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/694dc115d425dce85b433f60b19dbd3b7443805c}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Osborne|first=Barbara|last2=Yarbrough|first2=Marilyn V.|date=2000|title=Pay Equity for Coaches and Athletic Administrators: An Element of Title IX?|url=https://repository.law.umich.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1469&context=mjlr|journal=University of Michigan Journal of Law Reform|volume=34|issue=1|pages=231\u2013251|via=}}</ref> although some research has shown revenue-specific variables may be more relevant than gender-specific variables when examining compensation levels.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Traugutt|first=Alex|last2=Sellars|first2=Nicole|last3=Morse|first3=Alan L.|date=April 2018|title=Salary Disparities Between Male and Female Head Coaches: An Investigation of the NCAA Power Five Conferences|url=https://digitalcommons.kent.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1054&context=sport|journal=The Journal of SPORT|volume=6|issue=1|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlthough several professional women's sports leagues have been established throughout the world in the post-Title IX era, they are generally behind in terms of exposure, funding, and attendance compared to the men's teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-xpm-2014-feb-10-la-sp-womens-sports-leagues-20140211-story.html|title=Women's pro sports leagues have trouble staying in the game|last=Rohlin|first=Melissa|last2=Baxter|first2=Kevin|date=February 10, 2014|website=LA Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fink|first=Janet|date=2015|title=Female athletes, women's sport, and the sport media commercial complex: Have we really \"come a long way, baby\"?|journal=Sport Management Review|volume=18|issue=3|pages=331\u2013342|doi=10.1016/j.smr.2014.05.001}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliviaabrams/2019/06/23/why-female-athletes-earn-less-than-men-across-most-sports/#1ba69a2d40fb|title=Why Female Athletes Earn Less Than Men Across Most Sports|last=Abrams|first=Olivia|date=June 23, 2019|website=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> However, there are notable exceptions. The 2015 Women's World Cup final was the most-watched soccer game ever in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/07/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-final-was-most-watched-soccer-game-in-united-states-history.html|title=Women's World Cup Final Was Most-Watched Soccer Game in United States History|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=July 6, 2015|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2015}}</ref> And in 2017, [[Portland Thorns FC]] of the [[National Women's Soccer League|NWSL]] had higher average attendance than several men's professional teams, including 15 [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] teams, 13 [[National Hockey League|NHL]] teams, and 1 [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/13/sports/soccer/portland-thorns-nwsl.html|title=A Blueprint for Women's Sports Success - But Can It Be Copied?|last=Murray|first=Caitlin|date=October 13, 2017|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The Thorns' 2019 season saw an even higher average attendance of 20,098.<ref>{{cite web|title=2019 NWSL Attendance|url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2019-nwsl-attendance/ |publisher=Soccer Stadium Digest |date=October 12, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> This was higher than all but one of the 30 NBA teams in the 2018\u201319 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/attendance/_/year/2019 |title=NBA Attendance Report \u2013 2019 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> all but three of the 31 NHL teams in the 2018\u201319 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nhl/attendance/_/year/2019 |title=NHL Attendance Report \u2013 2019 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> 15 of the 24 MLS teams in the 2019 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=2019 MLS Attendance|url=https://soccerstadiumdigest.com/2019-mls-attendance/ |publisher=Soccer Stadium Digest |date=October 6, 2019 |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref> and 6 of the 30 MLB teams in the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2019-misc.shtml |title=2019 MLB Attendance & Team Age |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Active women's professional leagues and associations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Country\n!Sport\n!League or Association Name\n|-\n|Australia\n|Australian rules football\n|[[AFL Women's]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's National Basketball League]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Golf\n|[[ALPG Tour]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Netball\n|[[Suncorp Super Netball]]\n|-\n|Australia\n|Association football\n|[[W-League (Australia)|Westfield W-League]]\n|-\n|China\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's Chinese Basketball Association]]\n|-\n|China\n|Golf\n|[[China LPGA Tour]]\n|-\n|Denmark\n|Handball\n|[[Danish Women's Handball League|HTH Ligaen]]\n|-\n|England\n|Association football\n|[[FA Women's Super League]]\n|-\n|Europe\n|Golf\n|[[Ladies European Tour]]\n|-\n|France\n|Association football\n|[[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]]\n|-\n|Germany\n|Association football\n|[[Frauen-Bundesliga]]\n|-\n|Japan\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA of Japan Tour]]\n|-\n|Mexico\n|Association football\n|[[Liga MX Femenil]]\n|-\n|New Zealand\n|Netball\n|[[ANZ Premiership]]\n|-\n|Russia\n|Basketball\n|[[Russian Women's Basketball Premier League]]\n|-\n|South Korea\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA of Korea Tour]]\n|-\n|Turkey\n|Volleyball\n|[[Turkish Women's Volleyball League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Basketball\n|[[Women's National Basketball Association]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[LPGA|Ladies Professional Golf Association]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[Legends Tour]] (age 45 and over)\n|-\n|USA\n|Golf\n|[[Symetra Tour]] (second-tier tour)\n|-\n|USA\n|Ice hockey\n|[[National Women's Hockey League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Lacrosse\n|[[Women's Professional Lacrosse League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Lacrosse\n|[[United Women's Lacrosse League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Association football\n|[[National Women's Soccer League]]\n|-\n|USA\n|Softball\n|[[National Pro Fastpitch]]\n|-\n| Worldwide\n| Tennis\n| [[Women's Tennis Association]]\n|}\n\n==Battle for equality==\n<!-- [[Gender and sport]] redirects here. The anchor insulates against section title changes, please do not remove it. -->\nThe [[2012 London Olympics]] were the first games of their kind in which women competed in every sport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/london-2012-is-this-the-womens-olympics |title=London 2012: was this the women's Olympics? \u2013 Channel 4 News |publisher=Channel4.com |date=2012-08-12 |access-date=2016-03-24}}</ref> The fight for women to gain equality on national levels and in professional leagues, in terms of pay and better funding, has continued; however sports still remain dominated by men, financially and globally. Gender remains a selective and primary factor in terms of determining if women are able-bodied as men and if they should get the same treatment in terms of sports.<ref>Henne, K. (2014). The \"Science\" of Fair Play in Sport: Gender and the Politics of Testing. ''Signs: Journal of Women in Culture & Society'', ''39''(3), 787\u2013812.</ref> It is often said{{By whom|date=April 2017}} that sports are a thing for men, and has become a stereotypical notion within society. Negative gender-based characteristics such as masculinity and femininity have been described as the deciding factor in order to play sports, and has often been held as justifiable dismissing sports equity.<ref>Spaaij, R., Farquharson, K., & Marjoribanks, T. (2015). Sport and Social Inequalities. ''Sociology Compass'', ''9''(5), 400\u2013411. doi:10.1111/soc4.12254</ref> Although there are various purposes and outcomes of organized teamsport participation in Western cultures, a consistent finding is that sport is principally organized around the political project of physically and symbolically elevating men over women [1]. There was evidence throughout the study that notions of audience interest or preference were based on personal beliefs and assumptions\u2014rather than evidence or research\u2014and in some cases it was clear that these beliefs and assumptions still prioritized the coverage of men's professional sports.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Joseph|first=Lauren J.|last2=Anderson|first2=Eric|date=2016-09-02|title=The influence of gender segregation and teamsport experience on occupational discrimination in sport-based employment|journal=Journal of Gender Studies|language=en|volume=25|issue=5|pages=586\u2013598|doi=10.1080/09589236.2015.1070712|issn=0958-9236}}</ref>\n\nThe pay gap in women sports is a controversial issue.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Women athletes, in their respective fields, are often get paid far less than their male counterparts, and this has been true for a long  time. The difference between the American men's and women's soccer teams' salaries serves as an example regarding pay inequality.  Women on the U.S national team earned $99,000 per year, while men earned $263,320 if they were to win 20 exhibition matches.<ref name=\"auto2\">WALTERS, J. (2016, April 1). TAKING A CLOSER LOOK AT THE GENDER PAY GAP IN SPORTS. Retrieved January 23, 2017, from <nowiki>http://www.newsweek.com/womens-soccer-suit-underscores-sports-gender-pay-gap-443137</nowiki></ref> There is a substantial gap in rewards in regards to winning the [[FIFA World Cup]]. The German men's national team earned 35 million dollars, while the American women's national team earned 2 million dollars after winning the World Cup.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> The battle in equality for fair pay divulges in to other sports in which men earn far more than women. Golf is another sport which has a significant rising female presence. In 2014, the [[PGA Tour|PGA tour]] awarded US$340 million in prize money for men's tournaments, compared to 62 million dollars awarded to the [[LPGA|LPGA Tour]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|author=Brennan, A.|date=May 5, 2016|title=Which Sports Have The Largest And Smallest Pay Gaps?|access-date=January 23, 2017|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andrewbrennan/2016/05/05/the-pay-discrimination-in-sports-we-wish-didnt-exist-will-only-dissipate-with-womens-leadership/#48f31f9941d6}}</ref> Basketball is another sport which has surged in popularity in the last few decades and has significant female presence. In the United States, the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] organizes top-level professional basketball competition for both sexes, with men playing in the NBA proper and women in the [[Women's National Basketball Association|WNBA]]. A WNBA player's minimum salary is $38,000, while an NBA player's minimum salary is $525,000.<ref name=\":3\" /> An average NBA player makes over $5 million while an average WNBA player makes $72,000.<ref name=\":2\" /> Male athletes generate more revenue for their teams. However, when one compares the revenue earned to salary received, women athletes often get an extremely low{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=April 2017}} salary in comparison to the revenue they generate and their accomplishments. Although female athletes have come a long way since the establishment of professional sports, they still remain far behind in terms of pay (and ticket sales) and media coverage.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nIn September 2018, the [[World Surf League]] announced equal pay for both male and female athletes for all events. This decision has contributed to the conversation in the world of professional sports surrounding equality .\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn September 2015, the [[Australia women's national soccer team|Australian women's national soccer team]] (nicknamed the Matildas) announced that it had canceled a sold-out tour of the United States due to a dispute with the [[Football Federation Australia|Football Federation of Australia]] (FFA) over their pay. Their salary was below [[Minimum wage law|minimum wage]] levels in Australia. The Matildas requested health care, [[Parental leave|maternity leave]], and improved travel arrangements, as well as an increased salary. The players also said that their low salaries forced them to remain living at home, since they could not afford rent, and their strict training schedule meant they were unable to get another job.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/09/11/football/australia-matildas-women-soccer-pay/index.html|title=Australian women's soccer team boycott sell-out U.S. tour over pay|last=McCafferty|first=Georgia|date=September 11, 2015|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/09/12/matildas-boycott-us-tour-as-they-call-foul-on-gender-pay-gap.html|title=Matildas boycott US tour as they call foul on gender pay gap|last=Smyth|first=Jamie|date=September 12, 2015|website=CNBC.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, a new pay deal was announced for players in Australia's national soccer league, the [[W-League (Australia)|W-League]]. The deal included an increase in wages, an increase in the salary cap, improved medical standards, and a formal maternity policy. Some commentators have attributed the success of the new W-League deal to the Matildas' boycott in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/sep/11/w-league-breaks-new-ground-with-pay-deal-for-trailblazers-of-womens-sport|title=W-League breaks new ground with pay deal for 'trailblazers' of women's sport|last=Australian Associated Press|date=September 10, 2017|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/wleague-ffa-and-pfa-unveil-new-pay-deal-for-womens-soccer/news-story/ee0dcf9abb601663ee67dcb3f308253a|title=W-League, FFA and PFA unveil new pay deal for women's soccer|last=Gatt|first=Ray|date=September 12, 2017|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the FFA announced a new contract with the union [[Professional Footballers Australia]] (PFA) in which the Matildas and the [[Australia national soccer team|men's national team]] (the Caltex Socceroos) will receive equal shares of total player revenue and equal resources. In addition, the guaranteed minimum salary for a player on the Matildas will increase as a result of this deal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/06/sports/soccer/australia-soccer-matildas-equal-pay.html|title=Australian Women and Men's Soccer Teams Reach Deal to Close Pay Gap|last=Zraick|first=Karen|date=November 6, 2019|website=The New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== China ===\nOne of the earliest examples of women's sports in modern China was [[Qiu Jin]]. Qiu Jin, a Chinese revolutionary during the late 1800s and early 1900s, trained women to be soldiers alongside men in sports societies. They were taught fencing, riding, and gymnastics.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Freeing the female body : inspirational icons|author=Mangan, J. A.|author2=Fan, Hong|date=2001|publisher=F. Cass|isbn=0714650889|location=London|oclc=45363183}}</ref> According to Susan Bronwell, the most important moment for women's sports in China came in 1981 with a Chinese victory in the [[1981 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1981 FIVB Women's World Cup]] in Tokyo, Japan. This victory made the female volleyball players household names in China, though the victory was portrayed as the work of leading male government officials like Ma Qiwei, [[He Long]], and [[Zhou Enlai]], who helped contribute at various stages to the success of the team. The victory symbolized a growth of women's sports in China after the [[Cultural Revolution]] of the 1960s and 1970s, wherein many athletes were suppressed:<ref>{{Cite book|title=Beijing's games : what the Olympics mean to China|last=Brownell, Susan.|date=2008|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780742556409|location=Lanham, Md.|oclc=173243758|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/beijingsgames00brow}}</ref>\n{{Block quote|text=In the years following the women's volleyball victory, female athletes generally had greater success in international sports than males, and so they became the symbolic figureheads in the revival of Chinese nationalism.|sign=Susan Bronwell|source=Beijing's Games, Pg. 107}}\n[[File:London 2012 Olympics 052 Basketball Arena (2) China (7682998022).jpg|thumb|The Chinese women's basketball team prepares to compete at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.]]\nContemporary Chinese sports teams are noted for their wide breadth of participation by female athletes, specifically in the [[Olympic Games]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Noland|first=Marcus|last2=Stahler|first2=Kevin|date=2014|title=What Goes into a Medal: Women's Inclusion and Success at the Olympic Games|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/dfe11fa406f813d37ae4d1f7e2c654c6b338c714|doi=10.2139/ssrn.2512876|issn=1556-5068}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brownell|first=Susan|date=1996-02-01|title=Representing gender in the Chinese nation: Chinese sportswomen and Beijing's bid for the 2000 olympics|journal=Identities|volume=2|issue=3|pages=223\u2013247|doi=10.1080/1070289X.1996.9962536|issn=1070-289X}}</ref> A [[Herfindahl\u2013Hirschman Index|Herfindahl Index]] (a measure often used in economics to show the degree of concentration when individuals are classified by type, and a lower number indicates higher diversity) showing Female Participation in the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympics]] indicated China's female Olympic delegation, the fourth largest present, to be the second most spread out across all events at 0.050, compared to higher numbers from over 190 other delegations. The same index showed the ratio of women to men to be 7 to 10. 213 total female athletes participated.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Roche|first=Maurice|date=November 2008|title=Putting the London 2012 Olympics into perspective: the challenge of understanding mega-events|journal=Twenty-First Century Society|volume=3|issue=3|pages=285\u2013290|doi=10.1080/17450140802447212|issn=1745-0144}}</ref> In total, approximately 60% of Chinese Olympic gold medals were earned by female athletes over the last 8 Olympic games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/espnw/sports/article/19492563/world-fame-100-china-female-athletes-winning-competition-losing-fame-game|title=Chinese women winning in sports but losing in fame game|date=2017-05-30|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2019-10-24}}</ref> Challenges to equality remain such as media representation. According to Yu Chia Chen, female Asian athletes receive much less coverage than their male counterparts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yu|first=Chia-Chen|date=June 2009|title=A Content Analysis of News Coverage of Asian Female Olympic Athletes|journal=International Review for the Sociology of Sport|volume=44|issue=2\u20133|pages=283\u2013305|doi=10.1177/1012690209104796|issn=1012-6902}}</ref> Another report indicates Chinese girls and women are also less likely to be exposed to sports programming on television.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lagaert|first=Susan|last2=Van Houtte|first2=Mieke|last3=Roose|first3=Henk|date=2019-09-01|title=Gender Differences in Sport Spectatorship and (Fe)male Adolescents' Gender Identity, Experienced Pressure for Gender Conformity and Gender Role Attitudes|journal=Sociology of Sport Journal|volume=36|issue=3|pages=233\u2013243|doi=10.1123/ssj.2018-0022|issn=0741-1235}}</ref>\n\n=== Ireland ===\nIn October 2017, the [[Irish Rugby Football Union]] (IRFU) advertised an available position for head coach of the [[Ireland women's national rugby union team|Irish women's national rugby team]]. The job was advertised as \"part-time,\" \"casual,\" and available on six-month basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/rugby-union/2017/10/22/english-womens-rugby-players-lend-support-irish-protest/|title=English women's rugby players lend support to Irish protest|last=Rowan|first=Kate|date=October 22, 2017|website=Telegraph|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> Players expressed their disagreement with the decision, believing it was a sign that the IRFU was disrespecting and not prioritizing the women's game. In response to this announcement, the players highlighted what they perceived as the IRFU's lack of commitment to the long-term development of the women's game by wearing bracelets with \"#Legacy\" written on them for games with their club teams in the All Ireland League.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/rugby/international/irish-women-s-rugby-legacy-campaign-gathers-pace-1.3264755|title=Irish women's rugby 'Legacy' campaign gathers pace|last=Cummiskey|first=Gavin|date=October 22, 2017|website=The Irish Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nThe [[Jamaica women's national football team|Jamaican women's national soccer team]] (nicknamed the Reggae Girlz) participated in the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]]. This was the first [[FIFA Women's World Cup|Women's World Cup]] the country had qualified for, and the country was also the first Caribbean country to ever qualify.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womensworldcup/teams/team/1885011/profile/|title=Jamaica Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, in September 2019, members of the team, including [[Khadija Shaw]] and [[Allyson Swaby]], posted a graphic on [[Instagram]] with captions stating that they had not been paid by the [[Jamaica Football Federation]] (JFF) for nine months of work. They announced that the team would not participate in any future tournaments until they received payment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soccer.nbcsports.com/2019/09/03/jamaica-womens-team-on-strike-after-not-being-paid/|title=Jamaica women's team on strike after not being paid|last=Bonn|first=Kyle|date=September 3, 2019|website=NBC Sports|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> JFF President Michael Ricketts later announced that the team would be paid by the end of September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mls/article234660082.html|title=Jamaica's Reggae Girlz say 'No Pay, No Play,' threaten strike over unpaid salary|last=Kaufman|first=Michelle|date=September 3, 2019|website=The Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, the Reggae Girlz began playing again, and they won their group in the [[2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship qualification|Qualification Tournament]] for the [[2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship|2020 CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Competition]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1085649/jamaica-win-concacaf-olympic-qualifier|title=Jamaica thump St. Lucia at CONCACAF Women's Olympic Qualifying Championship|last=Etchells|first=Daniel|date=6 October 2019|website=Inside the Games|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Jamaica national netball team|Jamaican national netball team]] (nicknamed the Sunshine Girls) is ranked 4th in the world, as of July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://netball.sport/events-and-results/current-world-rankings|title=Current World Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=International Netball Federation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, the team has not been well-funded, and had to resort to [[crowdfunding]] to attend the [[2019 Netball World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/all-woman/game-changers_176411?profile=1440|title=Game changers - modern-day athletes who are fighting for women's rights in sports|last=Knight|first=Candiece|date=October 7, 2019|website=The Jamaica Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> After receiving support from sponsors, the Sunshine Girls were able to go to the tournament, where they placed 5th overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/laptestnews/_Sunshine_Girls_beat_Malawi,_claim_fifth_spot?profile=1548|title=Netball World Cup: Sunshine Girls beat Malawi; claim fifth spot|last=Myers|first=Sanjay|date=July 21, 2019|website=The Jamaica Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Muslim world===\n{{Main|Muslim women in sport}}\n[[File:Sania Mirza (5993143538).jpg|thumb|upright=.65|[[Sania Mirza]], a former world No. 1 in women's tennis doubles, is an Indian Muslim.]]\n\nMuslim women are less likely to take part in sport than Western non-Muslims.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/5286568.stm Muslims 'face barriers' over sport]. [[BBC Sport]]. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref> This is particularly so for [[women in Arab societies]]. The traditions of [[Islamic modesty]] in dress and requirements for women's sport to take place in a [[Sex segregation|single-sex environment]] make sports participation more difficult for devout female adherents. The lack of availability of suitably modest sports clothing and sports facilities that allow women to play in private contributes to the lack of participation. Cultural norms of women's roles and responsibilities towards the family may also be a source of discouragement from time-consuming sports practice.<ref name=\"Women1\">[http://sites.duke.edu/wcwp/research-projects/middle-east/muslim-women-in-sport/#_ftn7 Muslim Women in Sport]. Soccer Politics. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref><ref name=\"Women2\">Maesam, T-AbdulRazak, et al (2010). [http://www.japss.org/upload/13.maesam.pdf The Perspective of Arabic Muslim Women toward Sport Participation]. ''Journal of Asia Pacific Studies'', Vol 1, No 2, 364\u2013377. Retrieved on 2015-01-30.</ref>\n\nHowever, Islamic tenets and religious texts suggest that women's sports in general should be promoted and are not against the values of the religion. The Quranic statements that followers of Islam should be healthy, fit and make time for leisure are not sex-specific. The prophet [[Muhammad]] is said to have raced his wife [[Aisha]] on several occasions, with Aisha beating him the first couple of times. Correspondingly, some scholars have proposed that Muslim women's lack of engagement with sport is due to cultural or societal reasons, rather than strictly religious ones.<ref name=\"Women1\" /><ref name=\"Women2\" />\n\nHowever, besides religious testaments, there are many barriers for Muslim women in relation to sports participation. A significant barrier to Muslim women's sports participation is bans on the Islamic headscarf, commonly known as the [[hijab]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ayub|first=Awista|date=2011-04-14|title=A Closer Look at FIFA's Hijab Ban: What it Means for Muslim Players and Lessons Learned|journal=SAIS Review of International Affairs|volume=31|issue=1|pages=43\u201350|doi=10.1353/sais.2011.0010|issn=1945-4724}}</ref> FIFA instituted such a ban in 2011, preventing the Iranian women's national football team from competing.<ref name=\":0\" /> They have since repealed the ban, but other organizations, including FIBA, maintain such regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://muslimmatters.org/2016/07/19/muslim-basketball-players-urge-fiba-to-allow-hijab/|title=\u00bb Muslim Basketball Players Urge FIBA To Allow Hijab|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> At the same time, many Muslim female athletes have achieved significant success in athletic competitions. Some have also used sports towards their own empowerment, working for women's rights, education, and health and wellbeing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dubey|first=Bipin Kumar|last2=Dubey|first2=Binayak Kumar|last3=Acharya|first3=Jayashree|date=2010-09-01|title=Participation in sport as an assessment of women empowerment|url=http://bjsm.bmj.com/content/44/Suppl_1/i62.2|journal=British Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=44|issue=Suppl 1|pages=i62|doi=10.1136/bjsm.2010.078725.208|issn=1473-0480}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=worldfocusonline|title=Female soccer players shoot down Turkish taboos|date=2009-09-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IIsM93orVn8|accessdate=2016-11-16}}</ref><ref>Contomichalos, Stephanie. \"How is Sport Employed as a Vehicle for Redefining Gender Identity in Islamic Societies?\" ''Retrieved'' 4, no. 7 (2010): 2015.</ref>\n\nIranian women were banned from attending a volleyball game and an Iranian girl was arrested for attending a match. Iran was given the right to host the International Beach Volleyball tournament, and many Iranian women were looking forward to attending the event. However, when the women tried to attend the event, they were disallowed, and told it was forbidden to attend by the FIVB. The women took to social media to share their outrage; however the Federation of International Beach volleyball refuted the accusations, saying it was a misunderstanding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2016/08/17/iranian-women-should-not-face-arrest-and-threats-for-watching-volleyball/|title=Iranian women should not face arrest and threats for watching volleyball|author=|date=August 17, 2016|work=NYTimes.com|access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> This is one of the instances of unfair treatment of women, trying to participate in supporting their teams in Iran.\n\n\nIn October 2018 Iran announced that, after 40 years, it would allow women to enter sport arenas.<ref>[https://dailytimes.com.pk/312207/football-stadium-politics/ Football stadium politics]</ref> On September 22, 2019, the Iranian authorities assured [[FIFA]] that women would be able to attend the October qualifier of [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] in [[Tehran]], stated [[Gianni Infantino]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.compuserve.com/sports/story/0002/20190922/KBN1W7072_1|title=Iran has 'assured' women can attend qualifier: Infantino|website=CompuServe|accessdate=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Nigeria ===\nIn 2016, the [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigerian women's national soccer team]], known as the Super Falcons, won the [[2016 Africa Women Cup of Nations]]. The players alleged that they had not received their earned bonuses from winning the tournament owed to them by the [[Nigeria Football Federation]] (NFF). The NFF promised that it would pay them, but said the \"money [was] not readily available at the moment.\" In response, players engaged in a sit-in at their hotel as well as publicly demonstrated outside Nigeria's [[National Assembly (Nigeria)|National Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/africa/nigerian-womens-soccer-team-protest-unpaid-victory-bonuses|title=Nigerian Women's Soccer Team Protest at Unpaid Victory Bonuses|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2016|website=VOA News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the Super Falcons participated in the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup|2019 Women's World Cup]] and were eliminated from the tournament in the Round of 16. Following their elimination, the players engaged in another sit-in at their hotel, refusing to leave Paris until the NFF paid them the bonuses and daily allowances they had earned both from the World Cup as well as from other matches played in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/fifa-womens-world-cup/story/3882567/nigeria-stage-sit-in-at-wwc-over-unpaid-bonuses|title=Nigeria Stage Sit-In at WWC Over Unpaid Bonuses|last=Udoh|first=Colin|date=June 22, 2019|website=ESPN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Norway===\n\nNorwegian sports are shaped by the values associated with them. For example, aggression generally is associated with males and being personable, with females. However, in terms of Norwegian handball, a study done by the Norwegian School of Sports and Sciences shows that gender is disregarded when the sport is covered in the media. The same study revealed that Women's handball is covered and followed as equally if not more than the men's team. In contrast to international handball coverage, the Norwegian coverage of Men's and Women's handball are discussed in the media using the same or similar verbiage. While they are especially noticeable in handball, equality and opportunity in Norwegian sports is not limited to the handball. Many top-female athletes from a number of sports have come from Norway. The act of playing or coaching were described slightly differently but categorized as successful using similar terms despite the gender of the coach or the player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sciencenordic.com/unique-norwegian-female-sports-heroes|title=The unique Norwegian female sports heroes|date=2014-09-30}}</ref>\n\n[[Ada Hegerberg]] is a highly skilled and decorated Norwegian soccer player, having won numerous [[UEFA Women's Champions League|Champions League]] and [[Division 1 F\u00e9minine]] titles with French club [[Olympique Lyonnais F\u00e9minin|Olympique Lyonnais]]. She also won the first-ever women's [[Ballon d'Or F\u00e9minin|Ballon D'Or]], a prestigious award given to the best soccer player in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/05/football/ada-hegerberg-ballon-dor-norway-spt-intl/index.html|title=Ada Hegerberg: The world's best player won't be at the Women's World Cup|last=Lewis|first=Aimee|last2=Davies|first2=Amanda|date=December 5, 2018|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref> However, in 2017, she stopped playing with the [[Norway women's national football team|Norwegian national team]], citing unequal pay and conditions between the women's team and the men's team as her reason for stepping away from the team. She said she would no longer play for the national team until she felt that it was more respected by the [[Norwegian Football Federation]] and the culture surrounding women's soccer had improved, which meant she did not participate in the high-profile [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/soccer/2019/6/5/18653682/ada-hegerberg-womens-world-cup-norway-skipping|title=Why Ada Hegerberg, the best player in soccer, is skipping the World Cup|last=Dator|first=James|date=June 5, 2019|website=SB Nation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== South Africa ===\nBetween 2004 and 2008, the previously highly successful [[South Africa women's national football team|South African women's national soccer team]], known as Banyana Banyana, began to struggle on the field due to a lack of a permanent coach. Members of the [[South African Football Association]] (SAFA) attributed the declining quality of play to the players' \"lack of femininity\" (Engh 2010), and the players were instructed to take etiquette classes and maintain stereotypical feminine hairstyles, as well as wear more feminine uniforms while playing. In response, players threatened to strike unless they were able to return to their preferred styles of dress.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Engh|first=Mari Haugaa|date=2010|title=The battle for centre stage: Women's football in South Africa|journal=Agenda: Empowering Women for Gender Equity|volume=85|issue=85|pages=11\u201320|jstor=27917362}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Banyana Banyana was not paid the agreed-upon amount owed to them after qualifying for the [[2018 Africa Women Cup of Nations]] (AWCON), and they protested by not returning their official national team uniforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kayafm.co.za/banyana-banyana-payment-woes/|title=Banyana Banyana payment woes|last=|first=|date=July 3, 2018|website=Kayafm|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> In January 2019, the team was again not paid their stipends and bonuses, despite finishing in second place at AWCON. They threatened to strike by not attending interviews or team practices, as well as not playing in a game against the [[Netherlands women's national football team|Dutch national team]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mg.co.za/article/2019-01-18-00-banyanas-payment-woes-continue/|title=Banyana yet to be paid SAFA monies|last=Feltham|first=Luke|last2=Mokwena|first2=Busisiwe|date=January 17, 2019|website=Mail & Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> However, in May 2019, it was announced that Banyana Banyana would receive equal pay with the men's team heading into the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/south-africa-national-womens-football-team-banyana-banyana-to-get-equal-pay/|title=South Africa's National Women's Football Team to Receive Equal Pay|last=Durosomo|first=Damola|date=May 24, 2019|website=OkayAfrica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\n\nIn Sweden, public funds are mostly given to men's hockey and football, and the women's team are left without proper funding. In 2016, Al Jazeera published an article bringing the discrimination that female Swedish athletes face to light by mentioning the double standard put on female athletes in terms of having to work double and still not receive the recognition or pay of the men's teams. Sweden is recognized as being a feminist country, however the wage gap is significant between male and female athletes. In 2013, Swedish striker, Zlatan Ibrahimovic earned  $16.7 million a year playing for Paris Saint-German, whereas Lotta Schellin who played for Lyon in France only earned $239,720. The wage gap is also evident among coaches. The difference in pay is evident in how male athletes and female athletes are able to spend their time between games. Women often have to work between training and games to make a living and to pay for their training camps, whereas men have that time to recuperate and relax; men also don't pay to attend training camps.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2016/03/swedish-female-athletes-face-discrimination-160315110758946.html|title=Swedish female athletes face discrimination &#124; Europe &#124; al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the [[Sweden women's national ice hockey team|Swedish women's national ice hockey team]] boycotted the team's training camp and the Five Nations Tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2019/08/16/swedish-womens-hockey-players-boycott-over-pay-dispute/|title=Swedish women's hockey players boycott over pay dispute|last1=Dure|first1=Beau|date=2019-08-16|website=NBC Sports|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref> In a movement they called #F\u00f6rFramtiden (in English, \"For the Future\"), all 43 players invited to camp cited lack of equal pay as well as various instances of poor treatment by [[Swedish Ice Hockey Association|Svenska Ishockeyf\u00f6rbundet]] (the Swedish Ice Hockey Association, or SIF) toward the national team, including, but not limited to:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/8/18/20805729/for-the-future-how-team-sweden-reached-their-limit-damkronorna-sdhl|title=For the future: How Team Sweden reached their limit|last1=Foster|first1=Meredith|date=2019-08-18|website=The Ice Garden|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n* Team travel conditions - traveling by ferry instead of by plane to games; arriving to games one day before a tournament began, without accounting for time differences and jet lag\n* Team uniforms - players are provided men's clothing by SIF, not women's clothing\n* Nutrition - players are provided expired products\n* Lack of development - players allege that SIF has not adequately created a program to foster development of women's hockey at the youth level\n\nThe [[4 Nations Cup|Four Nations Cup]], originally scheduled for November 2019, was canceled by SIF due to the players' dispute with the federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/09/13/four-nations-cup-cancelled-amid-team-swedens-equality-battle/|title=Women's Four Nations Cup cancelled amid Team Sweden's equality battle|last1=Ingemi|first1=Marisa|date=2019-09-13|website=The Boston Herald|accessdate=9 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the boycott, it was announced in October 2019 that the players had reached a new agreement with the federation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.swehockey.se/Nyheter/nyheterfransvenskaishockeyforbundet/2019/Oktober2016/damkronornaklaraforspel/|title=The Crowns are Ready for Play|last=|first=|date=October 15, 2019|website=Svenska Ishockeyf\u00f6rbundet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref> and that the team will begin training in November 2019 and play in a tournament against [[Switzerland women's national ice hockey team|Switzerland]], [[Finland women's national ice hockey team|Finland]], and [[Germany women's national ice hockey team|Germany]] in December 2019. The new deal includes terms guaranteeing performance-based bonuses and additional compensation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/10/15/20915396/damkronorna-players-boycott-is-over-a-deal-has-been-reached-with-the-swedish-ice-hockey-association|title=Damkronorna players' boycott is over, a deal has been reached with the Swedish Ice Hockey Association|last=Jay|first=Michelle|date=October 15, 2019|website=The Ice Garden|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n[[File:Training of Seattle Mist Lingerie Football 0154.jpg|thumb|Players of [[Legends Football League]] do a [[warming up]] exercise, USA]]\n\nWomen make up 54% of enrollment at 832 schools that responded to an NCAA gender equity study in 2000; however, females at these institutions only account for 41% of the athletes. Before Title IX, 90% of women's college athletic programs were run by women, but by 1992 the number dropped to 42% since Title IX requires that there are equal opportunities for both genders.<ref name=\"Steiner 1995\"/>  This violates Title IX's premise that the ratio of female athletes to male athletes should be roughly equivalent to the overall proportion of female and male students.<ref name=\"garber1\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/gen/womenandsports/020619title9.html|title=Landmark law faces new challenges even now|last=Garber|first=Greg|accessdate=February 16, 2012}}</ref> Many of the issues today often revolve around the amount of money going into men's and women's sports. According to 2000\u20132001 figures, men's college programs still have many advantages over women's in the average number of scholarships (60.5%), operating expenses (64.5%), recruiting expenses (68.2%) and head coaching salaries (59.5%).<ref name=\"garber1\"/> Other forms of inequality are in the coaching positions. Before Title IX, women coached 90% of women's teams; in 1978 that percentage dropped to 58, and in 2004 it dropped even more to 44 percent.<ref name=\"coakley255\">{{cite book|title=Sports in Society|last=Coakley|first=Jay|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=2007|location=New York|page=255}}</ref> In 1972, women administered 90 percent of women's athletic programs, and in 2004 this fell to 19 percent. Also in 2004, 18 percent of all women's programs had no women administrators.<ref name=\"coakley255\"/> In 2004, there were 3,356 administrative jobs in NCAA women's athletic programs and of those jobs, women held 35 percent of them.<ref name=\"coakley255\"/>\n\nThe fight for equality extends to the wallet. On March 30, 2016, five players from the U.S. women's soccer team filed a federal complaint of wage discrimination against U.S. Soccer, the governing body that pays both the men's and women's team.<ref name=\"Love equals\">{{cite web|url=https://loveequals.net/blogs/sports/u-s-women-s-soccer-team-sued-federation-for-equal-pay|title=U.S. Women's Soccer Team Sued Federation For Equal Pay}}</ref> The complaint argues that U.S. Soccer pays players on the women's team as little as forty percent of what it pays players on the men's team. This pay discrepancy exists despite the fact that the women's team has been much more successful in international competitions; the women's team has won four Olympic gold medals and three of the last five Women's World Cups, while the men's team has never won either of these competitions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/01/sports/soccer/uswnt-us-women-carli-lloyd-alex-morgan-hope-solo-complain.html?_r=0|title=Top Female Players Accuse U.S. Soccer of Wage Discrimination|author=Andrew Das|date=2016-03-31|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2016-04-02}}</ref>\n\n===World conferences===\n\nIn 1994, the International Working Group on Women and Sport organized the first World Conference on Women and Sport in Brighton, United Kingdom, where the Brighton Declaration was published. The IWG hosted further world conferences every four years, with the result of the Windfoek Call for Action (1998), Montreal Tool Kit (2002) and Brighton Plus Helsinki 2014 Declaration (2014). The conferences pretend to \"develop a sporting culture that enables and values the full involvement of women in every aspect of sport and physical activity\", by \"increas[ing] the involvement of women in sport at all levels and in all functions and roles\".<ref>[http://www.fisu.net/medias/fichiers/EN_Helsinki_calls_the_world_of_sport_to_LEAD_THE_CHANGE_BE_THE_CHANGE_2.pdf 6th IWG World Conference on Women and Sport 2014 \u2013 The Legacy Document]</ref>\n\n== Media coverage ==\n[[File:Alem\u00e3s levam ouro no v\u00f4lei de praia em Copacabana 1038687-18.08.2016 ffz-9127.jpg|thumb|Spectators and media personnel take photos even as Brazil's [[\u00c1gatha Bednarczuk]] hugs her support staff after winning a women's [[beach volleyball]] match in [[2016 Summer Olympics]].]]\n\nMedia coverage for women's sports is significantly less than the coverage for men's sports. Substantial research indicates that women's sports and female athletes gain only a small fraction of sports media coverage worldwide. Research that has examined why this is the case suggested this can be attributed to three particular factors that govern sports newswork: the male-dominated sports newsroom, ingrained assumptions about readership, and the systematic, repetitive nature of sports news.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherwood|first=Merryn|last2=Osborne|first2=Angela|last3=Nicholson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherry|first4=Emma|date=December 2017|title=Newswork, News Values, and Audience Considerations: Factors That Facilitate Media Coverage of Women's Sports|journal=Communication & Sport|language=en|volume=5|issue=6|pages=647\u2013668|doi=10.1177/2167479516645535|issn=2167-4795}}</ref> In 1989, a study was conducted that recorded and compared the amount of media coverage of men and women's sports on popular sports commentary shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=When it comes to women in sports, TV news tunes out |url=https://news.usc.edu/82382/when-it-comes-to-women-in-sports-tv-news-tunes-out/}}</ref> Michael Messner and his team in 2010 analyzed three different two-week periods by recording the amount of time that the stories were on air and the content of the stories. After recording sports news and highlights, they wrote a quantitative description of what they saw and a qualitative description of the amount of time that story received.<ref>Messner, Michael A., and Cheryl Cooky (2010): [https://dornsifecms.usc.edu/assets/sites/80/docs/tvsports.pdf \"Gender in Televised Sports\"]. n. pag. Dornsife.usc.edu. Center for Feminist Research, University of Southern California, June 2010.</ref>\n\nDuring that first year that the research was conducted in 1989, it was recorded that 5% of the sports segments were based on women's sports, compared to the 92% that were based on men's sports and the 3% that was a combination of both. In the late 1900s Women's Sports started to gain popularity in the media because of their talent in the Olympics.<ref>{{cite journal |title=An Imperceptible Difference: Visual and Textual Constructions of Femininity in Sport Illustrated and Sports Illustrated for Women |url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=4&sid=b1aa5c2a-a43c-40c6-97e5-7d193c12cfdd%40sdc-v-sessmgr01}}</ref> In 1999, women's sports coverage reached an all-time high when it was recorded at 8.7%. It maintained its higher percentages until it reached an all-time low in 2009, decreasing to 1.6%. The researchers also measured the amount of time that women's sports were reported in the [[news ticker]], the strip that displays information at the bottom of most news broadcasts. When recorded in 2009, 5% of ticker coverage was based on women's sports, compared to the 95% that was based on men's sports. These percentages were recorded in order to compare the amount of media coverage for each gender.\n\nWhen researching the actual amount of time that women's sports stories were mentioned, they focused specifically on differences between the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Women's National Basketball Association]]. They recorded two different time periods: when they were in season and when they were off-season. The WNBA had 8 stories, totaling 5:31 minutes, during their season, which was less than the NBA, which had a total of 72 stories, totaling approximately 65:51 minutes. During the off-season, the WNBA did not receive any stories or time on the ticker, while the NBA received a total of 81, which were approximately 50:15 minutes. When compared, the WNBA had a total of 8 stories and 5:31 minutes while the NBA had 153 stories and 1:56:06 hours. The actual games had several differences in the way the games were presented. The findings were that WNBA games had lower sound quality, more editing mistakes, fewer views of the shot clock and fewer camera angles. There was less verbal commentary and visual statistics about the players throughout the games as well.<ref>\"Gender Stereotyping in Televised Sports.\" LA 48 Foundation. June 2010. Web. November 2014. http://www.la84.org/gender-stereotyping-in-televised-sports/</ref> The quality of the stories has also significantly changed. In past studies, women were sexualized, portrayed as violent, or portrayed as girlfriends, wives and mothers. Female athletes were often included in gag stories that involved sexual dialogue or emphasized their bodies. In Australia, the wives of the men's cricket team members were given more media coverage than the players on the women's cricket team, who also had won more games than the men's rugby team.<ref>Holmes, Tracy. \"After Homophobia Let's Tackle Prejudice Against Women's Sports.\" ABC. April 2014. Web. November 2014. http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/lifematters/after-homophobia-lets-tackle-prejudice-against-womens-sport/5381930</ref> In 2009, ''SportsCenter'' broadcast segments called \"Her Story\", which was a commentary that highlighted women's athletic careers.<ref>\"Gender in Televised Sports News and Highlights Shows, 1989\u20132009.\" Center for Feminist Research, University of California. June 2010. Web. November 2014</ref>\n\nIn newspapers articles, coverage on men's sports once again had a greater number of articles than women's sports in a ratio of 23\u20131. In 1990, a study was conducted that recorded and compared the amount of media coverage of men and women's sports on popular newspapers. They analyzed four different sports magazines for three months and recorded the number of women's sports stories that were featured and the content of the stories. Women's sports made up 3.5%, compared to the 81% of men's coverage. The lengths of these articles were 25\u201327% shorter than the length of men's articles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.la84.org/coverage-of-womens-sports-in-four-daily-newspapers/ |title=Coverage of Women's Sports in Four Daily Newspapers \u2013 LA84 Foundation |author= |date= |work=LA84.org |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> There was an international frenzy in 2012 when the first woman that represented Saudi Arabia in the 2012 Olympics competed in track. That was the most women's sports coverage that there had been in several years.Women played 90 minutes of football, 80 minutes of rugby, 18 holes of golf and ran the same distance in a marathon as men. Exactly 12 months later, the newspapers returned to featuring 4% of articles on women's sports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/07/sport/olympics-women-equality-attar/index.html |title=Why has coverage of women's sport stopped post Olympics? - CNN.com |first=Amanda |last=Davies |date=August 7, 2013 |work=CNN.com |access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref> This same trend can be seen with regards to the FIFA World Cup. The 2015 Women's World Cup Final had an average of 25.4 million American viewers throughout the duration of the match, and peaked at 30.9 million viewers.<ref>Deitsch, Richard. \"USA-Japan's Women's World Cup Final Shatters American TV \nRecord Ratings.\" Futbol Planet. Sports Illustrated, 6 July 2015. Web. 8 May 2016.</ref> It was the most-viewed game of soccer ever in the United States\u2013men's or women's\u2013by a margin of almost 7 million viewers. Despite this jump in viewership of women's soccer in the U.S., television broadcasting of the women's professional soccer league in the U.S. remained much lower than that of the men's league. Fox Sports Network (the company that owns the rights to broadcast the National Women's Soccer League) broadcast 3 regular season NWSL games and 34 Major League Soccer regular-season games during the 2016 seasons. The dearth of coverage of women's sports is evidenced by the low number of segments (i.e., stories) in our sample. Of the 934 local network affiliate news segments (over 12 hr of broadcasts), 880 were on men's sports (or approximately 11\u00bd hr), 22 segments (or nearly 18 min) were on gender-neutral sports (e.g., a horse race, coverage of the Los Angeles [LA] marathon, and a recreational sports event), and only 32 segments (about 23 min) featured women's sports. SportsCenter's numbers were similar. Of the 405 total SportsCenter segments in our sample (nearly 14 hr), 376 covered men's sports (slightly over 13 hr), 16 segments were on gender-neutral sports (just over 20 min), and only 13 segments featured women's sports (approximately 17 min).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cooky|first=Cheryl|last2=Messner|first2=Michael A.|last3=Musto|first3=Michela|date=September 2015|title=\"It's Dude Time!\": A Quarter Century of Excluding Women's Sports in Televised News and Highlight Shows|journal=Communication & Sport|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|pages=261\u2013287|doi=10.1177/2167479515588761|issn=2167-4795}}</ref>\n\nA recent article from the Wall Street Journal states \u201cfrom 2016 to 2018, women's games generated about $50.8 million in revenue compared with $49.9 million for the men, according to U.S. soccer's audited financial statements<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bachman |first1=Rachel |title=U.S. Women's Soccer Games Outearned Men's Games |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-womens-soccer-games-out-earned-mens-games-11560765600. |website=Wall Street Journal |publisher=Dow Jones & Company |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\u201d (Bachman, 2019). These numbers contrasts the idea that women's sports are not entertaining enough for the viewer or typical fan by $1.9 million. This idea stems from the male dominated sports perspective, which constantly undermines the perception of quality, effort, and potential that women's soccer exhibits. However, we can see through the caliber of women's soccer displayed most recently within the Women's FIFA World Cup of 2019 that it was on par if not better than the level of play of their male counterparts.{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} The U.S. Women's National Team scored 13 goals against Thailand in their opening match, the most goals scored in any World Cup match in history. Media outlets though may remain concerned that increased coverage of women's sport will lead to a reduction in audience draw and advertising revenue. \n\nAmy Godoy-Pressland conducted a study that investigated the relationship between sports reporting and gender in Great Britain. She studied Great Britain's newspapers from January 2008 to December 2009 and documented how media coverage of men's sports and women's sports was fairly equal during the Olympics and then altered after the Olympics were over. \"Sportswomen are disproportionately under-represented and the sheer quantity and quality of news items on sportsmen demonstrates how male athletes are represented as dominant and superior to females.\" She also documented how women's bodies were sexualized in photographs and written coverage, noting that the women featured were either nude, semi-nude, or wearing revealing clothing. \"The sexualization of sportswomen in Sunday reporting is commonplace and aimed at the mostly male readership. It promotes the idea of female aesthetics over achievements, while the coverage of women not directly involved in sport misrepresents the place of women in sport and inferiorizes real sportswomen's achievements.\"<ref>\"Women underrepresented, sexualized in weekend sports reporting\" ''Science Daily''. September 2013. Web. December 2014. https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2013/09/130918090756.htm</ref> The media has the ability to create or prevent interest in women's sports. Excluding women's sports from the media makes it much less likely for young girls to have role models that are women athletes.<ref>Donna A. Lopiano, Ph.D., (2008). Media Coverage of Women's Sports is Important, (2), Sports Management Resources, http://www.sportsmanagementresources.com/library/media-coverage-womens-sports</ref> According to Tucker Center for Research on Girls & Women in Sport at the University of Minnesota 40% of all athletes in the United States are women but women's sports only receive about 4% of sports media coverage.<ref>University of Minnesota (Producer) and PBS, (2014). Media Coverage & Female Athletes, http://video.tpt.org/video/2365132906/</ref> This amount of coverage has decreased in the last 20 years although there has been a major increase in women athletes.\n\nMedia coverage has slightly increased and this is mostly due to social networking.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} Social media has further exposed women sports out to the public world, and often at a much greater rate than traditional news media. Traditional media has also improved its coverage of women's sports through more exposure time and using better equipment to record the events. Recent research has shown that in the past twenty years, camera angles, slow motion replays, quality and graphics regarding the presentation of women sports has gradually improved.<ref name=\"Cooky, C. 2012\">Cooky, C., & Lavoi, N. (2012). Playing but losing women's sports after title ix. ''Contexts,'' ''11''(1), 42\u201346. {{jstor|41960748}}</ref> However, mainstream media still is far behind in its showcasing of female sports in comparison to that of men's. A study has shown that ESPN, which began airing women NCAA tournament in 2003, aired eleven women tournament segments in comparison to one-hundred men's tournament segments.<ref name=\"Cooky, C. 2012\"/> ESPN and other sports outlets are airing more female-oriented sporting events; however the length of the segments are very small. This representative data is showcases a main part of the minimal interaction the media has with women athletes. Media coverage of women sports in the United States has further justified the divisional hierarchy faced by women athletes in terms of popularity and coverage. Scholarly studies (Kane, M. J., LaVoi, N. M., Fink, J. S. (2013) also show that when women athletes were given the option to pick a photo of a picture that would increase respect for their sport, they picked an on-the-court competency picture. However, when women athletes were told to pick a picture that would increase interest in their sport, 47% picked a picture that sexualized the women athlete.<ref>Kane, M. J., LaVoi, N. M., Fink, J. S. (2013). Exploring elite female athletes' interpretations of sport media images: A window into the construction of social identity and \"selling sex\" in women's sports. Communication & Sport, 1(3), 269\u2013298. doi: 10.1177/2167479512473585</ref> The UK is more representative than the United States with the BBC giving women's sports about 20% of their sports coverage (BBC spokesperson). Many women athletes in the UK do not see this as adequate coverage for the 36% of women who participate in sports.<ref>Gareth Lewis, (2014). Nicole Cooke calls for women's sport to have equal coverage on BBC, (p. 2), BBC News Wales, https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-26653208</ref> [[NewsChain]] is the first commercial publisher totally dedicated to women's sport coverage based in the UK.\n\n== Sex-specific sports injuries ==\nThere are some common sports injuries for which female athletes may be at a higher risk than male athletes.\n\nSeveral studies have shown that female athletes are more likely to tear their [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|anterior cruciate ligaments]] (ACLs) than male athletes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DeHaven|first=Kenneth E.|last2=Lintner|first2=David|date=1986|title=Athletic injuries: Comparison by age, sport, and gender|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=14|issue=3|pages=218\u2013224|doi=10.1177/036354658601400307|pmid=3752362}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ito|first=Eri|last2=Iwamoto|first2=Jun|displayauthors=1|date=2015|title=Sex-specific differences in injury types among basketball players|journal=Open Access Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=6|pages=1\u20136|pmc=4284005|pmid=25565908|doi=10.2147/OAJSM.S73625}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lindenfeld|first=Thomas|last2=Schmitt|first2=David|displayauthors=1|date=1994|title=Incidence of Injury in Indoor Soccer|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=22|issue=3|pages=364\u2013371|doi=10.1177/036354659402200312|pmid=8037278}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zelisko|first=John|last2=Noble|first2=H. Bates|displayauthors=1|date=1982|title=A comparison of men's and women's professional basketball injuries|journal=The American Journal of Sports Medicine|volume=10|issue=5|pages=297\u2013299|doi=10.1177/036354658201000507|pmid=6814271}}</ref> There are several different theories about why women are more prone to this injury, but there is no consensus on one theory in particular. The difference in injury risk may be due to female-specific hormonal changes associated with the menstrual cycle, or due to different skeletal and muscular structures (like a wider pelvis, stronger quadriceps than hamstrings, or more elastic ligaments) that cause women to place more stress on and more easily stretch the ACL than men.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Editorial|date=2016|title=The female ACL: Why is it more prone to injury?|journal=Journal of Orthopaedics|volume=13|issue=2|pages=A1\u2013A4|pmc=4805849|pmid=27053841|doi=10.1016/S0972-978X(16)00023-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orthonc.com/your-health/preventing-acl-tears-why-are-acl-tears-more-common-in-female-athletes|title=Preventing ACL Tears - Why are ACL Tears More Common in Female Athletes?|last=Galland|first=Mark|date=|website=Orthnonc.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beaconortho.com/blog/risk-acl-injuries-female-athletes/|title=The Risk of ACL Injuries in Female Athletes|last=|first=|date=|website=Beaconortho.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bcm.edu/news/sports-medicine/female-athletes-at-higher-risk-for-acl-tears|title=Female athletes at higher risk of ACL tears|last=Pathak|first=Dipali|date=August 12, 2015|website=Baylor College of Medicine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFemale athletes are also more prone to concussions than male athletes. They exhibit more visible symptoms of a concussion than male athletes and for a longer period of time than male athletes, a phenomenon known as the \"concussion gap.\" <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mollayeva|first=Tatyana|last2=El-Khechen-Richandi|first2=Graziella|displayauthors=1|date=2018|title=Sex and Gender Considerations in Concussion Research|journal=Concussion|volume=3|issue=1|pages=CNC51|pmc=6094024|pmid=30202593|doi=10.2217/cnc-2017-0015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frommer|first=Leah|last2=Gurka|first2=Kelly|displayauthors=1|date=2011|title=Sex Differences in Concussion Symptoms of High School Athletes|url=|journal=Journal of Athletic Training|volume=46|issue=1|pages=76\u201384|doi=10.4085/1062-6050-46.1.76|pmid=21214354|pmc=3017493}}</ref> However, there is no consensus on the reason women are more prone to concussions than men or experience symptoms differently. Some theories have been that women have smaller, more breakable nerve fibers in their brains,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dolle|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Jaye|first2=Andrew|displayauthors=1|date=2018|title=Newfound sex differences in axonal structure underlie differential outcomes from in vitro traumatic axonal injury|url=|journal=Experimental Neurology|volume=300|issue=|pages=121\u2013134|doi=10.1016/j.expneurol.2017.11.001|pmid=29104114|pmc=6495524}}</ref> that their necks are weaker and so their brains accelerate more sharply on impact,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tierney|first=R|last2=Sitler|first2=MR|displayauthors=1|date=2005|title=Gender differences in head-neck segment dynamic stabilization during head acceleration|journal=Med Sci Sports Exerc|volume=37|issue=2|pages=272\u2013279|pmid=15692324|doi=10.1249/01.MSS.0000152734.47516.AA|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1196f9acb8d4ca46a3f48728b0c0bad8b6e8dbf2}}</ref> or fluctuating hormones during menstrual cycles that make them more susceptible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/news/story/3965/menstrual-cycle-influences-concussion-outcomes.aspx|title=Menstrual Cycle Influences Concussion Outcomes|last=University of Rochester Medical Center|date=November 13, 2013|website=URMC.Rochester.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\n== Gallery of women athletes today ==\n<gallery caption=\"Women athletes today\">\nFile:Greek women's indoor volleyball team in bikini uniform.jpg|Greek women's indoor [[volleyball]] team at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]\nFile:Camogie.jpg|thumb|Camogie players at [[Croke Park]] in 2006\nFile:Meseret Defar Valencia 2008.jpg|[[Olympic Games]] track gold medalist [[Meseret Defar]] of Ethiopia\nFile:1 patti 060123 1Ds 7037.jpg|Master [[Hao Zhihua]], the most accomplished female [[Wushu (sport)|Wushu]] athlete in China's history\nFile:Ellen van Dijk, Time Trial Olympic Summer Games 2012.jpg|Dutch cyclist [[Ellen van Dijk]], at the [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's road time trial|2012 Summer Olympics]]\nFile:Fernanda BRITO 5962.JPG|Fernanda Brito of Chile playing women's doubles tennis at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 2010\nFile:Russia 4 x 400 m Paris 2011.jpg|Russian women's team pose after winning 4 \u00d7 400 m relay at [[2011 European Athletics Indoor Championships]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Dong Jinxia: ''Women, Sport and Society in Modern China: Holding Up More Than Half the Sky'', Routledge, 2002, {{ISBN|0-7146-8214-4}}\n*Allen Guttmann: ''Women's Sports: A History'', Columbia University Press 1992, {{ISBN|0-231-06957-X}}\n*Helen Jefferson Lenskyj: ''Out of Bounds: Women, Sport and Sexuality.''  Women's Press, 1986.\n*Helen Jefferson Lenskyj: ''Out on the Field: Gender, Sport and Sexualities''.  Women's Press, 2003.\n*[https://www.npr.org/2011/08/02/138919822/the-nation-sports-dont-need-sex-to-sell The Nation: Sports Don't Need Sex To Sell] \u2013 NPR, Mary Jo Kane \u2013 August 2, 2011\n* Else Trangbaek & [[Arnd Kr\u00fcger]] (eds.): ''Gender and Sport from European Perspectives''. Copenhagen: University of Copenhagen 1999\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports|Feminism}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Women's professional sports]]\n* [[Mixed-sex sports]]\n*[[Bikini in popular culture#Sports|Bikini as sportswear]]\n*[[Sex verification in sports]]\n* [[Timeline of women's sports]]\n* [[Title IX]] (Patsy T. Mink Equal Opportunity in Education Act)\n* [[Women's Sports Foundation]]\n* [[Major women's sport leagues in North America]]\n* [[WTSN (TV channel)]]\n* [[Association for Intercollegiate Athletics for Women]] (defunct since 1982)\n* [[Misogyny in sports]]\n* [[Participation of women in the Olympics]]\n* [[Sportswear (activewear)]]\n* [[Legends Football League]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* https://www.irishtimes.com/student-hub/tackling-gender-barriers-to-sporting-equality-1.2619267\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|Women's sports}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140527131109/http://www.northnet.org/stlawrenceaauw/timeline.htm History of Women in Sports Timeline]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041115121944/http://www.personal.psu.edu/users/s/j/sjf187/olympics/6.html Heraea Games]\n\n{{Women's sports}}\n{{Sport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Women's sports}}\n[[Category:Women's sports| ]]\n[[Category:Sports by type]]\n", "name_user": "Derpboi9000", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Women%27s_sports"}
