y-e6frg6n6-1111118361254 |title=Submarine for sale as group's dream sinks in a sea of red tape |last=Stewart |first=Cameron |date=19 December 2008 |work=The Australian |accessdate=24 April 2015}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/asio-eyes-mystery-group-after-attempt-to-buy-sub/story-e6frg6n6-1225814011176 |title=ASIO eyes mystery group after attempt to buy sub |last=Stewart |first=Cameron |date=28 December 2009 |work=The Australian |accessdate=28 December 2009}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://mpnews.com.au/2015/02/05/wyuna-heads-to-docklands/ |title=Wyuna heads to Docklands |last=Taylor |first=Stephen |date=5 February 2015 |work=The News |publisher=Mornington Peninsula News Group |accessdate=24 April 2015}}\n*{{cite news |title=Sundance's unheralded short film and grant winners |first=Bob |last=Tourtellotte |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2011/01/27/sundances-unheralded-short-film-and-grant-winners/ |agency=Reutersblogs |date=26 January 2011 |accessdate=29 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201162421/http://blogs.reuters.com/fanfare/2011/01/27/sundances-unheralded-short-film-and-grant-winners/ |archivedate=1 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}\n*{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110930040 |title=H.M.A.S. OTAMA COMES HOME Manufacturing strengthens |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=18 December 1978 |accessdate=24 April 2015 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110588990 |title=CYCLONE DAMAGE Fiji's PM appeals to nation for help |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=9 April 1980 |accessdate=24 April 2015 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}\n*{{cite news |title=Subs leave harbour behind |work=The Daily Telegraph |page=4 |date=30 March 1999}}\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.shippingtimes.co.uk/item_10195.html |title=Submarine fails to sell on Ebay |date=19 December 2008 |work=The Shipping Times |accessdate=24 April 2015}}\n\n'''Press releases'''\n*{{cite press release |last=Nelson |first=Brendan |title=Australian Submarine History Lands at Hastings with $500 000 Centenary of Federation Grant |date=3 October 2001 |publisher=Australian Department of Defence |url=http://www.defence.gov.au/minister/7tpl.cfm?CurrentId=1057 |accessdate=8 October 2013}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.maritimecentre.com.au/ Website of the Victorian Maritime Centre]\n\n<!-- non-breaking space to keep AWB drones from altering the space before the navbox-->\n\n{{Oberon class submarine}}\n{{Australian submarines}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otama}}\n[[Category:Oberon-class submarines of the Royal Australian Navy]]\n[[Category:Ships built on the River Clyde]]\n[[Category:1975 ships]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=HMAS Otama sub.jpg\n|Ship caption=''Otama'' in Western Port Bay in June 2011\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=Australia\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Australia|naval}}\n|Ship builder=[[Scotts Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]]\n|Ship laid down=25 May 1973\n|Ship launched=3 December 1975\n|Ship commissioned=27 April 1978\n|Ship decommissioned=15 December 2000\n|Ship motto=\"Unseen We Seek\"\n|Ship nickname=*One of the \"Mystery Boats\"\n*The \"Gucci Boat\"\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship status=Awaiting preservation\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Oberon|submarine}}\n|Ship displacement=*1,610&nbsp;tons standard\n*2,030&nbsp;tons surfaced\n*2,410&nbsp;tons submerged\n|Ship length={{convert|295.2|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|26.5|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draught={{convert|18|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion=*2 \u00d7 Admiralty Standard Range supercharged V16 diesel generators\n*2 \u00d7 English Electric motors\n*3,500&nbsp;bhp, 4,500&nbsp;shp\n*2 shafts\n|Ship speed=*{{convert|12|kn}} surfaced\n*{{convert|17|kn}} submerged\n*{{convert|11|kn}} at snorkel depth\n|Ship range={{convert|9000|nmi}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship test depth={{convert|200|m|ft}}\n|Ship complement=*'''As launched:'''\n*8 officers, 56 sailors\n*'''At decommissioning:'''\n*8 officers, 60 sailors\n|Ship sensors=*'''Sonar:'''\n*Atlas Elektronik Type CSU3-41 bow array\n*BAC Type 2007 flank array\n*Sperry [[BQG-4]] Micropuffs rangefinding array\n*Sonartech PIPRS intercept processor\n*'''Radar:'''\n*Kelvin Hughes Type 1006\n|Ship armament=*'''Torpedo tubes:'''\n*6 \u00d7 {{convert|21|in|cm|adj=on}} bow tubes\n*2 \u00d7 short-length {{convert|21|in|cm|adj=on}} stern tubes (later removed)\n*'''1996 payload:''' Mix of 20:\n*[[Mark 48 torpedo|Mark 48 Mod 4]] torpedoes\n*[[Boeing Harpoon|UGM-84 Sub Harpoon]] missiles\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''HMAS ''Otama'' (SS 62/SSG 62)''' was an {{sclass-|Oberon|submarine}} of the [[Royal Australian Navy]] (RAN). Built in Scotland, the submarine was the last of the class to enter service when commissioned into the RAN in 1978. ''Otama'' was a specialist, one of two \"Mystery Boats\", fitted with additional surveillance and intelligence-gathering equipment.<ref name=AFRmag>Barker, ''The Mystery Boats''</ref> ''Otama'' was routinely deployed on classified operations to obtain intelligence on [[Soviet Pacific Fleet]] vessels and [[People's Liberation Army Navy|Chinese Navy]] vessels, and conducted associated coastal surveillance, throughout Asia.<ref name=AFRmag/>\n\nThe submarine was part of the RAN's largest [[flag-showing cruise]] in the Indian Ocean during 1980. From 1983 to 1985, she underwent an extensive upgrade. On Monday 3 August 1987\n, two submariners died when ''Otama'' submerged while they were still working in the [[Sail (submarine)|fin]]. ''Otama'' remained in service until late 2000; a delay from her original planned decommissioning date to help attenuate the problems with the replacement {{sclass-|Collins|submarine|1}}s.\n\n''Otama'' was sold to the Western Port Oberon Association in 2001, which planned to preserve her as a [[museum vessel]] as part of the proposed [[Victorian Maritime Centre]]. Submissions to build the [[maritime museum]] at various locations on the [[Mornington Peninsula]] were repeatedly rebuffed. In late 2008, the submarine was listed for sale on [[eBay]], but despite several expressions of interest, ''Otama'' was not sold. In-principle approval to build the Victorian Maritime Centre on [[reclaimed land]] adjacent to the Western Port Marina at [[Hastings, Victoria|Hastings]] was granted in 2013, but as of 2016, planning permits have not been approved.\n\n==Design and construction==\n{{main|Oberon-class submarine}}\nThe ''Oberon'' class was based heavily on the preceding [[British Porpoise-class submarine|''Porpoise'' class]] of submarines, with changes made to improve the vessels' hull integrity, sensor systems, and stealth capabilities.<ref name=compedium>Chant, ''A Compedium of Armaments and Military Hardware'', pp. 167\u20138</ref> Eight submarines were ordered for the RAN, in two batches of four.<ref name=Cooper188>Cooper, in Stevens, ''The Royal Australian Navy'', p. 188</ref> The first batch was approved in 1963, and the second batch (including ''Otama'') was approved during the late 1960s, although two of these were cancelled before construction started in 1969, with the funding redirected to the [[Fleet Air Arm (RAN)|Fleet Air Arm]].<ref name=Cooper194>Cooper, in Stevens, ''The Royal Australian Navy'', p. 194</ref><ref>Bastock, ''Australia's Ships of War'', p. 394-5</ref> This was the fourth time the RAN had attempted to establish a [[Royal Australian Navy Submarine Service|submarine branch]].<ref name=OxCom399>Dennis et al., ''The Oxford Companion to Australian Military history'', p. 399</ref>\n\nThe submarine was {{convert|295.2|ft|m|1}} long, with a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|26.5|ft|m|1}}, and a [[Draught (hull)|draught]] of {{convert|18|ft|m|1}} when surfaced.<ref name=Janes96/> At full load [[Displacement (nautical)|displacement]], she displaced 2,030&nbsp;tons when surfaced, and 2,410&nbsp;tons when submerged.<ref name=Janes96/> The two propeller shafts were each driven by an English Electric motor providing {{convert|3,500|bhp|lk=in|0}} and {{convert|4,500|shp|lk=in|0}}; the electricity for these was generated by two Admiralty Standard Range supercharged V16 diesel generators.<ref name=Shaw15>Shaw, ''HMAS Onslow'', p. 15</ref> The submarine could travel at up to {{convert|12|kn|lk=in|0}} on the surface, and up to {{convert|17|kn|0}} when submerged, had a maximum range of {{convert|9000|nmi|lk=in|0}} at {{convert|12|kn|0}}, and a [[test depth]] of {{convert|200|m|ft|0}} below sea level.<ref name=Janes96/><ref name=Shaw15/> When [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]], the boat had a [[Ship's company|company]] of 8 officers and 56 sailors, but by the time she [[Ship commissioning#Ship decommissioning|decommissioned]], the number of sailors had increased to 60.<ref name=Janes96/><ref name=Shaw15/> In addition, up to 16 trainees could be carried.<ref name=Shaw15/>\n\nThe main armament of the ''Oberon''s consisted of six {{convert|21|in|mm|0|adj=on}} [[torpedo tube]]s.<ref name=compedium/> The [[British 21 inch torpedo#21 inch Mark VIII|British Mark 8 torpedo]] was initially carried by the submarine; this was later replaced by the [[Wire-guided torpedo|wire-guided]] [[British 21 inch torpedo#21 inch Mark 23 Grog|Mark 23]].<ref name=Shaw21>Shaw, ''HMAS Onslow'', p. 21</ref> After a multi-year refit ending in 1985, ''Otama'' was upgraded to carry United States Navy [[Mark 48 torpedo]]es and [[Boeing Harpoon|UGM-84 Sub Harpoon]] [[anti-ship missile]]s; the last Australian ''Oberon'' to undergo the Submarine Weapon Update Program.<ref name=OxCom399/><ref name=Sharpe22/><ref name=Owen32>Owen, in Mitchell, ''Australian Maritime Issues 2010'', p. 32</ref> As of 1996, the standard payload of an Australian ''Oberon'' was a mix of 20 Mark 48 Mod 4 torpedoes and Sub Harpoon missiles.<ref name=Janes96/> Some or all of the torpedo payload could be replaced by [[Stonefish (mine)|Mark 5 Stonefish]] [[Naval mine|sea mines]], which were deployed through the torpedo tubes.<ref name=Janes96>Sharpe (ed.), ''Jane's Fighting Ships, 1996\u20131997'', p. 23</ref><ref name=Shaw21/> On entering service, two stern-mounted, short-length {{convert|21|in|cm|adj=on|0}} torpedo tubes for Mark 20 anti-submarine torpedoes.<ref name=Shaw19/> However, the development of steerable wire-guided torpedoes made the less-capable aft-firing torpedoes redundant; they were closed off, and later removed during a refit.<ref name=Shaw19>Shaw, ''HMAS Onslow'', p. 19</ref>\n\n''Otama'' was [[Keel laying|laid down]] by [[Scotts Shipbuilding and Engineering Company]] at [[Greenock, Scotland]] on 25 May 1973, launched on 3 December 1975, and [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] into the RAN on 27 April 1978.<ref name=Sharpe22>Sharped (ed.), ''Jane's Fighting Ships 1992\u201393'', p. 22</ref> The submarine was due to enter service in 1976, but faulty high-power electrical cabling had been installed in ''Otama'' and [[Sister ship|sister boat]] {{HMAS|Orion||2}}; stripping out and replacing the cabling delayed each submarine's construction by two years.<ref name=Owen31>Owen, in Mitchell, ''Australian Maritime Issues 2010'', p. 31</ref> The delay meant that the two boats could be fitted with [[Passive Underwater Fire Control Feasibility System|Micropuffs]] rangefinding [[sonar]] during construction that the earlier built boats were due to receive as an upgrade.<ref name=Owen32.3>Owen, in Mitchell, ''Australian Maritime Issues 2010'', p. 32-3</ref>\n\n''Otama'' was the sixth and final ''Oberon''-class submarine to enter service with the RAN.<ref>Stevens, in Stevens, ''The Royal Australian Navy'', opp. p. 32</ref> The boat's name comes from a North Queensland [[Aboriginal Australians|Aboriginal]] word meaning \"dolphin\"; this was a break in RAN tradition, which had used the names of explorers and pioneers for previous submarines.<ref>Bastock, ''Australia's Ships of War'', p. 394</ref><ref name=DeptDefPR/> ''Otama'' was assigned the [[pennant number]] 62.<ref>Gillett, ''Australian and New Zealand Warships since 1946'', p. 77</ref> The high standard of internal fittings compared to the rest of the class led to the \"[[Gucci]] Boat\" nickname.<ref name=SealBlake83>Seal & Blake, ''Century of Silent Service'', p. 83</ref>\n\n''Otama'' received a special electronic surveillance fit after ''Orion'' had been fitted with this during construction.<ref name=\"Owen32.3\"/><ref name=AFRmag/>\n\n==Operational history==\nAfter a delivery voyage via ports in Denmark, [[Florida]], and Mexico, ''Otama'' arrived at {{HMAS|Platypus|naval base|6}} in [[Sydney]] on 15 December 1979.<ref>''H.M.A.S. OTAMA COMES HOME Manufacturing strengthens'', in ''The Canberra Times''</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Cold War]], ''Otama'' and ''Orion'' regularly deployed on surveillance and spying operations using their specialist intelligence-gathering equipment, earning them the nickname \"Mystery Boats\".<ref name=AFRmag/><ref name=RSLnsw>''Cat and Mouse'', Reveille \u2013 The Voice of New South Wales Serving and Ex-Service Men and Women</ref><ref name=WkAust>Barker, ''Cold War exploits of Australia's secret submarines''</ref><ref name=Owens103.5>Owens, in ''Centenary of Australian Submarines'', pp. 103-5</ref> These activities starting in 1978 were part of the broader Western nations' intelligence-gathering apparatus, and included surveillance off the coasts of Vietnam, China, India and Indonesia. Obtaining intelligence on [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] and Chinese made vessels in operations in the Indian Ocean and South China Sea.<ref name=AFRmag/><ref name=RSLnsw/><ref name=WkAust/> Observation off the Soviet base at [[Vladivostok]].<ref name=Owens103.5/> These activities continued until 1992 after an incident with ''Orion'', and most of ''Otama''{{'}}s activities and deployments during this period remain classified.<ref name=Owens103.5/><ref name=AFRmag/><ref name=RSLnsw/><ref name=WkAust/>\n\nIn April 1980, ''Otama'' and the [[destroyer]] {{HMAS|Hobart|D 39|2}} were sent to [[Fiji]] as part of Australia's response to [[1979\u201380 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Wally|Tropical Cyclone Wally]].<ref>''CYCLONE DAMAGE Fiji's PM appeals to nation for help'', in ''The Canberra Times''</ref> On 8 September 1980, ''Otama'' joined five other RAN vessels to form the Australia Squadron.<ref name=Lind297>Lind, ''The Royal Australian Navy'', p. 297</ref> The Squadron, which included HMA Ships {{HMAS|Melbourne|R21|2}}, {{HMAS|Perth|D 38|2}}, {{HMAS|Derwent|DE 49|2}}, {{HMAS|Stalwart|D 215|2}}, and {{HMAS|Supply||2}} spent two months in the Indian Ocean as part of a flag-showing cruise; the largest RAN deployment since World War II.<ref name=SealBlake83/><ref name=Lind297/>\n\nIn July 1983, ''Otama'' was docked for modernisation.<ref name=Gillett76>Gillett, ''Australian and New Zealand Warships since 1946'', p. 76</ref> The Submarine Weapon Update Program refit lasted until 1985.<ref name=Gillett76/>\n\n[[File:Oberon class submarines memorial, Rockingham, September 2019 01.jpg|thumb|right|Commemorative plaque at [[Rockingham Naval Memorial Park]] for the three sailors killed on board of Australian ''Oberon''s]]\nOn 3 August 1987, two sailors were killed aboard ''Otama''. At 09:00, the submarine left HMAS ''Platypus'' to test a new towed [[hydrophone]] array.<ref name=Waller6>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', p. 6</ref> Extreme weather forced the cancellation of the test, and two sailors were sent into the [[Sail (submarine)|fin]] at around 10:20 to retrieve and stow the array.<ref name=Waller6/> At 10:35, the submarine was prepared for diving, and she submerged four minutes later, with the two men still in the fin.<ref name=Waller6/> The submariners, on noticing their vessel diving underneath them, climbed up the fin to the [[Bridge (nautical)|bridge]] and opened the [[voicepipe]] in an unsuccessful attempt to contact the control room before being washed overboard.<ref name=Waller7/> Their absence was not noticed until around 11:00, despite post-dive checks and a rotation of duty stations in the interim, and was not confirmed for at least another half-hour.<ref name=Waller6/> A search for the submariners was conducted, and one of the bodies was spotted, but could not be recovered.<ref name=Waller7>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', p. 7</ref> Estimated survival time in the prevailing conditions was only five minutes, and the submariners were not required to wear [[lifejacket|lifebelts]].<ref name=Waller7/> A naval board of inquiry recommended that action be taken against two officers, although the Navy Office did not take action, as there were multiple factors leading into the incident, and [[Courts martial|court martialing]] the two officers could find one or both held solely responsible for the deaths.<ref name=Waller3.4>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', pp. 3\u20134</ref> In addition to the rejection of the board's findings, several officers involved in the incident (including the two singled out by the inquiry), were promoted.<ref name=Waller10>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', p. 10</ref> A [[coronial inquiry]] followed (one of the first heard by the new office of the [[State Coroner of New South Wales]]), to which there was some opposition by the RAN, including advising personnel not to cooperate with the task force gathering evidence for the inquiry, and attempting to fend off a request by the coroner for a trip on the submarine replicating the events of the day.<ref name=Waller3.4/> Following two separate weeks of hearings in October and November 1988, the state coroner concluded that the incident was the sum of multiple moderate-to-minor breaches of operating procedure and careless negligence (including that notices indicating personnel were outside the submarine were not posted, and key personnel were not informed) aboard a submarine operating in non-standard conditions (such as the testing of new equipment, along with observers and trainees aboard, and a high rotation of personnel between stations in a short period of time).<ref>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', pp. 5-10</ref> The coroner singled out ''Otama''{{'}}s commanding officer for allowing so many rules and procedures to be ignored under his command, but did not find sufficient cause to recommend charges against any individual.<ref>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', pp. 8-9</ref> Several changes were made to casing operational procedures at sea, including making lifebelts compulsory and requiring the senior petty officer on duty to sign out and sign back in personnel working outside.<ref>Waller, ''Suddenly Dead'', pp. 7, 10</ref> The fatalities aboard ''Otama'' were two of the only three deaths aboard Australian ''Oberon''s.<ref>Owen, in ''Centenary of Australian Submarines'', p. 105</ref>\n\nFrom 1996, ''Otama'' was given approval to conduct coastal surveillance operations using its specialist intelligence-gathering equipment on Indonesia in particular to obtain information on East Timor.<ref name=WkAust/>\n\nAt the end of March 1999, ''Otama'' was reassigned to {{HMAS|Stirling||6}} in Western Australia, where the {{sclass-|Collins|submarine|2}}s were operating.<ref name=Owens103.4>Owens, in ''Centenary of Australian Submarines'', pp. 103-4</ref><ref name=DTbehind>''Subs leave harbour behind'', The Daily Telegraph, p. 4</ref> Within days of leaving Sydney, sister boat {{HMAS|Onslow||2}} was [[paid off]], leaving ''Otama'' the only one of her class in service, and the submarine base at HMAS ''Platypus'' was cleared for closure.<ref name=Owens103.4/><ref name=DTbehind/>\n\n==Decommissioning and fate==\n''Otama'' paid off on 15 December 2000: problems with the introduction of the ''Collins''-class submarines kept ''Otama'' and sister boat HMAS ''Onslow'' in service for several years beyond their planned decommissioning date.<ref>Jones, in Stevens, ''The Royal Australian Navy'', pp. 276\u20137</ref><ref name=\"YW298.9\"/> In the year leading up to her paying off, the pending decommissioning combined with the findings of the [[McIntosh-Prescott Report]] to cause the \"Fast Track\" program, A$1&nbsp;billion of modifications to make {{HMAS|Dechaineux|SSG 76|2}} and {{HMAS|Sheean|SSG 77|2}} fit for service by the end of the year.<ref name=YW298.9>Yule & Woolner, ''The Collins Class Submarine Story'', pp. 288\u20139</ref> ''Otama'' was the last Australian ''Oberon'' to leave service.<ref>Owen, in ''Centenary of Australian Submarines'', p. 93</ref>\n\nThe submarine was sold in 2001 to the Western Port Oberon Association, a community group intending to preserve her as a [[museum vessel]] and building the [[Victorian Maritime Centre]] in [[Hastings, Victoria]].<ref name=StewartASIO>Stewart, ''ASIO eyes mystery group after attempt to buy sub''</ref><ref name=CogdonEbay>Cogdon, ''Submarine for sale on internet auction website eBay''</ref> The association beat 32 other tenders for the disposal of ''Otama'', and received a $500,000 \"Centenary of Federation\" grant from the federal government to fund the purchase and relocation.<ref name=DeptDefPR>Nelson, ''Australian Submarine History Lands at Hastings with $500 000 Centenary of Federation Grant'' (press release)</ref><ref name=Silkstone>Silkstone, ''Sub group fights battle of Hastings''</ref> The grant included the $50,000 purchase price of the submarine, plus $300,000 to tow ''Otama'' from Fremantle to [[Western Port Bay]], with the balance to be used in bringing the boat ashore once a suitable venue was built.<ref name=DeptDefPR/><ref name=Silkstone/><ref name=Hast/> ''Otama'' arrived in [[Western Port Bay]] in 2002, where she was moored while waiting for the approval and development of the museum.<ref name=\"CogdonEbay\"/>\n\nBy late 2008, plans for three separate locations for the [[Victorian Maritime Centre]] \u2013 Hastings, [[Crib Point, Victoria|Crib Point]], and [[Stony Point, Victoria|Stony Point]] \u2013 had all been rejected by the [[Department of Sustainability and Environment]].<ref name=StewartASIO/><ref name=CogdonEbay/><ref name=Steward19122008/> As the Western Port Oberon Association could no longer afford to maintain the submarine while waiting for a favourable decision, ''Otama'' was listed on [[eBay]] for sale in November 2008.<ref name=CogdonEbay/><ref name=SealBlake84>Seal & Blake, ''Century of Silent Service'', p. 84</ref><ref name=CliftonEvans>Clifton-Evans, ''Is eBay the answer?''</ref><ref>College & Warlow, ''Ships of the Royal Navy'', p. 291</ref> Although no bids were placed by the time the online auction closed in late December, the association received several expressions of interest: including from the St Kilda Marina, [[City of Frankston|Frankston City Council]], and one purporting to be a tourism operator but believed by the Western Port Oberon Association to be wanting to restore the [[Narco-submarine|submarine for drug smuggling]] (which was referred to the [[Australian Federal Police]] and the [[Australian Security Intelligence Organisation]]).<ref name=StewartASIO/><ref name=Steward19122008>Stewart, ''Submarine for sale as group's dream sinks in a sea of red tape''</ref><ref>''Submarine fails to sell on Ebay'', in ''The Shipping Times''</ref> No sale was made, and the submarine remained in the possession of the association.\n\nIn early 2010, ''Otama''{{'}}s interior was used to represent a Russian submarine for the short film ''[[Deeper Than Yesterday]]''.<ref name=Bodey/> The 20-minute film won awards at the [[2010 Australian Film Institute Awards]], the 2010 [[Leeds International Film Festival]], and the [[2011 Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=Bodey>Bodey, ''Red carpet unrolls, but Cannes gives local filmmakers short shrift''</ref><ref name=\"tourtellotte\">Tourtellotte, ''Sundance's unheralded short film and grant winners''</ref>\n\nIn-principle approval to build the Victorian Maritime Centre was given by Victorian environmental minister [[Ryan Smith (Australian politician)|Ryan Smith]] in March 2013.<ref name=Hast>Hast, ''Sub ashore in 18 months''</ref> The association submitted plans in June for a {{convert|2.5|ha|adj=on}} site on the seawall of the Western Port Marina at Hastings, to be built on reclaimed land.<ref name=Hast/> The proposed site is on the outer edge of the existing seawall, with ''Otama'' enclosed in a semi-recessed concrete pit designed to support the main internal deck at ground level, located between the seawall and the planned site of the maritime centre.<ref name=Hast/> As of February 2015, design work has been completed, but the association was awaiting the approval of a planning permit.<ref>Taylor, ''Wyuna heads to Docklands''</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 it was announced that there new mooring cables worth $50,000 were needed if the vessel was to withstand winter storms.<ref>[http://mpnews.com.au/2016/01/12/marine-history-all-at-sea/ Marine history all at sea January 12, 2016] ''Mornington Peninsula News'' Retrieved September 20, 2016</ref> By May 2016 difficulties in raising the funds led to the Western Port Oberon Association looking into selling the submarine for scrap if necessary.<ref>Platt, Keith [http://mpnews.com.au/2016/05/03/distress-signals-from-subs-owners/ Distress signals from sub\u2019s owners May 3, 2016] ''Mornington Peninsula News'' Retrieved September 20, 2016</ref> Pledges of more than $10,000 were received by the end of May.<ref>Platt, Keith [http://mpnews.com.au/2016/05/31/pledges-flow-in-wake-of-subs-moorings-mayday/ \u2018Pledges\u2019 flow in wake of sub\u2019s moorings mayday May 31, 2016] ''Mornington Peninsula News'' Retrieved September 20, 2016</ref> The following month the moorings were repaired by [[Patrick Corporation|Patrick Ports Hastings]] after being contracted by [[Parks Victoria]].<ref>Platt, Keith [http://mpnews.com.au/2016/06/21/sub-safe-as-moorings-take-hold/ Sub safe as moorings take hold June 21, 2016] Retrieved September 20, 2016</ref>\n\n==Citations==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n'''Books'''\n*{{cite book |last=Bastock |first=John |title=Australia's Ships of War |year=1975 |publisher=Angus and Robertson |location=Cremorne, NSW |isbn=0-207-12927-4 |oclc=2525523}}\n*{{cite book |last=Chant |first=Christopher |title=A Compedium of Armaments and Military Hardware |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k9cNAAAAQAAJ&dq=&as_brr=3&source=gbs_summary_s&cad=0\n|accessdate=30 July 2008 |year=1987 |publisher=Routledge |location= |language= |isbn=0-7102-0720-4 |oclc= |doi= }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Colledge |first1=J.J. |last2=Warlow |first2=Ben |title=Ships of the Royal Navy |publisher=Casemate Publishers |location=Newbury |date=2010 |edition=Revised |isbn=9781612000275|oclc=784981062 |url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WfODMIsqtTQC |accessdate=24 April 2015}}\n*{{cite book |last=Gillett |first=Ross |title=Australian and New Zealand Warships since 1946 |year=1988 |publisher=Child & Associates |location=Brookvale, NSW |isbn=0867772190 |oclc=23470364}}\n*{{cite book |last=Lind |first=Lew |title=The Royal Australian Navy: Historic Naval Events Year by Year |edition=2nd |year=1986 |publisher=Reed Books |location=Frenchs Forest, NSW |isbn=0-7301-0071-5 |oclc=16922225}}\n*{{cite book |last=Owen |first=Bill |title=Australian Maritime Issues 2010 |editor=Mitchell, Rhett |publisher=Sea Power Centre \u2013 Australia |year=2011 |series=Papers in Australian Maritime Affairs |volume=35 |pages=25\u201333 |chapter=Submarines in Australia, 1949\u20131979 |url=http://www.navy.gov.au/w/images/PIAMA35.pdf |accessdate=6 March 2012 |isbn=978-0-642-29757-0 |issn=1327-5658 |oclc= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227141238/http://www.navy.gov.au/w/images/PIAMA35.pdf |archive-date=27 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book|last1=Seal |first1=Graham |last2=Blake |first2=Lloyd |title=Century of Silent Service